<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Media Kit</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Media Kit</H1>

<P>
A media kit need not be in glossy full color.  It usually consists
of a folder with pockets, which contain information on the product
or service.  The information contained in the press kit usually
includes several components:  
<UL>
<LI>A business card which is glued on the pocket or set in die
cuts.
<LI>A background sheet on the history of the area, attraction,
business and owner.  The philosophy of the company or what makes
it unusual is generally included with hours of operation, the
products sold or services offered, etc.  
<LI>Press clippings of coverage (copies) may also be included
to add credibility (only 2 or 3 of the best stories are needed).
 
<LI>A brochure which includes a diagram of the product and directions
to the company.  Photos really do say a thousand words, so try
to include a color copy or, if budget permits, a color slide.
 Your media kit must paint a picture of your story.   
<LI>Some PR professionals like to include &quot;canned&quot;,
pre-written features, but our advice is that pre-written material
should rarely be used.
<LI>If a promotional item is available (a sticker, a luggage tag,
a button), include it if your budget allows.  Remember to factor
in postage cost.  Sometimes small gift items are included, such
as flower seeds sent by a seed distributor.  
<LI>Video releases are also becoming more common in reaching the
media.  As the world becomes more visually oriented, video footage
is often an easier way to communicate a message to media.  Obviously
there is a cost involved and not all journalists have access to
a VCR.  If a video release is used, the need for the written media
release still remains vitally important as an introduction and
accompaniment.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Again, the envelope and folder are important, because you must
generate enough interest for the journalist to take the time,
open the envelope, look through the folder and glance at the headline
on the press release in the right-hand pocket.  So, making an
effort to decorate the folder and/or envelope with a photo or
pasted company logo/design is usually worth the time and expense.
 Make the overall presentation intriguing-but with easy-to-find
information.  You may want to stairstep the information (with
background sheets of different heights, from the first sheet peeking
out just above the pocket and building incrementally to the last
page at 11 inches in height).
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: MEDIAKIT.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

