<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Media Release</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Media Release</H1>

<P>
The key to a good media release is to give accurate, pertinent
facts that answer who, what, when, where and why.  Journalists
are sometimes wary when they see superlatives and adjectives (best,
biggest, most, cheapest, etc.) in the copy.  Make sure the information
is accurate.  If you can't verify a fact, don't include it.  If
you have support documentation (a photo, research statistics,
a registration form), attach it to the release.  A release is
not an opportunity to write that novel you've always dreamed about.
 Keep it concise, make sure the headline will draw attention,
and present important information.
<P>
Include contact information (name and phone number are a must),
keep the copy in the active voice, have a friend proofread it
and try to include a quote from someone who can substantiate and
give credibility to your message.  If your event is open to the
media, list the location and event time.  Is the news time-related?
 Then mention the release date, and be certain to send the information
early enough for each media market:  magazines, three months to
two years; newspapers, three days to six weeks depending on the
section; television, one day to two months; radio, one day to
one month.  Mention additional documentation photos, interviews,
etc. which are available.  Make the ONE page release easy to read-double-
or triple- spaced on white or a light-colored paper.  Avoid acronyms
and industry jargon.  BE CREATIVE!  
<P>
Make your release stand apart from the other 50 white envelopes
with releases in them that hit a journalist's basket each day
by including colorful designs on the envelope, or use an unusual
size of envelope.  What would make you open an obvious solicitation
mailing?  One Department of Energy PR professional super-glued
plastic fish (her cost was $.25 per release) to her release on
watershed protection. Make certain you are mailing or faxing the
release to the appropriate person and that you are spelling the
journalist's name correctly.
<P>
At the time of this printing, most media releases are still sent
by mail.  However, more and more journalists are going on-line,
and releases may be sent by e-mail.  From anecdotal information
collected, approximately 30 percent of Oregon media are on-line,
60 percent of the top national publications (magazine and newspapers)
are on-line and nationally, approximately 30 percent of journalists
get their information on-line. 
<P>
 
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: RELEASE.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

