<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Create your Media Relations Plan</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>


<H1>Create your Media Relations Plan</H1>

<H2>Step 1:  Determine your media relations goal(s).</H2>

<P>
Example:  To reach more families in the San Francisco market by
placing stories in Bay Area newspapers and city/community magazines
such as San Francisco Focus, the Lifestyle section of the San
Francisco Chronicle, etc.
<H2>Step 2:  Determine who you are and what your story is.</H2>

<P>
Determine what is newsworthy about your story.  What makes you
different?  Keep in mind that the story should be of interest
to the particular audience you are trying to reach, and be critically
honest.  Does it pass the &quot;Who cares?&quot; test?  Are you
the only person who cares about the product or service, or would
a specific audience really be interested?  Perhaps your story
is about a new wine being served, a new chef, a children's attraction,
a new historical tour, a recycling program or a new product that
is being launched.  
<H2>Step 3:  Determine who your customers are and, subsequently,
who your media targets are.</H2>

<P>
Media relations is the means of conveying messages to the public
through the media.  Developing a list of media outlets (newspapers,
radio stations, magazines or television stations) and determining
who might be interested in your story is important.  Watch for
bylines, or note a journalist's name in publications you read.
 There are many reference books that include information on media
outlets, the size of their readership, viewership or listenership,
and contact information.  These references may be found in your
library.  They include:  Bacon's Publicity Checker, Editor &amp;
Publisher International Yearbook, BPI Media Services, Writer's
Market, Gebbie Press, and Broadcasting &amp; Cable Marketplace.
 
<P>
Familiarity with the media outlets and their reporters will help
you determine who to contact with your story idea (food editor,
assignment editor, living section editor, morning deejay).  Seek
out connections you may have with local media through local civic
organizations or friends.  Once you have established a connection
with a journalist, nurture the relationship through press kit/news
release mailings when appropriate.  Target the appropriate media
for each story.  Remember to concentrate on local coverage, and
then expand to larger markets.  Larger media markets are more
difficult to reach and generate a story within, unless particularly
appropriate to your product or service.  If you offer tours of
Oregon for European customers, for example, then target European
publications.  
<P>
<h2><U>Potential Consumer Markets:</U></h2>
<ul><LI>
Art Collectors
<LI>
Children/Families
<LI>
Food and Wine Connoisseurs
<LI>
History Buffs
<LI>
Meeting Planners
<LI>
Outdoor Enthusiasts
<LI>
Seniors
<LI>
Tour Operators
<LI>
Travel Agents
</ul>
<h2><U>Potential Media Markets:</U></h2>

<h3><I><B>Magazines:</B></I></h3>
<ul><LI>
Business
<LI>
Camping/RV
<LI>
Family
<LI>
Food
<LI>
Health
<LI>
Meeting Trade
<LI>
Regional Lifestyle
<LI>
Sports/Outdoor Recreation
<LI>
Travel
<LI>
Travel Trade
<LI>
Women
</ul>
<h3><I><B>Newspaper:</B></I></h3>
<ul><LI>
Arts and Entertainment
<LI>
Business
<LI>
Food
<LI>
Regional
<LI>
Sports
<LI>
Travel
</ul>
<h3><I><B>Radio: </B></I></h3>
<ul><LI>
A.M. Deejay hosted
<LI>
Current Affairs
<LI>
News
<LI>
P.M. Romance focused
<LI>
Sports
<LI>
Syndicated Shows
</ul>
<h3><I><B>TV: </B></I></h3>
<ul><LI>
Calendar of Events
<LI>
Documentaries
<LI>
Magazine Format
<LI>
News
<LI>
Special Features
<LI>
Travel
</ul>
<H2>Step 4:  What is your message?</H2>

<BR>
You have determined who you are and what you are &quot;selling&quot;,
but how are you differentiating yourself from the rest of the
pack (i.e., your competition)?  Because we are so close to our
product/service, it is difficult to see ourselves and our &quot;goods&quot;
as everyone else does.  Take advantage of networks you are part
of in order to bounce ideas off of colleagues.  For the cost of
a lunch you may develop some excellent ideas on how to stand apart
from the competition.  For example, one national video store conducted
an event for families to come in and videotape their children.
 It was a fun thing for families to do (this was at the advent
of video cameras, when they were a novelty), and the video the
family created  served as a record of the child's height, build
and visage for security purposes.  Thus, the promotion was a public
service for store patrons.  
<H2>Step 5:  How will you convey your message to the media?</H2>

<BR>
The primary ways of communicating your story to the media include:
<ul><li>
Face-to-face visits
<li>
Media release
<li>
Personal letter
<li>
Press conferences
<li>
Press kit
<li>
Slides and photos (usually part of the press kit)
<li>
Telephone calls
<li>
Word of mouth/networking/personal experience
</ul><BR>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (December 1995)
<BR>
File name: MEDIA.DOC
<BR>
