<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Media Relations Do's and Don'ts</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Media Relations Do's and Don'ts</H1>

<H2>Do your homework.</H2>

<P>
Find out what topics a targeted journalist covers.  What section
does she write for?  What is a recent story she has written/produced
that you can refer to?  What are her personal interests?  Is she
familiar with your service/product?  Is she new to the media outlet
or to the region of the country?  What are her deadlines and lead-times?
 Ask her what she is looking for in a story.  Does a photo help?
 Is she on-line?  Does she read on-line releases, or does she
prefer mail or fax?
<H2>Do nurture personal relationships with journalists.  </H2>

<P>
Contacting one journalist you know personally is likely to turn
up more coverage than sending out 1,000 releases to media outlets
that aren't in your target market and/or for which you don't have
a specific name.  Don't send a press release to a newspaper without
a contact name; it's worth a phone call to get a properly spelled
name.
<H2>Do stop at news stands and pick up publications with which
you are not familiar, but which might be likely candidates for
a story.</H2>

<P>
Take the name of the appropriate editor and the address for the
publication with you.  Reading an airline in-flight magazine is
an excellent time to find out who is writing what.  If a freelancer
is contributing the story, look for a mini-bio at the front of
the publication or immediately following the last sentence of
the story.
<H2>Don't forget your own backyard.</H2>

<P>
Yes, a story on the evening network news would be wonderful coverage
to receive, but don't put all of your efforts into striving for
something that's nearly impossible.  Target your local newspaper,
magazines and television stations, and when you have time, approach
the nationally televised shows.  Often a national network will
learn about a story after it has been run by a network affiliate.
<H2>Do be persistent, but don't be a pest.  </H2>

<P>
Stay in touch with your media contacts, but don't inundate them
with frivolous stories that aren't newsworthy (remember the &quot;Who
cares?&quot; test) or that don't pertain to their readers, listeners
or viewers.
<H2>Do give contact information on all materials you send out,
including a name, phone number and address.</H2>

<P>
If you will be away from the office attending an event for which
you sent out a release, make sure it includes contact information,
so the media can reach you even during non-office hours.
<H2>Do take a  journalist's response of &quot;I don't think I
can use this story, but call me if something else interesting
turns up&quot; as positive.</H2>

<P>
Accept a &quot;no&quot; this time, and thank her for her willingness
to listen.
<H2>Do be honest!</H2>

<P>
Be an expert on the story you're pitching, but tell her  when
you don't have an answer . . . and get back to her.
<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: DO'S.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

