<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Media: Phone and Face-to-Face Media Calls</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Phone and Face-to-Face Media Calls</H1>

<P>
Like you, journalists are very busy people. However, they have
the additional burden of an ever looming deadline hanging over
their heads.  Be sensitive to their schedules.  (Don't call a
television newsroom at 4 p.m. as they're preparing for the 5 p.m.
news and ask if it is a good time for a brief chat.)  Even if
you think they know who you are, remind them, and succinctly tell
them the reason for your call.  
<P>
Try to engage the journalist quickly with your story, or convince
him to give you ten minutes for a face-to-face meeting.  It is
important to be genuine, both on the phone and in person, and
not be overly consumed with the importance of your story.  Obviously,
the story dictates the tone of the meeting (serious, fun, etc.),
but try not to dominate the conversation with a 15- minute speech.
 Be a good listener.  If you don't know the answer to a journalist's
question, tell him you'll do some research and follow up promptly.
 
<P>
If you run into a dead end with a journalist, ask if there is
another journalist at that media outlet for whom the story might
be appropriate.  You cannot dictate anything to a journalist:
 whether to write the story, how to write the story, or when to
write the story.  Again, keep in mind that a long-term, positive
relationship with a journalist is more important than placing
an individual story.
<P>
Keep your telephone call or face-to-face meeting brief, and follow
up with requested information.  If you take more time than the
journalist can afford, he won't be as willing to talk/meet with
you next time.
<P>
A follow-up thank you note for meeting in person or for a story
is a professional gesture that will further nurture the long-term
relationship.
<P>
 Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (December 1995)
<P>
File name: PHONE.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
