<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Tools: Activities for Generating Awareness</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>
<H1>Activities for Generating Awareness</H1>

<H2>1. Hold a contest.</H2>

<P>
Trade out time on the air or in print in exchange for tickets
to your event, attraction, etc. Have a photo contest, a drawing
for a trip, or a recipe contest featuring locally grown products.
<H2>2. Hold a press conference.</H2>

<P>
Make certain it is visual.  Does the story work better for print
(longer, in depth coverage of stories of a static nature) or television
(a newborn animal at a local zoo).
<H2>3. Send out a press release/video release.</H2>

<P>
Make sure you're getting the information to the right person.
<H2>4. Conduct radio interviews.</H2>

<P>
Deliver breakfast to deejays during the early-morning rush hour.
 Follow up a press release, and set up an interview with your
business' spokesperson and local media.
<H2>5. Host a sampling event.</H2>

<P>
A sampling of a food product or a casting demonstration for a
new fly rod.
<H2>6. Media Tour</H2>

<P>
Have your business' spokesperson visit media in targeted markets.
<H2>7. School Promotions</H2>

<P>
Offer curriculum, clean-up (SOLV) programs, coloring contests
or field trips.
<H2>8. Stage an event.</H2>

<P>
Pinpoint why you wish to stage the event, and make certain your
message and your event sponsor's message are communicated.
<H2>9. Issue a proclamation.</H2>

<P>
Typically issued from a government agency (Mayor's Office, Governor's
Office) it usually generates local coverage if truly newsworthy,
unusual or includes good back-up information on why the proclamation
has been issued.
<H2>10. Media Kit Mailing</H2>

<H2>11. Public Service Announcement (PSA)</H2>

<P>
Produced in both audio and video format, it is wise to approach
the radio and television stations in advance to make certain that
the efforts and money put towards producing a psa actually pays
off by eliciting airtime.
<H2>12. Speakers Bureau</H2>

<P>
Have a team of ambassadors that can speak about your issue or
business.  Make service organizations, event coordinators and
business organizations aware that the speakers are available.
 Send out a mailing of who the speakers are, what visuals are
available, etc.
<H2>13. Business Cards</H2>

<P>
Create mini-stat sheets that can printed on the backs of business
cards.  If a group of international visitors is coming to town,
print key welcoming phrases on a business card, so it serves as
a cheat sheet.  Words such as welcome, good morning, thank you
and good-bye are helpful, with phonetic pronunciations.  These
could be made available to employees working the front lines,
welcome center volunteers, etc.
<H2>14. Volunteer Hand-outs</H2>

<P>
Send volunteers out during rush hour to pass out cookies to greet
visitors, or clowns to hand out buttons/balloons to kids.
<H2>15. Writing Contest</H2>

<P>
Host a writing contest and tie in a corporate sponsor who prefers
to sponsor educational activities.  Have the winning essays published.
<H2>16. Volunteer Information</H2>

<P>
Have volunteers at key information sources (gas stations for visitors)
give excellent advice and distribute maps and something indigenous
to the area.
<H2>17. Information Centers</H2>

<P>
Add new information at key information points (rest stops for
visitors) with new, up-to-date information, as well as information
concerning how important their visit is to the area.
<H2>18. Legislative Buy-In</H2>

<P>
Have a local organization host a legislator or key influencer
monthly, with updates on economic development activities and tourism
programs.
<H2>19. Community Quiz</H2>

<P>
Issue a quiz through a local paper with questions on the visitor
industry and visitor attractions.  (How deep is Hells Canyon?)
 Introduce a product inventory (what your community has to offer
a visitor) through the quiz.
<H2>20. Surveys</H2>

<P>
Conduct research with visitors in town and release it to the media.
 Stop visitors in the downtown area and conduct &quot;on the street
live reports&quot; of visitors' experiences.
<H2>21. Banners</H2>

<P>
Drape banners with key messages in the downtown, high traffic
areas.
<H2>22. Product Co-ops</H2>

<P>
Put your message on a locally produced product label, or use the
product as a giveaway (microbrewed beer, wines, tea, chowder,
kites)
<H2>23. Newsletter</H2>

<P>
Create a regular newsletter (quarterly or monthly) with updates
on your business, region, etc., and mail it to a list of key influencers.
<H2>24. Direct Mail</H2>

<P>
Create a brochure or mailing that can be direct mailed to a list
of individuals that are targeted for your needs.  Mailing lists
can be purchased based on psycho-graphic information.  Partner
with a bank or utility company and have them include your mailer
in one of their monthly mailings.
<H2>25. Advertising</H2>

<P>
Advertise in business or regional publications on the importance
of the issue.
<H2>26. Conduct hospitality training or business leadership classes
in your area and invite the community to attend.</H2>

<H2>27. Volunteers</H2>

<P>
For volunteer activities, advertise or generate media coverage
of the importance of volunteers to your business and/or promote
an activity that includes volunteers.  How many hours have they
worked for the organization?  Is there a group affiliation of
the volunteers (PTA, AARP, etc.)?
<H2>28. Printing Projects</H2>

<P>
Restaurant  placemats, bumper stickers, pins or posters can be
printed and distributed with a diagram of how the industry affects
many non-traditional visitor businesses and jobs such as department
stores, galleries, wineries, bakeries, utility companies, graphic
designers, architects, etc.
<H2>29. Scavenger Hunts</H2>

<P>
Have locals participate in a treasure hunt that takes them to
the attractions of the area.
<H2>30. Payroll</H2>

<P>
Pay visitor industry employees in two dollar bills (or have visitor
industry employees purchase all groceries and restaurant bills
with two dollar bills), so the community can see how quickly the
money is circulated throughout the community. Have travel suppliers
give visitors two dollar bills as change, to demonstrate how quickly
the money works through the community.
<H2>31. Billboards</H2>

<P>
Buy billboards that convey the importance of the industry message.
<H2>32. FAM Tour</H2>

<P>
Conduct a familiarization tour of local attractions with regional
dignitaries as guests.
<H2>33. Ambassador Program</H2>

<P>
Have key business leaders serve as local ambassadors,  They officially
greet visiting dignitaries and serve as an area representative
when traveling.  Suitcases, luggage tags and garment bags could
all have the awareness campaigns key phrase printed on them.
<H2>34. Industry Forum</H2>

<P>
Have business leaders convene with a local dignitary for a forum
to discuss the state of the industry and future plans.
<H2>35. School Programs</H2>

<P>
Select high school students to work at visitor attractions for
credit, to introduce them to the visitor industry.  Include students
in business meetings and industry forums when possible.
<H2>36. Employee Appreciation </H2>

<P>
Organize a &quot;vote for your favorite visitor industry employee&quot;
contest, with the winner(s) being awarded a trip throughout the
region.  This could include restaurant, lodging, attraction, airline,
tour operator, etc.
<H2>37. State Police</H2>

<P>
Have state troopers pull visitors to the side of the road and
share a travel guide with free coupons to visitor attractions.
 Make the &quot;arrested&quot; visitors VIP's for the day.
<P>
Source: Sunstone Marketing Group (October 1995)
<P>
File name: IDEAS.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
</BODY>

