<TITLE>VIA Kit Online: Tools: Oregon Tourism on the Internet</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<a href="../index.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/tico.gif" border=0 alt="Oregon Welcomes You!"></a>

<a href="../via.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/visitor.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>

<a href="viakit.htm"><img align=bottom src="../gifs/kit.gif" border=0 alt="Visitor Industry Awareness Campaign"></a>
<p>
<a href="overview.htm">Overview</a> - 
<a href="resear.htm">Research</a> - 
<a href="resource.htm">Resources</a> - 
<a href="govt.htm">Government</a> - 
<a href="medi.htm">Media Relations</a> - 
<a href="tools.htm">Tools And Ideas</a>

<br><HR>

<H1>Oregon Tourism on the Internet</H1>

<H2>What is Oregon Welcomes You!?</H2>

<P>
<I>Oregon Welcomes You!</I> is an information source on the World
Wide Web sponsored by the Travel Industry Council of Oregon.
<P>
Some of its features include:
<UL>
<LI>Listings of every organization that belongs to a TICO member
organization.
<LI>&quot;On-line&quot; discussion groups on subjects related
to the tourism industry in Oregon.
<LI>&quot;Web pages&quot; for Oregon tourism organizations who
wish to advertise their product or service on the Internet.
<LI>A vast collection of World Wide Web resources related to Oregon
tourism.
<LI>The complete VIA kit on-line for you to view and download.
</UL>

<H2>What can Oregon Welcomes You! do for me?</H2>

<UL>
<LI>You can promote your organization on the Internet at discounted
rates.
<LI>You can discuss &quot;on-line&quot; subjects that matter to
tourism industry professionals.
<LI>You can locate fellow tourism professionals on the Internet
and send them electronic mail.
</UL>

<H2>What do I need to get started?</H2>

<H3>1. A computer system equipped with a modem.  </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Almost all IBM-compatible, Macintosh, and Mainframe computers
are capable of hooking up to the Internet.  
<LI>Modems that support speeds of 14,400 bps (bits per second)
or more.
</UL>

<P>

<H3>2. A company that provides a hook-up to the Internet, known
as a &quot;local access provider.&quot; </H3>

<UL>
<LI>See &quot;Local Access Providers in Oregon&quot; on the back
of this sheet for a listing of access providers in your area.
</UL>

<P>

<H3>3. Computer software to access the Internet.  </H3>

<UL>
<LI>This is normally provided by your local access provider, and
includes programs for making a connection to your local access
provider, sending and receiving electronic mail (e-mail), and
viewing World Wide Web documents.
</UL>

<P>
Source: Travel Industry Council of Oregon (October 1995)
<P>
File name: INTERNET.DOC
<P>
Download this file at: <A HREF="ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit">ftp://ftp.tico.org/viakit</A>
