<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mannatech Tomorrow Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="Tom.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/1aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Fin.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/2aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Ath.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/3aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Pro.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/4aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Act.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/5aBtn.jpg"></A><BR><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/Hma.jpg"></A><BR><BR><A HREF="Tom.html">Tomorrow  |  </A><A HREF="Fin.html">Financial  |  </A><A HREF="Ath.html">Athletics  |  </A><A HREF="Pro.html">Products  |  </A><A HREF="Act.html">Action  |  </A><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/">Home</A><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><H1>Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> Complex<BR>Mannatech's New Proprietary Product</H1><BR><IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 SRC="/pics/ManAmb.jpg"></CENTER>On August 9, 1996, Mannatech Inc. took a giant step. The company moved to secure a proprietary position in the rapidly changing, constantly expanding health care industry with the filing of a new set of composition and use patent claims that belong exclusively to Mannatech. In an industry in which prevention and natural alternatives have become the new national focus, no technology offers more promise than the discovery and use of certain carbohydrates recently recognized as vital in the function and structure of cellular synthesis.An increasing number of scientists believe that certain carbohydrates represent the next frontier in the search for non-toxic treatments of various degenerative conditions. Even though science has only scratched the surface in understanding the full potential of these carbohydrates, the research reported in the last decade alone has generated a new level of hope and cautious optimism for some of the world's leading immunologists. <BR>Until recently, very little was known about carbohydrates other than their ability to provide energy. But recent discoveries of how certain carbohydrates support such critical functions as immune response and cellular communication has triggered enormous growth in the new science of glycobiology. One of the world's most renowned veterinary immunologists, Dr. Ian R. Tizard, wrote "There has long been a tradition in folk medicine that extracts of certain fungi and plants may be of assistance in the treatment of cancer. On investigation, many of these extracts have been found to possess potent immune-stimulating activity. In many cases, this activity is attributable to complex carbohydrates. These carbohydrates are usually large polymers of glucose (glucans and lentinans), mannose (mannans), xylose (hemicelluloses), fructose (levans) or mixtures of these sugars." (Tizard I.R., Carbohydrates, Immune Stimulating. Encyclopedia of Immunology. San Diego 1992.)<BR>The carbohydrates he refers to are long chain sugar molecules called polysaccharides, poly meaning many and saccharides meaning sugar. Even though they're all polysaccharides, not all polysaccharides are created equal. Dr. Tizard continues, "Although common polysaccharides such as starch (alpha-1,4-glucan), dextran (alpha-1,6-glucan) and inulin (fructan) do not have anti-tumor activity, there is abundant evidence that some mannans and glucans are very potent anti-cancer agents."<BR>Motivated by these incredible findings, the world's largest pharmaceutical companies are allocating hundreds of millions of research dollars to develop chemically synthesized carbohydrates. They hope that these synthetics will mimic the effect of their natural counterparts. Synthesizing these carbohydrates will hopefully provide their patentability. The July 1991 (Vol. 9) issue of BIO/TECHNOLOGY states, "New carbohydrate technology will provide novel products for treating diseases, including immune disorders, cancer, infectious diseases, and cardiovascular conditions. . . . By the year 2000, most biopharmaceutical companies will have demonstrated widespread involvement in carbohydrate product development. Several research and development collaborations-for instance, Monsanto with Oxford Glycosystems and Genetech and Eli Lilly with Glycomed-have already formed. . . But manufacturing, regulation, patents, and drug development uncertainties may mean that many companies will play the waiting game."<BR>Mannatech is at the forefront of this widespread trend in carbohydrate product development, with a couple of important differences. Instead of attempting to develop synthetic carbohydrates as drug companies are doing, Mannatech has developed naturally occurring, plant-derived, carbohydrate-based products. Rather than waiting until a person is sick to provide assistance, Mannatech's products are designed to use nutrients working through normal physiology to maintain optimal health through improved nutrition.<BR>A large body of the research conducted on naturally-occurring carbohydrates was provided by Dr. Bill McAnalley at Carrington Laboratories through his now world-renowned discovery and stabilization of the mannan-linked carbohydrate in the gel of the aloe vera plant.<BR>So significant was this discovery that Dr. McAnalley was able to obtain 66 worldwide patents for Carrington Laboratories on the composition and use of this unique aloe vera molecule. Over $50 million have been spent on the research and development of the pharmaceutical applications of this discovery. More than 150 peer-reviewed scientific papers have been presented to support these uses, making the aloe molecule the clear frontrunner in carbohydrate technology. <BR>Mannatech's first generation products utilized the patented aloe vera extract Manapol&#174; powder as its proprietary carbohydrate ingredient through an exclusive licensing agreement. As word of these products spread, exponential sales growth facilitated incremental increase in the research budget. When Dr. McAnalley's contract of employment ended with his previous employer, he was encouraged to accept a full-time position with Mannatech. He immediately began examining the body's use of other complex carbohydrates. This led to the discovery of the expanded role that certain polysaccharides play in the body's ability to communicate and revealed the potential benefit of  the nutritional supplementation of these unique polysaccharides in today's diets. This discovery and use is the basis for Dr. McAnalley's newly filed patent claims. <BR>Manapol&#174; powder provided the proprietary technology that helped establish Mannatech as a major player in this new health care environment. Dr. McAnalley's new composition, Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> complex, which includes the freeze-dried aloe vera extract as a key component, broadens the potential of our exclusive product line. We are now going beyond the potential of any single polysaccharide to build and maintain health. The true genius of this discovery and patent is that Dr. McAnalley has established the need for these eight essential natural carbohydrates from a nutritional basis, eliminating the need to develop a synthetic counterpart for pharmaceutical use. All society benefits from this insight, especially when health maintenance through nutritional supplements cost a fraction of medical expenses. <BR>The article "A Solid Scientific Foundation," by Dr. Bill McAnalley, discusses the scientific basis for these new patent claims and, while none of us can truly estimate the potential of this product in our continuing efforts to solve our health care crisis, its value to Mannatech's marketing efforts is clear. It simply puts us in a league of our own, in control of our own destiny, as Mannatech takes the nutraceutical industry into the next generation of nutritional supplements. For this, each of us owes a true sense of gratitude to the genius of Dr. Bill McAnalley and his staff.<BR><BR><BR><H3>Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> Complex Patent Inventors:</H3>Bill H. McAnalley<BR>H. Reginald McDaniel<BR>D. Eric Moore<BR>Eileen P. Vennum<BR>William C. Fioretti<BR><BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
