<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mannatech Tomorrow Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="Tom.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/1aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Fin.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/2aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Ath.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/3aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Pro.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/4aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Act.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/5aBtn.jpg"></A><BR><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/Hma.jpg"></A><BR><BR><A HREF="Tom.html">Tomorrow  |  </A><A HREF="Fin.html">Financial  |  </A><A HREF="Ath.html">Athletics  |  </A><A HREF="Pro.html">Products  |  </A><A HREF="Act.html">Action  |  </A><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/">Home</A><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><H1>A Solid Scientific Foundation</H1><I>by Bill McAnalley, Ph.D., Mannatech Director of Product Research & Development</I><BR><BR><IMG SRC="/pics/Golgi.jpg"><BR><I><H3>Glycoproteins are manufactured in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).</H3></CENTER>The DNA found in the nucleus of every cell contains all the information needed to produce any cellular component. When a cell needs glycoproteins, that part of the DNA is assembled into a message called messenger RNA. It is then transported to the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) - the assembly line of the cell - where enzymes are used as factory workers to assemble glycoproteins or other substances. (Stryer, 1995)</I><BR><BR><BR><BR>The Mannatech tradition of innovation and excellence is being further strengthened and enhanced with the introduction of an exciting new dietary supplement available to Associates within the next few months. Unique, the first of its kind, this product's design is based on current scientific knowledge about how the body communicates at the cellular level. <BR>Healthy bodies, comprised of many components working together in sophisticated harmony, must have accurate internal communication to function correctly. In its most basic form, this communication occurs at the cellular level. Molecular biologists refer to it as cell-cell communication. To maintain a healthy body, cells must "talk" to other cells. When the language of the cells is garbled so that the message is no longer clear, health problems occur. <BR>In an article called "Capitalizing on Carbohydrates" in the journal, BIO/TECHNOLOGY, John Hodgson writes, "Almost without exception, whenever two or more living cells interact in a specific way, cell surface carbohydrates will be involved. From the first meeting of sperm and egg, through embryo genesis, development and growth, carbohydrate molecules confer exquisite specificity upon cell-cell interactions."<BR>Any molecule where a sugar (saccharide, glyco) is bound covalently to a moiety (a portion of a functional group of a molecule) of another chemical classification is considered a glycoconjugate, i.e., sugar bound to a lipid forms a glycolipid or to a protein forms a glycoprotein. In other words, nature uses the carbohydrates on glycoconjugates as recognition molecules because they are the most specific form of biological information. These glyco-molecules are collectively known as glycoconjugates. Since more is known about glycoproteins than any other glycoconjugate, let's now look at their structure and function in relation to cell-cell communication.<BR>Scientists have learned that glycoproteins - molecules found on the surface of all cells - play a key role in all cellular communication. The name, glycoprotein, is derived from the molecules' composition: sugar (glyco) and protein. The carbohydrate (sugar) content of glycoprotein molecules is significant, ranging from 1% to over 85% by weight. Most of the proteins that serve multiple functions in the body are glycoproteins.<BR><BR><BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="/pics/Alpha.jpg"><BR><I>All letters in the English language are made from 4 basic forms. <BR>The body uses 8 monosaccharides to comprise the letters of communication in the body.</I><BR></CENTER><BR><BR>Scientific knowledge concerning the importance of glycoproteins in cell-cell communication is relatively new. Proteins, which are made up of various combinations of amino acids, were originally thought to be the primary communication molecules of the body. What we know as The Biotech Revolution began as an attempt to create new drugs based on proteins. However, the structural simplicity of the protein molecule limits the number of possible configurations it can make in combination with other molecules. The body performs many more functions than those that can be attributed to the molecular configurations possible with proteins. <BR><BR><BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="/pics/Asp.jpg"><BR><I><H3>A closeup of the inside of a cell and the assembly line of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER. (Stryer, 1995)</H3></CENTER>Just as words are made from letters of the alphabet, our DNA builds cellular "words" from its own form of "letters" called glycoproteins. Each glycoprotein is produced from certain combinations of these eight monosaccharide substrates (sugars): galactose, glucose, mannose, N-acetylneuraminic acid, fucose, N-acteylgalactosamine, N-acetyglucosamine, and xylose (shown here in different colors). This diagram shows the products line of a glycoprotein "letter". Each sugar combination is built and changed by enzymes (the numbers shown between the sugar formations) until the "letter" is complete. If any of these sugars is missing or in short supply, glycoprotein "letters" are not formed or are altered. This can result in non-existent or inappropriate cellular communication experienced as symptoms or disease.</I><BR><BR><BR><BR>Several decades ago a theoretical mathematician, in calculating the number of configurations possible with proteins, found that another "language," yet unknown, had to be responsible for performing most of the communication functions of the body. Today we know that this language is the "language of carbohydrates."<BR>In contrast to the simpler proteins, many more molecular configurations are possible with the more structurally complex carbohydrate molecule, which has two isomeric forms and six binding sites. For example, while only 24 oligopeptide configurations are possible with four peptides (proteins), more than 100,000 different oligosaccharide configurations are possible with four sugars (Stryer et al., Biochemistry, 1995; p 477). So carbohydrates on the surface of cells make many more cellular "words" possible.<BR>Many diseases have altered glycoproteins in common. For example, individuals with collagen diseases have genetically unique glycoproteins. These patients have widespread immunologic and inflammatory alterations of connective tissue.<BR>These illnesses share certain symptoms. Common among them are synovitis, pleuritis, myocarditis, endocarditis, pericarditis, peritonitis, vasculitis, myositis, skin rash, alterations of connective tissues, and nephritis. Laboratory tests may reveal Coombs-positive hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, immunoglobulin excesses or deficiencies, antinuclear antibodies (which include antibodies to many nuclear constituents, including DNA and extractable nuclear antigen), rheumatoid factors, cryoglobulins, false-positive serologic tests for syphilis, elevated muscle enzymes, and alterations in serum complement (Tierney et al., 1994; page 681).<BR>Examples of collagen (autoimmune) diseases exhibiting one or more of the above symptoms include rheumatoid arthritis, juvenile chronic arthritis, systemic lupus erythematosus (lupus), progressive systemic sclerosis (Scleroderma), polymyositis-dermatomyositis, overlap (or mixed) connective tissue disease, and Sjšgren's syndrome.<BR>Although these autoimmune disorders are regarded as acquired diseases, their causes have not been determined. Genetic factors, however, play a role, since one family often has sequential generations with the same disease. Rheumatoid arthritis is one example of this. Since it's known that these patients have genetically unique collagen glycoproteins, it's immediately obvious that glycoproteins are extremely important to the healthy functioning of the body's structural molecules. Glycoprotein collagens acting as structural molecules illustrate just one of the numerous functions glycoproteins serve in the body. From the preceding list, it is clear that many diseases have altered glycoproteins in common.<BR>What raw materials does the body use to build these important glycoprotein molecules? Ultimately, only plants can capture the sun's energy to produce the carbohydrates (sugars) required by the body. Thus, the plants in our diet are the primary building blocks for the sugar portion of these molecules that are vital to continued good health. The body breaks down plant carbohydrates, restructures them into small sugars, then uses those sugars to build the glycoproteins required for accurate cellular communication and the resultant good health.<BR>Until now the fields of glycobiology and nutrition have never been adequately investigated together. This is true, even in light of 1) the above discussed current scientific knowledge concerning the importance of glycoproteins in cell-cell communication, 2) the importance of sugars in formation of glycoproteins and 3) in spite of the fact that diet is the major source of all carbohydrates (sugars). Although current nutrition textbooks stress the importance of essential vitamins, minerals, proteins (amino acids) and fats in great detail, sugars are currently recognized only as a source of energy (Shils et al., 1994)-not as substances essential to glycoprotein production for good health. <BR>In contrast to the nutrition textbooks, the textbook Harper's Biochemistry (Murray et al., 1996) lists eight monosaccharides commonly found in human glycoproteins which are known to be important to the healthy functioning of the human body. These are: galactose, glucose, mannose, N-acetylneuraminic acid, fucose, N-acetylgalactosamine, N-acetylglucosamine, and xylose. These eight come from a universe of approximately 200 monosaccharides found in nature. <BR>Of the required eight sugars named in Harper's Biochemistry, only glucose and galactose are addressed in the classic nutrition texts; the other six are omitted. Modern nutrition textbooks give the principal sources of dietary carbohydrates as: 1) maize, rice, wheat, and potato which yield starches composed of glucose; 2) sugar cane and beet sugar which yield glucose; and 3) milk which yields galactose and glucose (Shils et al., 1994). Lactose-intolerant individuals who do not eat dairy products will be deficient even in galactose since the body manufactures galactose from the lactose in dairy products. The remaining six sugars must either be synthesized by the body or obtained from dietary supplements. <BR>While the body uses certain dietary sugars as raw materials to build the glyco- portion of glycoproteins, enzymes are the tools the body uses to build them. Enzymes cause (catalyze) chemical reactions in other substances without being destroyed or altered themselves when the reaction is completed. To function properly, enzymes require adequate supplies of substrate (i.e. raw material). In the case of glycoprotein production, the substrates are the eight sugars mentioned above. Most important: This process does not occur at optimal capacity if adequate supplies of substrate (necessary sugars) are not available (Murray, 1996).<BR>The following equation (Michaelis-Menten Equation), which defines the kinetic properties of most enzymes, demonstrates the importance of consuming adequate amounts of dietary sugars for glycoprotein production:<BR>V=Vmax [S] / [S] + Kmwhere V is the velocity of the reaction; Vmax is maximum velocity; [S] is substrate (sugar), concentration; and KM is the Michaelis constant. This equation means that at high substrate concentrations the rate of the reaction is maximized, i.e. V = Vmax.<BR>Recognizing this, Mannatech has developed supplements to provide the various sugars needed for correctly structured and, therefore, optimally functioning glycoproteins. We have already experienced the results of adding only one of these sugars-mannose-to our diets; so, we are excited about the potential of providing other sugars essential for healthy glycoprotein production. Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> complex is a mixture of proprietary, standardized natural saccharides. <BR>Mannatech is thrilled to be able to bring this exciting technology to market with the introduction of Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> complex. This is totally in keeping with Mannatech's continuing mission: To provide cutting-edge proprietary technology to the marketplace. The patent claims which have been filed are focused on protecting Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> complex from competition for the next 20 years.<BR><BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
