<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mannatech Tomorrow Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="Tom.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/1aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Fin.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/2aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Ath.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/3aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Pro.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/4aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Act.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/5aBtn.jpg"></A><BR><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/Hma.jpg"></A><BR><BR><A HREF="Tom.html">Tomorrow  |  </A><A HREF="Fin.html">Financial  |  </A><A HREF="Ath.html">Athletics  |  </A><A HREF="Pro.html">Products  |  </A><A HREF="Act.html">Action  |  </A><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/">Home</A><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><H1>Third-Party Validation</H1><BR><A HREF="WallSt.html">The Wall Street Journal     |     </A><A HREF="NBJ.html">Nutrition Business Journal     |     </A><A HREF="Time.html">Time - Special Issue</A><BR><BR><BR></CENTER>Print and broadcast media often share their stark, violent headlines with health and wellness breakthroughs. Why not? Health is our basic wealth. Staying well is a priority, especially for those who've been ill or injured. With skyrocketing costs and health care provider uncertainty, patients still need the assurance that there are solutions to their health problems. Wellness is a hot media topic. Start with the September 1996 issue of "Texas Business" magazine. When the table of contents declares, "Give this company some respect. Mannatech is moving multilevel marketing and supplements out of the dark ages and into welcoming arms," you can be sure this leading business publication has found a lot to like. It's important to know that "Texas Business" came to Mannatech. Mannatech didn't contact the magazine. The article's author, Joe Grey, was so impressed with the company that he called recently, requesting information for an article slated for another publication.<BR>The November 1996 issue of Veggie Life magazine calls phytochemicals "Nature's Pharmacy." "Phytochemicals," it says, "are the biologically active substances in plants that give them their color, flavor, odor, and protection against plant diseases. During the past few years, scientists have discovered that many of these plant chemicals may also protect the body against disease." There's much more. This article is a mini-education which, at the same time, validates current information available on phytochemicals.Life magazine's September 1996 article, "The Healing Revolution," should be required reading. Here's an excerpt: "It is no secret that during the past few years an increasing number of Americans have been turning to alternative medicineÉ What's news is that their doctors are joining them: A recent survey of family physicians found that more than half regularly prescribe alternative therapy or have tried it themselvesÉ Even the American Medical Association, which two decades ago declared it 'unethical' for its members to associate with chiropractors, grudgingly passed a resolution last year suggesting that its 300,000 members 'become better informed regarding the practices and techniques of alternative or unconventional medicine.'" New wellness information is news!<BR>In 1992 The National Institutes of Health set up an Office of Alternative Medicine, acknowledging the existence of other therapies. Twenty-six modest but groundbreaking grants have been awarded to study such alternative therapies as guided imagery to control asthma and hypnosis to treat back pain.Public Radio recently reported FDA approval of acupuncture needles as medical instruments opening the way for acupuncture as valid therapy. It may soon be one of the alternative therapies insurance companies have begun to cover. The state of Washington became the first in the nation this year when it began requiring insurance reimbursement for treatment performed by any licensed or certified health-care practitioner of massage, acupuncture and approximately 30 other techniques. Various studies suggest that interest in and demand for alternative therapies is at an all-time high.<BR>The Journal of the American Medical Association, JAMA, of Feb. 22, 1995 says, "The growing use of botanicals (products derived from plants) by the U.S. public is forcing moves to evaluate the health claims of these agents and to develop standards of quality and manufacture."<BR>Demand is the key. As people learn more about the less expensive, less invasive, more effective therapies with implications for long-term benefits, they demand them. Other parts of the world are ahead of the U.S. in that regard. In Europe, more herbal remedies are sold than prescription drugs. In the Orient, a variety of alternative therapies has flourished for at least a thousand years. A direct result of such demand is the learning program for health care practitioner at the University of Arizona. Directed by Andrew Weil, M.D., a 1968 graduate of Harvard Medical School, U of A offers M.D.s a two-year postdoctoral program in alternative medicine, a process Weil calls "the integrative medicine movement."<BR>Phytochemicals' perceived health benefits position Mannatech in the forefront of this integrative movement. Mannatech's products, while not intended for use as disease treatments, are designed to support optimal health. Mannatech leads the way in the current trend to take responsibility for ones own health maintenance. Newsweek magazine stated in 1994, "In a world where science merges with health, phytochemicals are the next big thing. Private firms are eyeing them as a health blockbuster." Need we say more?<BR><BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</