<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mannatech Tomorrow Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="Tom.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/1aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Fin.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/2aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Ath.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/3aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Pro.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/4aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Act.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/5aBtn.jpg"></A><BR><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/Hma.jpg"></A><BR><BR><A HREF="Tom.html">Tomorrow  |  </A><A HREF="Fin.html">Financial  |  </A><A HREF="Ath.html">Athletics  |  </A><A HREF="Pro.html">Products  |  </A><A HREF="Act.html">Action  |  </A><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/">Home</A><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><H1>EM&#183;PACT your SPORT Performance</H1><I>by Bill Fioretti</I><BR><BR><BR></CENTER><IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 SRC="/pics/Sport.jpg">First let's discuss how specific combinations of EM&#183;PACT with the rest of the Mannatech product line could be used to help achieve maximal athletic performance. EM&#183;PACT can be described as a high-tech pre-exercise/during exercise supplement that could assist in the body's efficient conversion of fuel into energy.<BR>There is a tremendous amount of information associated with exercise physiology-the scope of which this article does not allow me to cover. However, I will explain some of the body's basic biochemical and physiological processes as it responds to varying levels of exercise intensity. During exercise, the single most important biochemical and physiological event is the supply of energy to the muscles. The basic philosophy behind the EM&#183;PACT product is to assist these biochemical events for the production of energy.<BR><BR><B>Fuels</B><BR>The three basic fuels used during exercise are carbohydrates, proteins, and fats. Predominantly, the body uses carbohydrates and fats as a source of fuel during exercise. The higher the intensity of exercise, the higher the percentage of carbohydrates used as a source of fuel. Therefore, during long duration, low-intensity exercises, such as walking or jogging long distances, there is a tendency to burn more fat. During high-intensity workouts, such as running at a competitive pace, sprinting, weight lifting, or resistance-type movements, there is a tendency to burn more carbohydrates. The body has a built-in mechanism regulated hormonally that switches the metabolism between these two basic fuels. The conversion of fat into energy has a limit that, when the energy demand exceeds this limit, causes the body to burn either carbohydrates or protein. Protein usually contributes less than 5% of the energy needed during an exercise bout because the body's mechanism is to spare protein and use fuels in the form of carbohydrates and fats instead.<BR>"Getting into shape" or becoming physically fit, basically involves stimulating the enzyme systems that make these biochemical conversions from stored fuel into usable energy. Along with this is an increase in muscle mass to insure that the body can handle the physical demand of exercise. Improving your physical performance level is achieved by continually putting increased demands on the body so that biochemically and physiologically the storage of fuels and the production of energy become as efficient as possible.<BR>The major energy-producing metabolic pathways in the body were some of the original biochemical discoveries, dating back as far as the 1930s and 40s. The body breaks down glucose (the major carbohydrate in its system) through a series of biochemical conversions into a chemical called pyruvate and then into a chemical called Acetyl CoA. This process of breaking down glucose or carbohydrates is called glycolysis. Acetyl CoA is a combination of Coenzyme A (made from the vitamin pantothenic acid, B5) and 2 of the 6 carbon molecules contained in each glucose molecule. (Acetyl CoA can also be formed from the breakdown of fat.) This is the point in energy metabolism at which the basic fuel supplies converge during the aerobic production of energy. Acetyl CoA then goes through the Tricarboxylic Acid Cycle (TCA Cycle), and roughly 38 adenosine-tri-phosphate (ATP) molecules per molecule of glucose are generated. ATP molecules fuel the body at rest as well as during all levels of activity.<BR><BR><B>Storage forms of the basic fuels</B><BR>The body's major storage of glucose is in the form of a substance known as glycogen. The body has a very limited storage capacity for glycogen. It is primarily stored in the liver and muscle. Glycogen could be compared to a string of pearls with each pearl being a glucose molecule. It has been estimated that approximately 2 pounds of glycogen can be stored by the average person. That represents about 3,500 calories of energy production. The body's major storage of fat is in the form of substances called triglycerides. These are merely 3 fat molecules connected to a glycerol molecule. In order for fat to be burned as energy, it must first be broken down from triglycerides into free-fatty acids. These free-fatty acids must then enter the mitochondria, described as the powerhouse of the cell because this is where the vast majority of energy production takes place in all cells, including muscle cells. To enter the mitochondria, free-fatty acids need to be combined with a substance known as Carnitine, which serves as the carrier molecule. Once in the mitochondria, the fat molecule is broken down by a process called beta-oxidation to form Acetyl CoA. From here, the process is exactly as we described above for carbohydrates.<BR> The body's ability to store energy in the form of fat is basically unlimited. Any calories that are not used for energy production and basic bodily functions are stored as fat. So in comparison to the energy stored in the form of glycogen, we have an almost unlimited supply of energy in the form of fat. For example, a man in reasonably good condition who weighs approximately 175 pounds with 15% body fat has about 26 pounds of stored fat. That amount of stored fat can produce roughly 110,000 calories (or 30 times the energy stored in the form of carbohydrates). One can easily see why the body prioritizes the use of fat as fuel when the exercise intensity permits fat to be used as fuel.<BR>Obviously, the production of energy is not just associated with exercise, it's essential to life. What we do during exercise is put a demand on our system that requires increased energy production. So how do we optimize this? Mannatech's EM&#183;PACT and some of its other products could help maximize the use of the body's energy supplies in order to accomplish the single most important goal of conditioning: to provide sufficient energy to allow an increase in workout intensity and duration, which over time could lead to improved physical condition.<BR><BR><B>Product Components</B><BR>EM&#183;PACT could help produce these results by providing various biochemical intermediates that are used in the breakdown of both carbohydrates and fats as well as to help accelerate and optimize the use of these stored bodily fuels. EM&#183;PACT is designed to be taken within 15 minutes of the start of an exercise bout. It provides several different components, such as energy in the form of crystalline fructose. Fructose is a carbohydrate that is readily converted to glucose in the system but does not induce the release of insulin. Insulin is a hormone that drives carbohydrates into the cell. If you ingest a large dose of carbohydrates immediately prior to exercise, you can induce a hypoglycemic state called exercise-induced hypoglycemia. That's why the use of candy bars and other such foods have been proven not to be beneficial to the system. Fructose, on the other hand, does not induce an insulin response and provides a readily available source of carbohydrates, which is essential for the body in the initial phases of exercise. Also contained in EM&#183;PACT are medium-chain triglycerides. These are readily broken down by the body to provide a short-chain free-fatty acid that is burned at a high rate of speed, used efficiently by exercising muscles, and helps the system burn fat as fuel. In essence, efficiently used bodily fuels are a basic component of EM&#183;PACT.<BR>The second major group of supplement components in EM&#183;PACT contains some of the biochemical intermediates that could assist in more efficient energy production through the use of stored carbohydrates and fats. These include calcium citrate, magnesium aspartate, magnesium succinate, potassium aspartate, and potassium succinate. These are specific biochemicals used in the TCA cycle, or direct precursors that provide the system with the ability to enhance energy production. EM&#183;PACT also contains Carnitine and lecithin, which could assist in the metabolism of fat that also use the TCA cycle for energy production. In all, EM&#183;PACT provides fuels and metabolic intermediates, that could help in the TCA cycle, as well as choline, magnesium, and potassium aspartate. These aspartates help buffer the cells from lactic acid build-up effects and also convert lactic acid back to pyruvate. Lactic acid is a by-product of anaerobic energy production. It causes muscle soreness after a workout and is the reason why, after sprinting a few hundred yards, you may get a very bad pain in your side or feel tightness in your legs.<BR>EM&#183;PACT is essentially a high-tech mixture of very specific biochemicals and bionutrients that could provide the basis for increased energy production. And of course, to complete the system, we have also added our patented and proprietary substance, Ambrotose<FONT SIZE=-3>(TM)</FONT> complex. EM&#183;PACT is a tremendous boost in preworkout supplementation that could provide the body with energy and the ability to convert its stored energy for use during sustained exercise. <BR><BR><B>Product Use</B><BR>Now, I would like to spend some time explaining how various Mannatech products can be combined to form an advanced nutritional supplement program for serious athletes as well as general exercise enthusiasts. As we have stated in our literature and training programs, the Mannatech SPORT product is used primarily as a post-exercise supplement. It combines several different bionutrients and phytochemicals, the basis of which is the dioscorea herb (wild yam). Mannatech SPORT could help assist the body in its exercise recovery process. Many physiological and biochemical events occur in the body as a result of exercise. Exercise is the great physiological equalizer because everyone recovers from exercise stress using the same metabolic pathways.<BR>Mannatech SPORT was developed with these metabolic activities in mind. Its basic component, dioscorea, provides important precursors (plant sterols) that the body could use to help support the endocrine system (hormonal system), which orchestrates the recovery process from exercise. Mannatech SPORT also provides additional supplements. Many of you have heard me speak about the importance of dioscorea (among other phytochemicals and medicinal herbs) and how it could help support the body's natural production and balance of hormones. Mannatech SPORT could help enhance the body's natural ability to recover from exercise stress by providing a large selection of plant sterols. This concept is the basis for the formulation of this product. We have taken this philosophy one step further by adding herbs and glandulars that assist in enhancing the anabolic state. The processes of metabolism are two: catabolic processes and anabolic processes. Catabolic means breaking down (such as breaking down glucose into energy), and anabolic means building back up. Mannatech SPORT could help the body in the postexercise rebuilding phase.Numerous testimonials have been received from people stating that their postexercise recoveries have occurred faster and that their next day's exercise routine is much easier. They also feel they have experienced an overall sense of well-being. Many people, athletes or not, report that Mannatech SPORT is the one Mannatech product they like best.<BR>Over the past year, we have gained a great deal of insight and information from people who use our products. This input has greatly assisted us in the formulation of a more advanced nutritional supplement program for athletes and exercise enthusiasts alike. Prior to exercise, using the combination of EM&#183;PACT and Mannatech SPORT might assist in fat breakdown and might increase the availability of fat as a fuel source during exercise. <BR>Specific hormones are known to stimulate an enzyme called carnitine acetyl transferase. Carnitine, one of the components of EM&#183;PACT, could assist in getting fat molecules into the mitochondria in order to be burned as fuel. In that way, the use of the dioscorea product one half hour to an hour prior to workout could possibly set the hormonal condition up so that you get a more efficient burning of fat during your workout. The benefits are twofold. First, if you are exercising as a means of weight management (most of us being more concerned with fat loss than just weight loss), it could promote fat loss. The second benefit is that when the body uses fat during exercise, it conserves carbohydrates. Most of us, and even well-trained athletes, normally have more fat energy stored than carbohydrates. Any time we can make better use of the fat molecules and the energy they contain and spare carbohydrates, we have an ability to extend our exercise routine and/or increase the intensity. <BR>I think what we, as a company, are learning through our experience with these products, particularly in the athletic area, that the use of our dioscorea-containing products in combination with EM&#183;PACT prior to workouts and then Mannatech SPORT following workouts, is a supplemental system that could have a significant effect in improving your exercise routines. I think that this combination is definitely the way for athletes at all levels to get maximum benefits from the use of Mannatech products.<BR>We hope this information has provided you with a better understanding regarding the body's complex energy production system. It is also important to understand that Mannatech products alone do not substitute for the other nutritional components provided by our diets that are essential for life and increased athletic performance. The recent advances in phytochemical discoveries and exercise physiology research have provided Mannatech with the information to formulate products that help to optimize these processes.<BR><BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
