ogy review: Most of us have a general idea of what metabolism is and does; few of us remember precisely what's involved. (Try to act like you knew all this, and you're just going over it for review!) Here goes:<BR>Metabolism is the name for the chemical and physical processes going on continuously in all living organisms and cells. Metabolism has two parts: Anabolism: the process in which assimilated food is built up into protoplasm (the essential living matter of all animal and plant cells), and Catabolism: the process in which protoplasm is used and broken down into simpler substances or waste matter, at the same time releasing energy for all vital processes (breathing, thinking, digesting, moving-insignificant stuff like that).<BR>Why are we torturing you with this? So that you can appreciate the fact that metabolism 1). is a critical function, uniquely different in each individual, and that 2). it requires specific nutritional elements in specific amounts to get the maximum value from the process. <BR>If you don't have enough of one element, or have too much of another, it will alter your metabolic processes. Because we're biochemically unique, it's obvious that one diet won't work for everyone. Each of us has different requirements and needs. <BR><BR><B>Biochemical Individuality</B><BR>Biochemical individuality is not NEW news. In the first century B.C., the Roman philosopher, Lucretius commented, "One man's meat is another man's poison." By 1919, Dr. Frances Pottenger was examining metabolic individuality. In the 1950s, Drs. Melvin Page and Henry Bieler concurrently developed concepts of "endocrine types" and their relationship to various foods. In the same time frame, Dr. George Watson described Fast and Slow Oxidizers and their characteristics.<BR>Dr. Roger Williams, the University of Texas's noted biochemical researcher and the first biochemist to be elected president of the American Chemical Society, originated the genetotrophic theory which suggests that every human being has distinct nutritional needs. He wrote, "That malnutrition--unbalanced or inadequate nutrition-at the cellular level should be thought of as a major cause of human disease seems crystal clear to me. It is the inevitable conclusion to be drawn from the facts produced by decades of biochemical research."<BR>In other words, philosophers and scientists have noted differences in behavior and performance created by nutrition for more than 2,000 years. It's just been in the last 25 years, however, that strategies to meet individual biochemical needs have finally begun to emerge. <BR>In the early '80s, Dr. William D. Kelley developed a computerized system of metabolic profiling. The database was compiled from 10,000 patients with degenerative diseases and focused first on the autonomic nervous system alone. This program was later expanded to include the other major energy-producing system in the body, the Oxidative System. This is an overview of how these systems work:<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>The Autonomic Nervous System:</B> Divided into sympathetic and parasympathetic, it controls the motor functions of heart, lungs, intestines, glands and other internal organs, and of the smooth muscles, the blood vessels, and the lymph vessels.<BR><LI><B>The Oxidative System:</B> The process inside the cells in which oxygen and substrates interact, producing energy and water.<BR></UL>These two systems are the focus of Mannatech's Metabolic Profiling. By design, best results are obtained from combining dietary recommendations for your metabolic profile with nutritional supplements designed specifically for your metabolic profile group. If you want to know even more, refer to the Mannatech brochure on Metabolic Profiling for complete information. Bon Appetit!<BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
