USP, United States Pharmacopoeia, vitamins. Very simply, that means that these vitamins are isolated pharmaceutical chemicals. And the minerals? The minerals are mined from the ground!<BR><BR><B>VITAMINS: Supplements vs Food</B><BR>As an example, Vit. B-6 in supplements is pyridoxine hydrochloride, a synthetic USP chemical. This is nothing like the Vit. B-6 in food. Pyridoxine hydrochloride isn't found in any food. The only vitamins that are found in food are contained in a highly complex form we call the food matrix. This food matrix contains proteins, carbohydrates, lipids, bioflavonoids and other food factors. Our bodies recognize and utilize these vitamins most easily in food matrix form.<BR><BR><B>MINERALS: Supplements vs Food</B><BR>All minerals originally come from the ground. Much of our food also grows in the ground. Minerals in the soil enter plants through the roots and are assimilated inside the plant cells into complex structures which our bodies can use. They become part of the living plant tissue, part of the food matrix. That's why the iron in broccoli doesn't look like the iron in your car. One is a metal mined from the ground and the other is contained in living food tissue. In those supplements that utilize USP minerals, the minerals are not food; they are rocks and metals mined from the ground.<BR>Let's examine calcium supplements. With a little training, you can learn to read container labels and translate some of the chemical names into everyday language. What's called calcium carbonate on the label is really limestone. Calcium sulfate is plaster. Calcium phosphate is chalk. Often these are reacted with chemicals. As one example: calcium citrate, lactate and ascorbate are limestone reacted with acids. Other forms of calcium that are not naturally occurring include amino acid chelates, colloidal minerals and hydroxyapatite.<BR><BR><B>Check the labels.</B><BR>Think about this: If we could assimilate rocks and metals from the ground, we wouldn't need to grow food. We could gain the necessary nutrients just by eating the soil. That's a ridiculous proposal, of course, because we all know that our bodies weren't designed to be nourished by rocks. No civilization in history has managed to exist on a diet of rocks, shells or bones, yet, that's what you get in USP supplements. How much ground rock do you think your body can assimilate? Not much! Nonetheless, your body will make a heroic effort. It does its best to make the mineral into complex molecules that it can use, excreting what it can't use. And, although the supplements provide such limited nutritional value, mega-dosing is not an option, since mega-doses can cause side effects.In looking for alternatives, some people have considered using colloidal minerals, minerals suspended in their own salts. These salts are very sensitive to pH, and as a result, can be broken down easily by the acid/alkaline present in the stomach. Where these might provide a higher level of absorption than the simple mineral, they are not in food matrix form, and as such don't compare favorably.<BR><BR><B>What About the So-Called "Food-Based" Vitamin/Mineral Supplements?</B><BR>"Natural" or "food-based" supplements are formulated with the same USP chemical vitamins and minerals we've mentioned before. Formulators simply put them into a big blender with small amounts of powdered foods and mix the two together. Products created by this method are then sold as "natural" or "food-based" powders, tablets or liquids. The problem with this approach is that the USP vitamins and minerals are unchanged. They are still not recognizable to your body. Your mind may be fooled by a little powdered food mixed with rocks and chemicals, but the cells of your body won't be.<BR><BR><B>The Best Answer: Food Matrix Vitamins and Minerals </B><BR>The closer a substance is to the elements of which the body is made, the more affinity the body has for the substance, the more recognizable the substance is to the body. That's why phrases such as "natural" and "food-based" have so much appeal, because they convey the idea that these substances are easy to absorb and use. That isn't the fact; it was the image that was conveyed. In fact, until recently, there were no acceptable options.<BR>People continue to look for high-quality supplements that perform as promised, but their efforts have largely been frustrated. Although scientists have researched all the right sources, the fruits and vegetables that promise so much, they've found it almost impossible to create a formula that provided enough of any of the necessary nutrients. <BR>They've investigated the cutting-edge "super" foods such as spirulina, blue-green algae, chlorella, bee pollen and nutritional yeast, but found that even these high-powered concentrates offered only minimal amounts of the desired nutrients. And even though it sounds like a good idea, eating large amounts of any of these substances to gain the potential benefits simply creates a more unbalanced system.<BR>Vitamin and mineral formulators had almost reached a stalemate before researchers developed processes which would convert USP vitamins and minerals into usable form through a food matrix. Although the processes are proprietary, most follow a format similar to this: Vitamins are combined, one-on-one, with biologically active concentrates of particular foods. This allows a reaction to occur, the result of which is a food matrix. Converting minerals and Vit. D to natural form is accomplished by feeding them to growing one-celled plants such as baker's yeast after which enzymes are added. Obviously there's more to both processes, but these are the basics.<BR>Obtaining vitamins and minerals in a food matrix enables your body to get more nourishment than ever before possible with no danger of toxicity. Studies have shown that this formulation may be better absorbed, utilized and retained than isolated USP forms. Better yet, vitamins and minerals in a food matrix rarely cause the nausea sometimes associated with ordinary vitamins.<BR><BR><B>Do You Need Food Matrix Vitamins and Minerals?</B><BR>None of us is eating an ideal diet unless we've already moved to the pollution-free hilltop of our dreams. The rest of us don't seem to have access to three perfectly balanced, properly prepared meals of natural foods each day. Long work hours, stress, polluted air, water and food affect our intake. That's why we need to be sure our supplements are providing everything we need. And that's also why the properly formulated ingredients in Profiles 1, 2 and 3 are so vital to our well-being.<BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
