<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mannatech Tomorrow Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="Tom.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/1aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Fin.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/2aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Ath.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/3aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Pro.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/4aBtn.jpg"></A><A HREF="Act.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/5aBtn.jpg"></A><BR><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/pics/Hma.jpg"></A><BR><BR><A HREF="Tom.html">Tomorrow  |  </A><A HREF="Fin.html">Financial  |  </A><A HREF="Ath.html">Athletics  |  </A><A HREF="Pro.html">Products  |  </A><A HREF="Act.html">Action  |  </A><A HREF="//www.mannatech-inc.com/">Home</A><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><H1>"Strategies for Success" List</H1><I>An interview by David Colister with Marion Culhane and Luis Kunz</I><BR><BR><BR><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 SRC="/pics/Cul.jpg"></CENTER>"Because of my 20 years of personal growth and experience as a seminar leader on the subject of 'Letting Go of Limiting Beliefs,' I never doubted for a moment that my partner and I would be successful as Mannatech Associates. I was committed from the very beginning. I was ready to allow it to happen. In fact, I didn't find Mannatech; Mannatech found me!"--Marion CulhaneThere is no doubt about it. Marion Culhane is one calm, confident and focused woman, but she's not at all self-absorbed. Rather, she is a sweet, kind, supportive person whose life has been devoted to helping others improve the quality of their lives. Her devotion to others has paved the way for enormous success in Mannatech. In a candid interview at the elegant Crown Sterling Suites in Phoenix, Arizona, where our certified MA Training weekend was held, Marion discussed with me the strategies she has employed in building a large organization that now earns more money for her in one month than she previously made in one year. Enjoy!<BR><BR>DC: What's at the very top of your "Strategies for Success List"?<BR><BR>MC: Making sure that my inner activities - the way I think about myself, others and my world - are as productive as my outer activities. I know that I knew less about the mechanics of network marketing than many others who make less money in Mannatech than we make. I contribute that to my mindset. In a little more than one year, our business has put us into a mid-six-figure income.<BR><BR>DC: Obviously it took years to develop such a positive self-image and attitude, but how did you translate that into confidence for the network marketing business?<BR><BR>MC: I became a serious student of network marketing and Mannatech. I read a book a week and listened to audio cassettes every time I was in my car - about six tapes a week.<BR><BR>DC: Name some of the books you read that really helped you.<BR><BR>MC: "Being the Best You Can Be in MLM," "Wave 3: The New Era in Network Marketing," "Streetsmart Networking," "Living With Passion," "The Greatest Networker in the World," "MLM Magic," "Think and Grow Rich." There were many more, but these were some of the best.<BR><BR>DC: What kinds of audio tapes did you listen to?<BR><BR>MC: Mostly company tapes and others about network marketing and motivation. I listened to them over and over again until they really sank in.<BR><BR>DC: What kinds of "outer" activities contributed to your quick success?<BR><BR>MC: First, I developed a list of over 200 names of friends and acquaintances who I wanted to share the business with and called about four new people every day.<BR><BR>DC: What did you say when you called them?<BR><BR>MC: I told them I was involved with a new business named Mannatech and that people were having great success in improving their health with the company's products. I told them I would like to send them some information about the business opportunity and products. Then I would send them the stuff and follow up within a few days to check on their interest level and either sign them up or get them on the products.<BR><BR>DC: What "stuff" do you send them?<BR><BR>MC: (A big grin spreads across her face...) In the early days, anything I could get my hands on that I thought would interest them. Now, however, I use only the brochures and the "Mannatech Today" newspaper with an audio tape. The paper has more than enough valuable information in it. In fact, I use a highlighter pen to emphasize key parts that I think will match people's interests.<BR><BR>DC: Do you concentrate mostly on getting people to try the products or to try the business?<BR><BR>MC: I have tried to meet people wherever they are, and now I focus primarily on the business. I dedicate almost all my time to working with sincere business builders.<BR><BR>DC: How many people did you sponsor personally?<BR><BR>MC: We recruited about 20 people in our first three months. We didn't always place them direct to ourselves. We tried to keep family members and friends together. So, sometimes, we would place someone who was personally interested in the business under someone else they knew.<BR><BR>DC: How did you direct these people once they were committed to their business?<BR><BR>MC: That's a key question. I think it's very important to get people started properly. One of the things I stress is attending training meetings and the national events such as All-Star Training and rallies, local Master Associate Training, and ongoing leadership training times. I encourage people to attend all of the national events, local meetings and events, and re-audit Master Associate Training regularly.<BR>This is a real business and people need to have a strong grasp of the basics of networking and the specifics of Mannatech. They, too, need to become serious students of this business if they expect to succeed. Networking is a process of duplicating your success-producing activities---those inside our minds and those outside our minds---in others. So, I encourage people to read a lot and listen to as many tapes as possible. My partner and I created an audio tape called "Beyond Your Wildest Dreams" to share what we've done to be successful, plus offering a one-day seminar to help people set their goals and release their blocks, fears and limiting beliefs.<BR><BR>DC: I have noticed that there are many activities that people involve themselves in that are counterproductive, really distracting things, that they think are important. Have you noticed this, too?<BR><BR>MC: Yes! One thing people need to be mindful of is that all distractions are equal. I teach people to ask themselves this question about everything they do, "Is this a distraction or am I actually doing the business?" Some of the most common distractions are:<BR><UL><LI>Watching television,<LI>Negative conversation and complaining,<LI>Focusing on problems rather than solutions,<LI>Pettiness,<LI>Unnecessary "rest" times,<LI>Associating with non-supportive people,<LI>Reading non-Mannatech-related, non-growth producing literature including newspapers, magazines, newsletters.</UL><BR><BR>If you don't want to waste a lot of time, energy, and money, you must focus! And I do believe in living a balanced life.<BR><BR>DC: What are some important disciplines for success in Mannatech?<BR><BR>MC: <BR><UL><LI>Personal time to get centered within yourself.<LI>Quiet time to get focused on your goals and priorities.<LI>Personal time with family members and friends to keep those supportive relationships strong.<LI>Exercise to keep your body healthy.<LI>Staying organized. Don't let clutter build!<LI>Handle mail immediately.<LI>Maintain a "To Do" list.<LI>Never put an action item on the "To Do" list that can be done now.<LI>Brainstorm with your leaders.<LI>Use all the products.<LI>Lead by example. Never tell people to do things that you aren't doing.<LI>Write a newsletter to send to your downline. (We publish ours every other month.)<LI>Do weekly conference calls with the leaders in your group.<LI>Broadcast fax urgent updates to your leaders. (I do this several times a week.)<LI>Hold a weekly meeting. (We alternate a Business Briefing with Business Builders' Training every other week.)<LI>Refrain from calling Customer Service for information that you can get from your upline.<LI>Don't jump past your immediate upline leader. This keeps an organization tight and healthy.<LI>Present the business to new people every day - for yourself and your downline. (I do a lot of three-way calls.)</UL><BR><BR>DC: List some of the essential "tools of the trade."<BR><BR>MC: <BR><UL><LI>Three-way or conference calling phone service,<LI>A fax machine,<LI>A copy machine,<LI>Voice mail,<LI>A file cabinet,<LI>Speaker phone,<LI>A good portable phone.</UL><BR><BR>DC: Is there anything you would like to say to the readers in closing?<BR><BR>MC: Sure. Have fun with this business. Everything you do allows for a win/win opportunity, so enjoy the journey. Commit yourself to helping others attain their goals while staying focused on your own. Be grateful for being part of this. The payoff in friendship, fun and financial freedom is fantastic. I've never been involved in an endeavor that's been as deeply satisfying as Mannatech.<BR><BR><CENTER><HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center SIZE=2><BR><FONT SIZE = 3>Available E-Mail addresses are as follows:<BR><A HREF="mailto:ldaniel@mail.mannatech-inc.com">Customer Service<BR> Email contact for customer service questions and problems.</A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Mannatech, Inc. all rights reserved.<BR></FONT></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
