<HEAD>

<TITLE>Cal Law Special Event - Charles Keating</title></head>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK=#cd661d VLINK=#008b8b>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR><FONT COLOR=FF0000 SIZE=+3>COUNSEL CONNECT WEB</FONT><BR CLEAR=ALL>






<H2>Charles Keating:<BR>
Scoundrel or Scapegoat?</H2>


<TABLE>



<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>n Dec. 2, a Los Angeles federal judge threw
out Charles Keating Jr.'s 1993 federal racketeering, conspiracy and fraud
convictions stemming from the collapse of the Lincoln Savings & Loan
Association. Several jurors, the judge found, had been tainted by knowledge of
a prior state conviction of Keating -- a conviction that, coincidentally, had
been reversed in April. The man who symbolized the savings-and-loan crisis of
the late 1980s was now free.
<P>
"He's an innocent man now; he hasn't been convicted of anything," his attorney,
Stephen Neal, told the <I>Los Angeles Times</I>.
<P>
Not convicted, yes. But innocent? Keating is still on the hook for part of a
$1.6 billion civil judgment for defrauding investors. He had taken a sleepy
industry that doled out mortgages to one that invested in risky real estate and
junk bonds to the elderly. His accusers say that the four and a-half years that
he spent in prison are not enough punishment for the losses his investors and
taxpayers suffered and prosecutors may yet have their way with him.
<P>
Keating has maintained throughout that he has been the victim of know-nothing
regulators and overzealous prosecutors and that he ran his businesses on the
up-and-up. And other observers say pinning the failure of an industry on the
shoulders of one individual distracts from an examination of more fundamental
systemic problems.
<P>
So what is it? Is Charles Keating a scapegoat or a scoundrel? We've gathered
four experts for an online discussion of that question.
<P>
<A NAME=neal>Our panelists are:<BR></A>
<B>STEPHEN NEAL</B>, Keating's lawyer and a partner in the Palo Alto office of
San Francisco's Cooley Godward. </FONT>(Read a <A
HREF=../../edt1114c.html><I>Recorder</I> profile</A> of Stephen Neal.)<FONT
SIZE=+1>
<A NAME=cabra><P></A>
<B>ELIZABETH CABRASER</B>, one of the lead attorneys in the civil litigation
against Keating. Cabraser is a partner at the San Francisco consumer
class-action firm Lieff, Cabraser, Heimann & Bernstein.
<A NAME=ely><P></A>
<B>BERT ELY</B>, a financial-industry consultant who was one of the first
analysts to predict the bailout of the FSLIC. Ely, who runs his own Alexandria,
Virginia, consulting firm has ified frequently before Congressional committees
investigating S&L industry. He has appeared as an expert witness in several S&L
cases, although not in those against Keating.
<A NAME=raph><P></A>
<B>IRA RAPHAELSON</B>, a former U.S. special counsel for financial institutions
crime. Raphaelson oversaw most of the federal prosecutions in the S&L arena,
including that of Keating. He is a Washington partner for Los Angeles-based
O'Melveny & Myers.
<A NAME=pes><P></A>
Moderating the discussion is <B>PETER SCHEER</B>, editor and publisher of
<I>The Recorder</I>, a daily legal newspaper in the San Francisco.
<P>
Our panelists are conversing via e-mail and the text of their comments,
rearranged and cleaned up slightly to ease reading, are being assembled here in
different "takes" as the conversation unfolds. As each take is posted you'll
have access to it from the top of this page.
<P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=51%>
<DT>Go to:</DT></FONT>
<DD><A HREF=keat1.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 1</FONT></A></DD>
<DD><A HREF=keat2.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 2</FONT></A></DD>
<DD><A HREF=keat3.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 3</FONT></A></DD>
<DD><A HREF=keat4.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 4</FONT></A></DD>
</TD>


</TR>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=49% ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>
Go to:<BR>
<A HREF=keat1.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 1</FONT></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1 COLOR=#008b8b>Keating's lawyer, Stephen Neal, argues that his
client was the victim of government regulators who acted rashly when the real
estate market hit the skids.</FONT>
</TD>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=49% ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>
<A HREF=keat2.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 2</FONT></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1 COLOR=#008b8b>Ira Raphaelson maintains that, subsequent rulings
aside, Keating's conviction was supported by ample evidence and a jury simply
did not believe his defense.</FONT>
</TD>


<TR>
<TD>
<PRE>
</PRE>
</TD>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=216 VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>

</TD>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=49% ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>
<A HREF=keat3.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 3</FONT></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1 COLOR=#008b8b>Forget the jury verdict, says Steve Neal, the
federal prosecutors' accounting witness testified there was no evidence of sham
transactions between Lincoln and parent firm American Continental Corp. What's
more, supposedly illegal tax-sharing payments from Lincoln to ACC had been
approved by federal regulators.</FONT>
</TD>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=49% ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>
<A HREF=keat4.html><FONT SIZE=+2>Take 4</FONT></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1 COLOR=#008b8b>What's the best evidence against Charles Keating?
Evidence showing he directed additional sales efforts while knowing that
Lincoln Savings' parent company was about to file for bankruptcy, says Ira
Raphaelson. Elizabeth Cabraser offers more: That Keating hid from investors
that the parent company had artificially inflated its assets and couldn't repay
loans.</FONT>
</TD>


<TR>
<TD WIDTH=49% ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>
<A HREF=keat5.html><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1 COLOR=#008b8b></FONT>
</TD>



<TR>
<TD>
