<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Charles Keating: Scoundrel or Scapegoat? Take
1</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff LINK=#cd661d VLINK=#008b8b>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR><FONT COLOR=FF0000 SIZE=+3>COUNSEL CONNECT WEB</FONT><BR CLEAR=ALL>
</blockquote>


<center>
<h2>Charles Keating:<BR>
Scoundrel or Scapegoat?</h2></CENTER>



        <TABLE WIDTH=650 cellspacing=20>



<TR><TD WIDTH=200></TD>


<TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN=right> 
<FONT SIZE=+2>Take 1</FONT></TD></TR>

                <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN=right VALIGN=top>
                
                <P>Go to:<BR>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A
HREF="http://www.counsel.com/features/keat.html">Introduction</A></FONT><P>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat2.html>Take 2</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat3.html>Take 3</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat4.html>Take 4</A></FONT>              
                                
                </TD>


                

<TD WIDTH=450 ROWSPAN=8 VALIGN=top>

<FONT Size=+1>

PETER SCHEER:<BR>
I'd like Steve Neal, as the sole Keating advocate, to open the discussion.
Steve, most of the panelists think that Charles Keating is a crook with a smart
lawyer. Please make the case that Keating is not a crook, but a victim of the
government.
<P>


STEPHEN NEAL:<BR>
Charlie Keating is very much a victim of the government.
<P>
He is a victim because he has spent over 4&#189; years in prison on two
unconstitutional convictions. The constitutional defects in those convictions
were clear, on the record, under controlling precedent at the time of his
trials. The defects were brought to the attention of both the Superior Court in
Los Angeles and the District Court in Los Angeles at the time of the trials,
yet it took over four years to get relief. Nor were these constitutional
defects "technicalities." In the state case, the court gave instructions which
permitted Keating's conviction without any proof of criminal intent. That error
was critical to the outcome, because there was no evidence of criminal intent
on Keating's part, circumstantial or direct. In the federal trial, the jury was
improperly exposed to and impermissibly discussed Keating's state conviction.
The prejudice from that jury misconduct was severe, particularly given the
fact, as found by the Ninth Circuit, that the evidence of Keating's guilt was
not overwhelming.
<P>
These constitutional violations arose and persisted because Keating became
vilified as the symbol of the savings and loan crisis. That notoriety was
undeserved. Keating was as much a victim of the savings and loan crisis as
anyone and more of a victim than most people. At a time when the industry was
already in the red, Keating was induced to invest his money, his energy and his
future in a deregulated industry. His investments in land, buildings and
securities were permitted under the law and approved by both state and federal
regulators. The sale of bonds in Lincoln branches was known to, and effectively
encouraged and approved by, federal and state regulators. Sales practices were
policed by the state of California and found fully satisfactory. The bond
prospectuses described the nature of the investments and the risks in
great detail and with great clarity -- as even the prosecution's own expert in
the state case admitted. All of the money raised from deposits and bond sales
went into hard assets -- land, hotels, office buildings, securities. Despite
the public perception, there was no "looting."
<P>
When the government passed the 1986 tax reform act, momentarily destroyed the
high-yield bond market with its attacks on Wall Street and re-regulated the
savings and loan industry, savings and loans, including Lincoln, suffered
immediate short term losses in the market values of their assets. Regulators
then seized scores of savings and loans, including Lincoln, locked in losses by
disposing of assets at fire-sale prices and caused a huge, avoidable loss to
the fisc and to investors. Then, in an audacious but largely successful move,
the regulators, with the aid of prosecutors, set out to blame the
owner-operators who were, in a real sense, the greatest victims of all. Keating
was their tallest target and their biggest victim. 
<P>


IRA RAPHAELSON:<BR>
Charles Keating was one of a number of high-profile prosecutions brought by the
Justice Department among literally thousands of cases the Department brought
through a deliberative process designed to prosecute traditional crimes of
lying, cheating and stealing. Despite tremendous media and Congressional
pressure to alter its standards, federal prosecutive policy was to bring
financial-institution fraud cases where the standards of the Federal Principles
of Prosecution were met -- that is, the prosecutor believed that there was
proof beyond a reasonable doubt of the elements of the offense. In the Keating
case, like the other 4,000 federal prosecutions, the charges required proof of
intent to defraud. The Department's conviction rate was over 90 percent in the
financial-institution fraud cases it brought and this conviction rate stands as
a direct rebuttal to any suggestion that prosecutive discretion was
misdirected.
<P>


PETER SCHEER:<BR>
Elizabeth, your civil suit yielded the only judgment against Keating that has
not been reversed or dismissed after trial. Based on the evidence in your case,
was Keating victimized by the judicial process?
<P>


ELIZABETH CABRASER:<BR>
Charles Keating is no victim. He needed -- and was fortunate to obtain -- a
very good and very dedicated lawyer. The real victims of the Lincoln Savings
debacle were the trusting depositors who were induced to switch from federally
insured accounts to non-insured and risky Lincoln Savings bonds. We were
fortunate to obtain a recovery for these bondholders, in civil proceedings
brought under the federal securities laws (now largely gutted by federal reform
legislation), civil RICO, and common-law claims. The major credit for this
should go to Joe Cotchett and his firm, the Milberg Weiss firm, and my partner
Bill Hirsch, together with the other plaintiffs' lawyers who served on the
trial team before Judge Bilby in Arizona. I worked with the bondholders to get
and keep the class certified. Through this experience I learned that, while our
ACC/Lincoln Savings multi-district litigation did ultimately achieve gratifying
results for the bondholders, they suffered greatly in the interim. 
<P>
The bondholders' story is summarized in Judge Bilby's 1992 decision denying the
motion of Lincoln Chairman Keating and the other defendants to decertify the
class, published at 140 F.R.D. 425 (D. Ariz. 1992). It describes the
bait-and-switch tactics by which officers at the Lincoln Savings branches were
induced to transfer their savings from insured accounts to higher yielding
Lincoln Savings bonds. Lincoln told its bond representatives to target what
Lincoln dubbed "the weak, the meek, and the ignorant" among its depositors with
a standardized sales pitch, characterized by the court as a "centrally
orchestrated strategy" to mislead bond purchasers into believing that the bonds
were safe. They weren't. 
<P>
As a result, thousands of bondholders lost everything they had, and waited
years for their recovery. They are the real victims of the Lincoln Savings
scam. Many were plunged into poverty, and there are documented instances of
suicide and other personal tragedies attributed by the victims themselves to
this loss. Keating spent some time in jail, but his victims spent years in
hell. Their only mistake was to repose trust in a man and his institution that
held themselves out as fiduciaries. 
<P>
The Lincoln Savings tragedy was repeated at numerous other savings and loans.
Charles Keating alone is not responsible for this industry-wide scandal. It had
its roots in the failure of public regulation, and the resulting fatal gap
between the standards of good faith, fair dealing and responsibility to which,
in the public mind, savings and loans as banking institutions were held, and
the virtually nonexistent standards in actual force. Bondholders and other
investors were the primary victims. The taxpayers who have footed the bill for
the savings and loan bailout were the secondary victims. Since it appears we
cannot have both, I prefer having Charles Keating free and his victims with
their money back, to the alternative of a jailed Keating and penniless
investors. But it is difficult, in the context of the actions of the
institution he directed and for which he is accountable, to view Charles
Keating as deserving of sympathy.
<P>


STEPHEN NEAL:<BR>
Elizabeth asserts that trusting depositors were induced to switch their monies
from federally insured accounts to non-insured and risky Lincoln Savings bonds.
That was the central theme in the public attacks on Keating, in the state
criminal case and in Judge Bilby's characterization of the case.
<P>
But that popular theme is just plain wrong.
<P>
The bond prospectuses said on their face that the bonds were uninsured and
risky. Every bond purchaser who testified for the prosecution in the state
criminal case admitted that they knew both that the bonds were uninsured and
that the bond proceeds were being used for real estate, hotel and other risky
investments. These same witnesses testified that they were told not to invest
any money in Lincoln bonds that they could not afford to lose.
<P>
All of the bond salespeople who testified for the prosecution testified that
they had been instructed to and did tell bond purchasers that the bonds were
uninsured and risky and that purchasers should not invest money they couldn't
afford to lose. The person who ran the bond program testified for the
prosecution under a cooperation agreement. He testified under cross-examination
that his only instruction from Keating concerning the bond sales program was
that he, Keating, wanted the program "squeaky clean."
<P>
It was because of this overwhelming, uncontroverted evidence, coming entirely
from the prosecution's own witnesses, that the prosecution could only get a
conviction with an unconstitutional strict-liability instruction which omitted
any requirement of criminal intent on Keating's part.
<P>
Judge Bilby's views of the case went largely unchallenged. Given the pending
criminal case, Keating did not defend the civil case. Worse, Judge Bilby forced
Keating to sit for a deposition in the civil case while the criminal cases were
pending. Keating had no choice but to exercise his Fifth Amendment rights, and
Judge Bilby then allowed Keating's Fifth Amendment assertions to be used
against those defendants who did try the case. There was never a full, fair
airing of the issues.
<P>
Lincoln did not target the weak, the meek and the ignorant. That phrase was
coined by a low-level employee in a misplaced attempt at humor. The joke was
neither known to nor condoned by Keating or Lincoln management at the time, and
it was repudiated when reported. It is a poor reflection on our justice system
that a joke, albeit a bad one, could help block a reasoned view of the real and
relevant evidence. 
<P>
Investors were given an opportunity to invest in bonds whose risks were
disclosed, according to the state prosecution's own expert, "warts and all."
Investors suffered not because of wrongdoing by Keating. They suffered because
the assets underlying those investments were dramatically and temporarily
reduced in value by government action, seized by the regulators and then sold
to wealthy investors who captured the rebounding appreciation in value while
investors, the taxpayers and Keating suffered greatly.
<P>


PETER SCHEER:<BR>
Bert, what's your response to Steve's take on the role of regulators in
causing/exacerbating the S&L crises?
<P>


BERT ELY:<BR>
The two S&L crises were the consequence of numerous public-policy failures. We
have identified 16 of them, nine of which pre-date 1980, when problems in the
S&L industry first surfaced. The two primary causes -- the creation of federal
deposit insurance and the transformation of S&Ls into severely mismatched
financial intermediaries (borrowing short to lend long) are rooted in the
1930s.
<P>
The first S&L crisis was the industry's interest-rate insolvency that occurred
during the early 1980s when interest rates skyrocketed. That crisis abated by
early 1983, but it left at least 500 insolvent S&Ls in its wake, many of whom,
at the encouragement of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, sold their fixed-rate
mortgages at substantial losses when interest rates were at their peak.
<P>
Because neither the Reagan Administration nor the Congress were willing to face
up to the magnitude of the cost of burying those insolvent S&Ls (I estimate $25
billion in the spring of 1983), the Bank Board left these insolvent
institutions open. Lincoln at that time was at best barely solvent, measured in
terms of its economic value. In many cases, unqualified persons acquired
control of these institutions; Charlie Keating was among the unqualified. The
Bank Board then irresponsibly permitted the managements of these institutions,
including Lincoln's Charlie Keating, to rapidly and recklessly grow them,
utilizing powers Congress has recently granted to S&Ls. So yes, the regulators
did exacerbate the S&L crisis by permitting Charlie Keating and his ilk to
acquire control of, and then to wildly grow, their increasingly insolvent S&Ls,
but the Bank Board's irresponsibility is no excuse for what Charlie did.
<P>
Steve Neal's analysis of how the regulators sank Keating does not wash. The
primary reason real estate values collapsed was because of excessive real
estate development in the 1980s, especially in the Southwest. Eventually, all
asset bubbles collapse, and real estate in the 1980s was no exception. Part of
the overexpansion of real estate was fueled by the excessive liberalization of
real estate depreciation allowances in 1981; part of this overexpansion was
financed by the rapid growth of insured deposits in insolvent and badly managed
banks and S&Ls, including Charlie's Lincoln. The 1986 Tax Reform Act further
depressed real estate values, but this legislation was a much needed reform of
the 1981 tax act; competent real estate developers (we do not include Charlie
in that category) did not get sucked in by the 1981 act and therefore did not
get sucked under by the inevitable collapse of real estate values. The
toughened regulation of S&Ls, which Congress finally enacted in 1989 after
years of dithering and denial, also was a long overdue corrective. In the
aggregate, the collapse of junk bond prices added relatively little to the
overall cost of the S&L fiasco; in any event, S&Ls had no business investing in
junk bonds in the first place. Our friend Charlie was anything but a victim of
the S&L crisis; instead, his incompetency, if not worse, finally caught up with
him. Shed no tears for Charlie.
<P>
As an S&L operator, Charlie failed for the same reason that scores of others
did, albeit on a grander scale. What is unique about Charlie, and why he should
be retried, was American Continental's sale of subordinated debt through the
offices of Lincoln S&L. Charlie, the great battler against sexual pornography,
figuratively raped those Lincoln depositors who were enticed to swap insured
deposits in Lincoln for extremely risky and uninsured subordinated debt issued
by American Continental. While a few other S&Ls and S&L holding companies sold
subordinated debt at the retail level, none went to Charlie's excess. Steve
Neal's legalisms to the contrary, what Charlie did was inexcusable; hopefully,
a court will again find that it was criminal.
<P>


STEPHEN NEAL:<BR>
Bert laces his comments with ad hominem. But he never explains how Keating
caused investor losses, let alone how he violated criminal laws.
<P>
He correctly notes that Keating invested heavily in real estate. But contrary
to Bert's implications, those investments were permitted by regulation, known
to, and approved by, regulators and disclosed to bond purchasers. He correctly
notes that real estate markets have always been cyclical. Keating knew that,
and presumably the government did too when it permitted and encouraged Lincoln
to make real estate investments. 
<P>
What Keating didn't know and couldn't have anticipated was that the government
would change the rules and seize Lincoln as soon as the real estate market
cycled down.
<P>
The government having permitted and encouraged real estate investments, it
should have allowed Lincoln and other savings and loans to hold and manage
their real estate portfolios through the downturn so that investors and
taxpayers would reap the benefits of the inevitable upturn. As we know, that
upturn was fast and dramatic in the Arizona market where Lincoln was most
heavily invested. Unfortunately, the beneficiaries of the upturn were those who
purchased seized assets from the RTC, often with incredibly favorable
financing. The losers were the investors, the taxpayers and Keating.  
<P>
Finally, Bert says savings and loans had no business investing in junk bonds.
That may be his view, although it is puzzling given the performance of the
high-yield bond market over the last decade. But the rules permitted those
investments. 
<P>
I would say equally strongly, that the government has no business using
taxpayer money to insure savings and loan deposits. But despite my view, the
government does just that. I don't presume to think that someone who runs afoul
of my philosophical or economic views should, absent something substantially
more, be subjected to the criminal sanction.
<P>


ELIZABETH CABRASER:<BR>
The government made him do it? Charles Keating, hapless cycle victim? Come on.
He sounds like the poster boy for the tort reform movement. Whatever happened
to personal responsibility, or the quaint notion of fiduciary duty? Bank
robbery is still a crime, whether it's done to a bank, or by it.
<P>
Lincoln Savings' bond scheme was not a highly-prepared Wall Street offering
made to sophisticated investors. It did not occur because tasteless, joking
employees ran amok. It did not happen because passbook savings depositors
suddenly demanded to be placed in highly risky, uninsured investments. The
branch employees didn't go berserk and neither did the depositors. The
employees did as they were told, and the depositors did as they were persuaded.
With everyone at these levels taking full responsibility for their own actions,
that still leaves a culpable party -- the person in charge. Even in a savings
and loan, the buck stops somewhere. It stops with Keating.
<P>
Americans are true believers in personal responsibility. They don't like
whiners or victims. They don't like to hear that it's everything and everybody
else's fault. As between the liar and the lied to, the latter may justifiably
have victim status. The former does not.
<P>
Again, the depositors-turned-bondholders weren't looking for risk; they were
insisting on safety. Their testimony, at the class certification and trial
stages, demonstrated that Lincoln's representatives stressed the safety of the
bonds, going so far as to state that Lincoln's and the parent company's assets
made it stronger than the government in terms of insuring the bonds. Reluctant
or confused depositors were given a hard sell unprecedented in the association
of savings institutions.  They were induced to "own a piece of Lincoln," and to
switch their trust and confidence from government insurance to Lincoln itself.
That, at the very least, is a massive undertaking of fiduciary duty -- a duty
that was then utterly disregarded by Lincoln as it engaged fully in the S&L
speculation of the day. Again, it's about responsibility. Charles Keating had
it.
<P>
I don't like ad hominems either, but it's difficult to refrain given the nature
of the misconduct and the level of audacity that characterize the Lincoln
story. And Charles Keating, whether he likes it now or not, was definitely in
charge. Being a leader involves moral and legal responsibility. Being
responsible means being accountable for decisions and conduct at every level of
the organization. The current tendency by corporations and their leaders to
avoid responsibility and seek immunity from the consequences of their actions
and their products is the most disturbing phenomenon in commerce today,
particularly in contrast to the high degree of trust and regard the public
still places in the corporation that make its products and safeguard its money. 
When a company (let's be charitable) makes a mistake, it is disconcerting at
the least to see a leader who points fingers and looks feverishly for others to
blame.
<P>
Steve Neal has my admiration and respect as an effective advocate.  I dare say
even the Lincoln bondholders could, grudgingly, admire him for his dedication
to his client.  Steve Neal is a wonderful lawyer, but Charles Keating will
never star in a remake of "It's a Wonderful Life." 
<P>
