<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Charles Keating: Scoundrel or Scapegoat? Take 2</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff LINK=#cd661d VLINK=#008b8b>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR><FONT COLOR=FF0000 SIZE=+3>COUNSEL CONNECT WEB</FONT><BR CLEAR=ALL>

</blockquote>

<center>


<h2>Charles Keating:<BR>
Scoundrel or Scapegoat?</h2></CENTER>
</center>


        <TABLE WIDTH=650 cellspacing=20>



<TR><TD WIDTH=200></TD>


<TD WIDTH=450 ALIGN=right> 
<FONT SIZE=+2>Take 2</FONT></TD></TR>

                <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN=right VALIGN=top>
               
                <P>Go to:<BR>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat.html>Introduction</A></FONT><P>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat1.html>Take 1</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat3.html>Take 3</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat4.html>Take 4</A></FONT>              
                </TD>


                

<TD WIDTH=450 ROWSPAN=8 VALIGN=top>

<FONT Size=+1>


IRA RAPHAELSON:<BR>
I agree with Ms. Cabraser when she says that Mr. Keating was no victim and had a fine lawyer. When Mr. Keating and his son were convicted by a federal jury on 1/6/93, that jury found him guilty of all 77 counts of an indictment that charged racketeering, conspiracy, bank fraud, interstate transportation of stolen property, misapplication of funds and securities fraud. The indictment charged Mr. Keating and four other officer/directors of Lincoln Savings and its parent American Continental Corp. (ACC) with engaging in a pattern of racketeering to obtain money from and through Lincoln. This activity included five alleged schemes: a scheme to create sham profits for ACC and Lincoln through fraudulent sales of undeveloped land and other assets; a scheme to sell ACC bonds through Lincoln's branch network, based in part on the sham profits; a scheme to transfer money illegally from Lincoln to ACC through an inter-company "tax sharing agreement"; a scheme to use Lincoln's money and property to bail ACC out of a costly contractual obligation; and a scheme to transfer money from ACC to the defendants and members of their families through sham loans from an ACC subsidiary while ACC was preparing to declare bankruptcy. 
<P>
During the trial, Mr. Keating took the stand in his own defense, claiming, as Mr. Neal has repeated, that he was victimized by bureaucrats and prosecutors. According to press reports after the verdict, the jury simply did not believe him. Rather, as one juror explained, "We all felt we would have liked to have one of those expanding noses that grows longer and longer.... We just didn't think any of it was valid." 
<P>
Another indication that Mr. Keating was not simply victimized is the irrefutable fact that eight defendants pled guilty. Some testified as to his intent to defraud regarding the flipping of loans for property whose value had been falsely inflated to fraudulently overstate the worth of the S&L. Judith Wischer, former ACC President and Keating's right hand, pled and so testified. Also pleading were the former CFO of ACC, a former Senior VP who was Keating's son-in-law, Lincoln's CEO and Board Chairman, two former Lincoln Presidents including one who also served as ACC VP, an ACC attorney and an Arizona land developer. These facts hardly support the notions that Mr. Keating lacked intent or was a victim in this matter.
<P>
The thrust of the Justice Department's prosecutive undertaking was not to lend credence to bad regulation or poor public policy by Congress. Rather 5,500 persons were convicted between 1988 and 1995 at a 95% conviction rate of defrauding financial institutions. The evidence presented in the Lincoln case, verified through guilty pleas by its officers and attorney was that Lincoln lied about the value of its assets to keep the piggy bank open for Mr. Keating and his associates to enrich themselves. This is not an original type of criminal activity, but it is criminal nonetheless. Those who run financial institutions with taxpayer backing have legally imposed fiduciary duties to protect those assets for the public and not to enrich themselves and their cronies or relatives.
<P>
One additional theme identified during the S&L prosecutions and in the Presidential Commission's Report on the Thrift Crisis in 1993 was that deregulation of the thrifts brought CD brokering, junk bonds and commercial real estate investment on an unprecedented scale to lending institutions that lacked the expertise to engage in any appropriate due diligence. When the investments went bad, as they were destined to do, many of those who sought to conceal their own failures as financial managers turned to "Ponzi"-like schemes to conceal the loss of book value. Resulting loan and land flips led to mounting losses and the size of the crisis simply grew.
<P>

PETER SCHEER:<BR>
Ira, please describe for us the strongest evidence the federal government had of criminal fraud by Keating personally. Also, would the government have proceeded criminally against Keating if he had not sold the high-risk bonds to depositors -- in other words, would the case have been criminal if the government, through the deposit insurance, had been the only real victim of the bank's investments?
<P>
IRA RAPHAELSON:<BR>
My original comment is not meant to suggest that merely because the DOJ convicted a lot of people that Keating was guilty as charged. The jury found him so with all deference to the Ninth Circuit, and the conviction was supported by substantial evidence of self-dealing. Nor is the mere fact that eight other officers and affiliated parties pled to the same crimes mean necessarily that Keating "knew" what he was doing was wrong. However, to suggest as Keating and his lawyer have maintained that he is victim of anything in this is to overstate the case. Mr. Keating unquestionably caused the loss of significant amounts of money to the public and to private persons. He neither was nor is entitled to keep the profits of his activity in that regard. Whether there is a retrial of the federal case or not, Mr. Keating has had his days in court. As to the federal charging decision, it is impossible to parse someone else's prosecutive decision. I can only say that on the evidence then available, I would have concurred in charging, even if the bond-sale evidence were not available.
<P>
PETER SCHEER:<BR>
Elizabeth, Steve makes the point that Keating's sale of subordinated debt to depositors of his bank was legal at the time and approved by state and federal regulators. If correct, that's a powerful argument against criminal prosecution of Keating. It's one thing to say that Keating should be civilly liable to his investors for their losses. But wasn't it a stretch for the government to prosecute him under these circumstances?
<P>
<A HREF=index.html#cabra>ELIZABETH CABRASER</A>:<BR>
Not necessarily. The sale itself might arguably have been legal and approved, but criminal conduct could still occur if the promotion and sale of the investments was conducted through a course of conduct that operated as a fraud upon investors and/or the regulatory process. As we all know, what is done and said, while perfectly legal and above board, may be rendered fraudulent -- and even criminal -- if accompanied by non-disclosure or concealment of material facts, or other fraudulent conduct.

