</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Charles Keating: Scoundrel or Scapegoat? Take 3</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff LINK=#cd661d VLINK=#008b8b>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR><FONT COLOR=FF0000 SIZE=+3>COUNSEL CONNECT WEB</FONT><BR CLEAR=ALL>

</blockquote>

<center>

<h2>Charles Keating:<BR>
Scoundrel or Scapegoat?</h2></CENTER>



        <TABLE WIDTH=650 cellspacing=20>



<TR><TD WIDTH=200></TD>


<TD WIDTH=450 ALIGN=right> 
<FONT SIZE=+2>Take 3</FONT></TD></TR>

                <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN=right VALIGN=top>
                
                <P>Go to:<BR>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat.html>Introduction</A></FONT><P>
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat1.html>Take 1</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat2.html>Take 2</A></FONT><P>           
                <FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF=keat4.html>Take 4</A></FONT>              

</TD>


                

<TD WIDTH=450 ROWSPAN=8 VALIGN=top>

<FONT Size=+1>



IRA RAPHAELSON:<BR>
The literal truth / good faith defense to federal fraud charges is absolute but not without its limitations. I agree with Ms. Cabraser's conclusion but for slightly different analytical reasons. A good faith belief in the bona fides of a venture as a whole does not justify false statements made in support of that venture. As I understand the evidence, not all statements made by the salesmen were true. Indeed, I recall some evidence that suggested that salesmen were coached to distort the distinction between ACC (uninsured) and Lincoln (insured) paper. Additionally, federal fraud law separately punishes material omissions frauds -- that is where there is a fiduciary relationship between the parties, material facts may not be concealed, even if the statements made are literally true, but materially incomplete. This is a distinct basis for criminal liability often seen in the securities arena. To the extent that the salesmen failed to inform investors that the paper sold in the lobby of a federally insured institution was not itself insured, a material omissions case may indeed be argued.
<P>
STEVE NEAL:<BR>
I appreciate Elizabeth's and Ira's nice comments about me as a lawyer. I hold them both in high esteem. But they are wrong about Keating and Lincoln.
<P>
I do agree with Elizabeth's comment about personal responsibility. Charlie Keating always has been willing to accept it. Too many others have not been so willing. 
<P>
The government not only permitted but encouraged Keating to grow Lincoln rapidly in size and to diversify its investments into real estate, hotels and other non-traditional assets. When the real estate markets dipped, Keating was prepared to work through and survive the downturn. The government wasn't.
<P>
Federal and state regulators not only permitted but encouraged the sale of ACC bonds through Lincoln branches. When government policies caused, or at a minimum aggravated, a downturn in the real estate values largely underlying those bonds, Keating was prepared to accept responsibility and make good on the bonds. But the government stripped him of his ability to do so.
<P>
Ira correctly identifies the main theories of prosecution in the federal criminal case. The overriding theory was that the reported profits of ACC and Lincoln were phony, inflated through "sham" transactions. But the only accounting witness called by prosecutors in the federal case -- no accounting witness was called by the prosecution in the state case -- testified that even with all of the evidence about supposedly "sham" transactions, she could not conclude that the profits of ACC/Lincoln were overstated by even one nickel. Despite the jury verdict, that evidence is, presumably, the reason why the Ninth Circuit has ruled that the evidence of guilt was "not overwhelming." Whether that court would ultimately rule that the evidence was sufficient to support the verdict may never be known unless the prosecutors appeal the new trial order. 
<P>
The second main theme of the federal case involved what Ira, and the prosecutors themselves, characterized as "illegal" tax-sharing payments from Lincoln to ACC. The problem with that theory, despite the jury verdict, is that the supposedly "illegal" payments were made pursuant to, and in exact conformance with, an explicit, written tax-sharing agreement between Lincoln and ACC that was approved and signed by federal regulators. The federal regulators later termed their approval a mistake. But rather than accept responsibility for their mistake, those regulators encouraged that tax-sharing agreement to become a cornerstone in the prosecution of Keating, who had complied fully with the terms of the agreement.
<P>
PETER SCHEER:<BR>
Steve, you seem to be saying that the government, having induced S&Ls to expand into risky real estate and junk bond investments in the mid-80s, should have refrained from taking over the insolvent thrifts, and selling off those assets, in the late 1980s. That's easy to say with 20-20 hindsight; we know that those assets eventually recovered in value. But in 1988 and 1989 that was not a sure thing. The government was facing a huge and exponentially growing liability to insured depositors. Surely, it is appropriate for the government to take action to stem those losses. It isn't required to "time" the market perfectly.
<P>
STEPHEN NEAL:<BR>
Whether, regardless of deregulation, it was appropriate for the government to take action to stem losses, the answer in the abstract must be yes. But in reality, the "losses" here were short-term market downturns -- like those that happen all the time in the stock market. When the government deregulated, it knew savings and loans would be investing in somewhat volatile assets. It should have had a sounder plan than to panic at the first downturn, seize assets, mark them down to market and then dump them. The contrast between the handling of savings and loans on the one hand and commercial banks with large real estate portfolios on the other hand is most instructive. In the latter case, the bank regulators -- a different crew than the savings and loan regulators -- did not seize institutions, aggressively mark down the value of their assets and then fire-sell those assets. Instead the regulators showed forbearance and patience while waiting for the inevitable upturn, even though its magnitude and timing they could not predict with precision.
<P>
Charlie Keating was and remains willing to accept responsibility for his own acts. But he should not have been subjected to unconstitutional imprisonment because of irrational and erratic conduct by people over whom he had no control.

<HR WIDTH=25%>
<DT>Go to:</DT></FONT>
