<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Practive Directories</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><HR><H3 ALIGN=CENTER><font color=FF0000><I>American Lawyer</I> Practice Directory Listings</font></H3><HR><TABLE WIDTH=550 border=0><TR><TD valign=top width=150><UL><PRE></PRE><B><P><LI><A HREF="95ATFolder/">Antitrust</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95CLFolder/">Commercial Litigation</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95CSFFolder/">Corporate Securities</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95ENVFolder/">Environmental</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95ERIFolder/">ERISA</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95IPFolder/">Intellectual Property</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="intfolder/">International Practice</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95LABFolder/">Labor</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95PLFolder/">Product Liability</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95WCCFolder/">White Collar Crime</A></P><P><LI><A HREF="95WOFolder/">Workout</A></P></B></UL></TD><TD valign=top width=400><H4 align=center>What's A Practice Directory?</H4><font size=-1><P>The American Lawyer's 1995-1996 Practice Directory series, now in its fifthyear of publication, covers legal practices ranging from Antitrust toWorkouts and Restructuring.  </P><P>The Directories are being provided to corporations and others that needlawyers at firms engaged in the areas listed on the previous page.  Theirpurpose is not so much to encourage a prospective client to scroll throughto choose a lawyer, as it is to help provide quick, convenient informationabout a practice group that a prospective client might have already heardabout or that he or she might otherwise want to include in a short list ofpossible choices for a given matter.</P><P>The practice profiles in these Directories were paid for and provided byeach firm.  However, American Lawyer also implemented the followingrestrictions for each profile:</P><P>First, each firm had to submit its profile in a specified format to insurethat the profile would be as informative as possible yet be free of "hype."</P><P>Second, each firm had to be willing to provide back-up information to ourstaff to support any general claim made in the profile.</P><P>Third, each firm had to be willing to avoid describing all clients andengagements so generally as to make the description of its work of littlevalue to those using the Directories.  Thus, we often required firms torewrite their profiles; and, in some cases, we rejected profiles. Moreover, each firm had to provide the names of three or more specificclients in the profile itself.  Or, if the firm did not want to publish thenames, we required that it at least provide the three names to our staff sothat we could verify the firm's experience with these clients beforepublishing its profile.</P><P>Fourth, to guard against inflation of a firm's stated presence in an area,we required that any individual lawyer listed in the profile as engaged inthe practice area have specific experience in that area.</P><P>Forcing all of these requirements on our paying customers was at times abit awkward.  But in the end most of them agreed that the process resultedin Directories that will be credible and, therefore, truly useful to you asyou continue to choose counsel in these increasingly important practiceareas.</P></td></tr></table></body></html>
