<HtML>
<title>Counsel Connect Web: "Squishing Rupert Like A Bug"</title>
<BODY bgcolor=ffffff text="000000" link="000080" vlink="ff0000">


<img align=left src="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif"> 
 <blockquote>
<font color=ff0000 size=+2>"Squishing Rupert Like A Bug"</font>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


October 11, 1996<P>
<BLOCKQUUOTE><PRE>

ANTITRUST
MERGERS & ACQUISITIONS
COMMUNICATIONS

[Editor's Note: Rupert Murdoch's Fox News Network challenged the
Time Warner-TBS merger, claiming the deal will restrict cable
programming sales. Fox alleges that Time Warner reneged on an
agreement to carry its new 24-hour news channel, claiming damages
of $250 million to be trebled under antitrust law.]


UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
EASTERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK

--------------------------------------------------------

FOX NEWS NETWORK, L.L.C.,

Plaintiff,

- against -

TIME WARNER INC., TIME WARNER
ENTERTAINMENT COMPANY, L.P., TURNER
BROADCASTING SYSTEM, INC., and
R.E. "TED" TURNER III,

Defendants.

--------------------------------------------------------


CIV. NO.

COMPLAINT


NATURE OF THE ACTION

          1.   Plaintiff Fox News Network, L.L.C. ("Fox
News") brings this action to enjoin permanently the
proposed merger of Time Warner Inc. ("Time Warner") and
Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.  ("Turner Broadcasting").
The merger agreement is a blueprint for the monopolization
of cable television by two cable television giants.  The
merger violates both federal and New York antitrust laws
because it enhances Time Warner's ability and incentive to
abuse its stranglehold over cable television systems to
favor programming in which it has a financial stake, and
thereby reduces competition in the sale of cable
programming in general and all-news cable programming in
particular.  In fact, Time Warner, Turner Broadcasting and
its chairman, R.E. "Ted" Turner, did not even wait until
the proposed merger closed to enter into arrangements that
restrain trade.  As discussed below, prior to the closing,
Turner Broadcasting and Ted Turner entered into an illegal
agreement with Time Warner to deny a competitor of Turner
Broadcasting's CNN -- the Fox News Channel -- access to
viewers served by Time Warner cable systems.  Until the
merger closes, Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting are
legally required to operate separately.  It is a violation
of Section 1 of the Sherman Act for Time Warner, Turner
Broadcasting and Ted Turner to conspire to restrain trade
together in this fashion.

          2.   Fox News launched the Fox News Channel, an
all-news cable programming service, on Monday, October 7,
1996.  The Fox News Channel premiered on cable systems
servicing approximately 17 million subscribers.  Because of
the illegal agreement to restrain trade among Time Warner,
Turner Broadcasting and Turner, Time Warner reneged on
commitments it previously made to Fox News to carry the Fox
News Channel.  Fox News seeks treble damages from Time
Warner, Turner Broadcasting and Ted Turner for the injuries
Fox News has suffered as a result of this illegal
agreement.  Fox News has sustained or will sustain damages
in excess of $250 million.  Under the antitrust laws, such
damages should be trebled for an award of no less than $750
million.  Time Warner's fraudulent misrepresentations
concerning its willingness to carry the Fox News Channel,
and its refusal to live up to the contract it negotiated
with Fox News, also entitle Fox News to recover damages.
Fox News also is entitled to an award of punitive damages
in connection with the fraud perpetrated upon it by Time
Warner to deter such nefarious conduct in the future.  Fox
News asks for an award of one billion dollars in punitive
damages.

          3.   On numerous occasions, Time Warner has
excluded from Time Warner's cable systems, programming
services that competed against programming services in
which Time Warner has an economic interest.  Time Warner
has thus exploited its position as one of the nation's
largest operators of cable television systems, to protect
from competition, cable programming services in which it
has an interest.

          4.   For some time prior to the proposed
acquisition of Turner Broadcasting, Time Warner held an
approximate 20 percent interest in Turner Broadcasting and
thus had a minority interest in CNN, CNNfn and the other
programming services now owned by Turner Broadcasting.  As
demonstrated below, Time Warner has sought to enhance the
value of that 20 percent interest by protecting Turner
Broadcasting programming services from competition from
unaffiliated programmers.

          5.   Time Warner now seeks to acquire the
remaining 80 percent of Turner Broadcasting it does not yet
own.  Ted Turner candidly bragged that the principals to
the transaction hope to use it to suppress competition,
when he responded to questions from reporters after the
proposed Time Warner-Turner Broadcasting merger was
announced.  When Turner was asked about reports that Rupert
Murdoch, Chairman of Fox News's ultimate corporate parent,
The News Corporation Limited ("News Corp."), had indicated
that Fox News intended to start a 24-hour cable news
station to compete against CNN, Turner stated that:


Time Warner is three times as big as News Corp. We're
looking forward to squishing Rupert like a bug.


          6.   Turner's remarks make clear that Turner
Broadcasting and Time Warner are seeking to "squish" the
Fox News Channel not by competing against it on a level
playing field -- by delivering a better product or charging
a lower price -- but by abusing Time Warner's stranglehold
over cable systems to prevent the Fox News Channel from
gaining widespread carriage.  In fact, Turner has expressed
delight with Time Warner's decision not to honor its
agreement to carry the Fox News Channel and the adverse
impact he expects that Time Warner's decision will have on
Fox News.  He recently went so far as to make a public
announcement that in light of the pending merger between
Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting, he advises investors
to "short" the stock of News Corp.  The extent of Turner's
antipathy toward Murdoch was also shown when, upon learning
that Murdoch had complained about Time Warner's breach of
its agreement to carry the Fox News Channel, Turner
compared Murdoch to the "late Fuhrer," Adolf Hitler.

          7.   Turner will have a continuing interest after
the merger in exploiting Time Warner's market power to
stifle competition against CNN and other Turner programming
services.  After the merger, Turner will be Time Warner's
largest voting stockholder and has been promised control
over Time Warner cable business as Time Warner's Vice
Chairman and first "Cable Czar".

          8.   Because of the likely anticompetitive
effects of the merger of Time Warner and Turner
Broadcasting, the Federal Trade Commission ("FTC")
concluded that the merger would violate Section 7 of the
Clayton Act.  The FTC announced that it would sue to block
the transaction unless the merging parties agreed to a
proposed consent order.  The proposed consent order is now
subject to public comment as required by 15 U.S.C. Sec. 45,
16 CFR Sec. 2.34, but the parties to the merger have
announced that they will not wait until the end of the
comment period to close the transaction.

          9.   The FTC's proposed complaint specifically
alleges that the merger will substantially lessen
competition by increasing Time Warner's direct financial
incentives "as the post-acquisition owner of the Turner
Cable Television Programming Services not to carry other
Cable Television Programming Services that directly compete
with the Turner Cable Television Programming Services."  In
a public statement made on the day the FTC announced the
complaint, FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky singled out the
effect of the merger in reducing competition among all-news
channels.  Chairman Pitofsky referred to CNN as holding a
"monopoly position" and characterized the merger as
"rais[ing] a threat of entrenching the monopoly position of
CNN."  The FTC also issued an "analysis" of the proposed
consent order that highlighted the reduction of competition
in the market for cable news channels by warning that "Time
Warner's acquisition of CNN gives it both the ability and
incentive to make entry of competing news services more
difficult, by denying them access to its extensive
distribution system."

          10.  Between June and sometime in August 1996,
executives at the highest levels of Time Warner and News
Corporation agreed that Time Warner would carry the Fox
News Channel on Time Warner cable systems.  Time Warner and
Fox News reached agreement on the carriage terms.  Under
that agreement, Fox News was to make an up-front payment to
Time Warner in excess of $100 million and Time Warner
obligated itself to offer the Fox News Channel to 90
percent of Time Warner's cable subscribers by 2001.  In
mid-July, Robert Wright, CEO of NBC, publicly announced
that he had been told that Time Warner had concluded an
agreement to carry the Fox News Channel on its cable
systems.

          11.  On information and belief: Ted Turner
discussed various issues concerning programming on Time
Warner cable systems with Time Warner representatives on or
prior to August 30, 1996, including at a meeting with
Gerald Levin at Turner's Montana ranch in late August,
1996; at some point in that period, Turner asked Time
Warner to agree not to carry the Fox News Channel on Time
Warner cable systems and Time Warner agreed.  Not content
to wait until Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting merged to
abuse Time Warner's cable power as a means of suppressing
competition from the Fox News Channel, Turner has solicited
Time Warner's agreement not to carry the Fox News Channel.
On September 24, 1996, The Los Angeles Times quoted
"[s]ources close to Turner [who] say he changed Time
Warner's direction on the deal because he feared it would
give Fox the lead by next year over MSNBC."

          12.  As noted above, the FTC concluded that the
merger, if closed, "would result in a violation of Section
7 of the Clayton Act."  This action by Fox News is needed
because, notwithstanding the substantial lessening of
competition noted by the FTC, the FTC has apparently
decided not to bring suit to enjoin the merger.  Instead,
the FTC has preliminarily settled on a "remedy" which
demonstrably does not prevent the serious and far-ranging
anticompetitive effects that will result from this
transaction.  Only permanent injunctive relief will prevent
substantial injury to competition, to Fox News and to the
public.


JURISDICTION AND VENUE

          13.  This complaint is instituted under Sections
4 and 16 of the Clayton Act, to obtain injunctive relief
and damages for violations of Section 7 of the Clayton Act
and Section 1 of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. Secs. 15, 18,
and 26; 15 U.S.C. Sec. 1.  The complaint also seeks
injunctive relief and damages resulting from defendants'
violations of the Donnelly Antitrust Act, New York Gen.
Bus. Law Sec. 340, et seq., and New York common law.  This
Court has jurisdiction over the federal antitrust law
claims pursuant to 15 U.S.C. Secs. 4, 16 and 28 U.S.C. Sec.
1337.  The state law claims arise out of the same operative
facts as the federal antitrust claims. Accordingly, this
Court has supplemental jurisdiction over the state law
claims. See 28 U.S.C. Sec. 1367.

          14.  This Court has personal jurisdiction over
the corporate defendants because each of the corporate
defendants has consented (by registering with the State of
New York to do business), transacts business, resides,
maintains an office, has agents, or is found in this
District or the State of New York. See 15 U.S.C. Sec. 22.
This Court has personal jurisdiction over defendant Ted
Turner because he transacts business, both related and
unrelated to the causes of action set forth herein, in New
York, has committed tortious acts within New York, has
committed tortious acts outside New York causing injury
within New York, and has purposefully availed himself of
the benefits of the laws and commerce of New York.  See
C.P.L.R. Sec. 302 (McKinney's 1995).

          15.  Venue is proper in this district because
each of the defendants transacts business, resides,
maintains an office, has agents or is found in this
district, and the acts complained of arose, in part, in
this district, and have had a substantial anticompetitive
effect in this district.


THE PARTIES

Fox News

          16.  Plaintiff Fox News is a limited liability
corporation organized under the laws of the State of
Delaware with its broadcast studios, corporate offices and
principal place of business located at 1211 Avenue of the
Americas, New York, New York.  As of the date of filing of
this Complaint, Fox News employs approximately 700 people,
600 of whom are in New York. Once the Fox News Channel
becomes fully established, it is anticipated that the
number of persons Fox News employs will increase to
approximately 1,500, with much of that increase involving
jobs in New York City.  News Corp. or its affiliates have
made substantial capital and other investments in
connection with launching the Fox News Channel.


Time Warner

          17.  Defendant Time Warner Inc. is a corporation
organized under the laws of the State of Delaware.  Its
headquarters and principal place of business are located at
75 Rockefeller Plaza, New York, New York.  Time Warner,
together with its corporate affiliates and subsidiaries, is
the largest producer of cable television programming
services in the United States. Time Warner's cable
television programming services include, among others, Home
Box Office ("HBO", which is the single largest programming
service), as well as Cinemax, Court TV, E! Entertainment
Television and Comedy Central.  In 1995, Time Warner's
revenues from all programming services were approximately
$1.5 billion.

          18.  Time Warner, together with its corporate
affiliates and subsidiaries, also is the nation's second
largest operator of cable television systems.  Time Warner
and its affiliates currently provide cable service to
approximately 11.5 million subscribers, or 17% of all
households in the United States that subscribe to cable
television.  Time Warner and its affiliates hold cable
franchises in numerous municipalities and governmental
units throughout the country, including in Manhattan,
Queens, Staten Island and portions of Brooklyn.  In every
territory where Time Warner has a cable franchise, its
cable systems are monopolies.  In fact, Time Warner has
boasted that it has maximized the value of its cable
systems by "clustering" its cable franchises in contiguous
geographic areas in order to insulate itself further from
competition.

          19.  Time Warner's cable systems in New York City
enhance its influence over cable programming across the
country.  That influence arises from the fact that many of
the persons deciding which cable programming services they
will support with advertising dollars live or work in New
York City and receive their primary first-hand exposure
only to the programming services Time Warner elects to
carry on its New York City cable systems.

          20.  In 1995, Time Warner's revenues from cable
system operations were approximately $3.25 billion.


Time Warner Entertainment

          21.  Defendant Time Warner Entertainment, L.P.,
("Time Warner Entertainment") is a Delaware Limited
Partnership.  Time Warner owns 74.49 percent, and U.S. West
owns 21.51 percent, of Time Warner Entertainment.  Time
Warner Entertainment owns and operates the cable
programming services in which Time Warner has an interest
and also has interests in Time Warner's cable systems.
(For ease of reference, Time Warner Entertainment is
sometimes referred to below collectively with Time Warner
Inc. as "Time Warner.")


Turner Broadcasting

          22.  Defendant Turner Broadcasting is a
corporation organized under the laws of the State of
Georgia, with its headquarters and principal place of
business located at One CNN Center, Atlanta, Georgia 30348.
Turner Broadcasting is the nation's third largest producer
of cable television programming services.  Its programming
services include, among others, the all- news CNN, Headline
News, the TBS Superstation, the Cartoon Network, Turner
Classic Movies, and CNN Financial Network.  According to
the FTC, CNN is viewed by cable system operators as a
"crown jewel" programming service -- a service essential to
attract and retain cable television subscribers.


Ted Turner

          23.  Defendant Ted Turner is the Chairman of
Turner Broadcasting.  Upon information and belief, Ted
Turner is a citizen of the State of Georgia who does
significant business in New York City.


TRADE AND COMMERCE

          24.  At all times relevant, defendants Time
Warner, Time Warner Entertainment, Turner Broadcasting, and
Ted Turner were engaged in commerce as commerce is defined
in Section 1 of the Sherman Act, as amended, 15 U.S.C. Sec.
1.


THE MERGER AND ITS ANTICOMPETITIVE EFFECTS

          25.  On or about September 22, 1995, Time Warner
and Turner Broadcasting entered into an agreement (the
"Merger Agreement") pursuant to which Time Warner would
acquire the approximately 80% of the outstanding shares of
Turner Broadcasting that it did not already own.  At the
time the Merger Agreement was executed, the market value of
the transaction was approximately $6.7 billion.

          26.  Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting are the
first and third largest producers of cable programming.
Accordingly, post-merger Time Warner will control more than
40% of the cable television programming market, including
several "crown jewels," such as HBO and CNN.

          27.  As a result of the far-reaching horizontal
and vertical combinations caused by the merger, Time Warner
will have the clear market power and strong economic
incentives to lessen competition substantially.  Time
Warner will have a direct financial incentive, as the post-
acquisition owner of Turner Broadcasting's programming, not
to carry any programming that directly competes with
programming already offered by Turner Broadcasting.

          28.  The inevitable result of these economic
realities is that Time Warner will foreclose -- as it has
done in the past and is doing today -- the launch and
distribution of unaffiliated cable programming.

          29.  With its monopoly stranglehold over 17
percent of the nation's cable subscribers, Time Warner can
refuse to carry existing cable television services that
compete with Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting
programming.  With control over the key New York City
market, Time Warner also can prevent the launch of
potentially successful new cable programming.  In short,
following the acquisition, Time Warner will have the power,
the incentive and, as has been demonstrated, the will to
squelch any and all serious competition with the
programming offered by Time Warner.


TIME WARNER'S RECORD OF ANTICOMPETITIVE BEHAVIOR

          30.  Time Warner's prior record of
anticompetitive behavior only increases the likelihood that
it will exploit the power gained from its acquisition of
Turner Broadcasting to foreclose entry by competing
providers into the cable programming market.

          31.  Historically, Time Warner has taken steps to
stifle competition with programming services in which it
has an interest.  For example, Time Warner refused to
provide channel space on its cable television systems to
movie networks such as Viacom's Showtime, which competed
against Time Warner's HBO and Cinemax services.  Competing
programmers such as Viacom were forced to bring suit to
force Time Warner to open its cable systems to them.  Only
after litigation did Time Warner agree to give Showtime
access to Time Warner systems.  In fact, Time Warner
ultimately did so as part of a settlement agreement that
required Time Warner to pay tens of millions of dollars to
Viacom for having kept Showtime off its system so long.
Likewise, Time Warner refused to carry the Bravo movie
channel on its cable systems until a federal District Court
Judge ordered it to do so in litigation brought by a
citizens group.

          32.  More recently, Time Warner has announced
that it will drop the Classic Sports Network -- a
programming service in which it has no financial interest
-- from many of its cable systems to make room for a
competing Time Warner network.  The Classic Sports Network
gained enormous popularity during the short time it was
carried on Time Warner systems. Nevertheless, Time Warner
has announced that it will replace Classic Sports with
CNN-SI, a new joint venture between the Turner
Broadcasting's CNN and Time Warner's "Sports Illustrated."

          33.  Finally, the foreclosure of Fox News from
Time Warner's distribution network was foreshadowed by Time
Warner's refusal to carry the fX channel.  News Corp.
launched fX in 1994 to bring viewers a fresh mix of live
and classic programming.  The fX channel has proven
successful and has achieved ratings that surpass the
ratings for many channels on Time Warner's cable systems.
Nevertheless, Time Warner -- which controls the cable
systems serving the vast majority of New York City cable
subscribers -- has refused to carry fX, or its subsequently
launched affiliate, fXM.  Richard Aurelio, President of
Time Warner's New York City cable systems, recently stated
that the Time Warner systems did not have the capacity to
carry all available cable programming services.  But Time
Warner's systems have capacity for Time Warner products
like CNNfn and CNN-SI.  Time Warner uses its cable
distribution system to offer its own programming services
and to block others that pose competitive threats.  After
the merger closes, Time Warner will have sufficient channel
space to find room for approximately 14 programming
services in which it has an economic interest.


FOX NEWS'S EFFORT TO OBTAIN CARRIAGE OF THE FOX NEWS
CHANNEL ON TIME WARNER CABLE SYSTEMS

          34.  When Time Warner's proposed acquisition of
Turner Broadcasting was announced, Turner's CNN had no
serious competition in the market for all-news cable
programming.  Nevertheless, CNN was vulnerable to strong
competition.  Because much of CNN's profitability was based
on its unique position as the only programmer providing
24-hour news service, even a small dip in its viewing
audience could significantly erode its profits.

          35.  In January 1996, Fox News officially
announced its plan to compete with CNN by creating the Fox
News Channel, a 24-hour-a-day, professionally produced,
high-quality worldwide cable television service consisting
entirely of national and international news.  To this end,
Fox News hired as President of the Fox News Channel Roger
Ailes, a veteran cable programming executive who had
launched and run two other cable programming services.

          36.  According to news reports, Ted Turner had
this to say when asked about reports that Rupert Murdoch
had announced the launch of the Fox News Channel as a new
competitor to Turner's CNN:   Time Warner is three times as
big as News Corporation.  We re looking forward to
squishing Rupert like a bug.   Thus, according to Ted
Turner, CNN would not eliminate the Fox News Channel by
competing on a level playing field. Rather, CNN would rely
on Turner Broadcasting's impending marriage to Time Warner
and Time Warner's stranglehold on cable television systems
to combat the Fox News Channel.


FOX NEWS'S CARRIAGE AGREEMENT WITH TIME WARNER

          37.  Because the Fox News Channel's success in
the market for all-news cable programming depends on its
ability to secure widespread distribution, Fox News entered
into negotiations with numerous cable television system
operators to obtain carriage agreements. Because of Time
Warner's dominant position as a distributor of programming
and the special influence it exercises over the ability of
cable programming services to attract advertising by virtue
of the strategic importance of Time Warner's New York City
cable television systems, Fox News negotiated and sought to
reach a carriage agreement with Time Warner for the Fox
News Channel.

          38.  In or about June 1996, Rupert Murdoch and
Chase Carey, Chairman and Chief Executive of Fox
Television, met with Time Warner's Gerald Levin and Richard
Parsons to discuss, among other things, the possibility
that Time Warner would carry the Fox News Channel
nationwide.  During this meeting, it was emphasized to
Levin and Parsons that Fox News placed significant
importance on the carriage of the Fox News Channel on Time
Warner's cable television systems throughout the United
States and in New York City in particular.

          39.  Following this discussion, and at Levin's
suggestion, Carey called Joe Collins, a Time Warner senior
executive, to schedule a meeting at which the parties could
discuss a carriage agreement further, as Fox News planned
an October 7, 1996 launch date for the Fox News Channel.
Collins stated that the discussions should include Fred
Dressler, the vice president of programming for Time
Warner's cable systems.

          40.  In or about July 1996, Carey and Ailes had
meetings with Dressler and Collins to outline the terms of
a proposed carriage agreement. Dressler and Collins
confirmed to Carey and Ailes that the terms of Fox News's
proposal provided the basis for negotiating a deal.

          41.  Fox News representatives then drafted a
letter agreement outlining the terms of a carriage
agreement and delivered it to Time Warner representatives
on or about July 18, 1996. Levin personally represented to
Murdoch that Fox News's proposal was acceptable to Time
Warner and that the parties should proceed to finalize an
agreement.  At or about that same time, Robert Wright, CEO
of NBC, announced publicly that he had been told that Time
Warner had concluded a carriage agreement with Fox News.

          42.  Several days later, Richard Aurelio
confirmed that Time Warner and Fox News had been
negotiating and that it was  inevitable  that Time Warner
would "do a deal" with Fox News.  This public statement was
consistent with Time Warner representatives  private
comments to Fox News's representatives throughout this
period.

          43.  Shortly thereafter, Fox News representatives
met several times with Dressler to present and discuss a
draft cable television affiliation agreement.  At one of
those meetings, Dressler expressed appreciation for the
speed with which Fox News had prepared the agreement, and
for the agreement's thoroughness.  During this period,
Dressler represented that closing the deal with Fox News
was Time Warner's second highest priority -- second only to
obtaining FTC approval for its proposed acquisition of
Turner Broadcasting.  The parties exchanged several drafts
of the carriage agreement.  Throughout this process,
Dressler repeatedly assured Fox News that the parties "had
a deal."


TED TURNER'S EFFORTS TO SECURE TIME WARNER'S AGREEMENT NOT
TO PROCEED WITH THE TIME WARNER-FOX NEWS CARRIAGE AGREEMENT

          44.  On information and belief: by late August,
Turner discussed with Time Warner representatives the
pending agreement for Time Warner to carry the Fox News
Channel; Turner and Time Warner management agreed that Time
Warner would reverse course and renege on Time Warner's
done deal  with Fox News to carry the Fox News Channel;
Turner and Time Warner reached this understanding for no
other reason than to stifle competition from the Fox News
Channel.  According to subsequent reports,  [s]ources close
to Turner say he changed Time Warner's direction on the
[Fox News Channel] deal because he feared it would give Fox
[News] the lead by next year over MSNBC."  Time Warner said
nothing to Fox News regarding the secret Time Warner
agreement with Turner Broadcasting and Ted Turner.

          45.  On or about August 30, 1996, Fox News
presented Time Warner with an agreement containing all of
the material terms to which the parties had agreed.  At
that time, Dressler told Fox News representatives that Time
Warner's attorneys had advised it to postpone signing the
parties' carriage agreement so as not to jeopardize the
FTC's review of Time Warner's proposed acquisition of
Turner Broadcasting.  At the same time, Dressler repeated
his representation that Time Warner and Fox News had a
"done deal" with respect to the Fox News Channel.


THE FTC'S ANALYSIS OF THE MERGER

          46.  During much of the time that Time Warner was
assuring Fox News that the Fox News Channel would be
carried on Time Warner systems, Time Warner was negotiating
to obtain the FTC's acquiescence in its proposed
acquisition of Turner Broadcasting.

          47.  On September 12, 1996, the FTC issued a
draft Complaint charging that the merger, would, if
consummated, violate Section 7 of the Clayton Act.  The FTC
charged that the effect of the merger, "if consummated, may
be substantially to lessen competition in the relevant
lines of commerce in the relevant sections of the country
in violation of Section 7 of the Clayton Act,  by, among
other things,  enabling . . . Time Warner to increase
prices on its Cable Television Programming Services sold to
MVPDs [Multichannel Video Program Distributors, such as
cable system operators] by raising barriers to entry by new
competitors or to repositioning by existing competitors, by
preventing such rivals from achieving sufficient
distribution to realize economies of scale.

          48.  According to the FTC, anticompetitive
effects will likely result from the proposed merger
because:


-- . . . Time Warner has direct financial incentives as the
post-acquisition owner of the Turner Cable Television
Programming Services not to carry other Cable Television
Programming Services that directly compete with the Turner
Cable Television Programming Services. . .


          49.  In a separate analysis accompanying the
draft complaint, the FTC summarized its core allegations as
follows:


[T]he acquisition, along with related transactions, would
allow Time Warner unilaterally to raise the prices of cable
television programming and would limit the ability of cable
television systems that buy such programming to take
responsive action to avoid such price increases.  It would
do so . . . both through horizontal combination in the
market for cable programming (in which Time Warner, after
the acquisition, would control about 40% of the market) and
through higher entry barriers into that market as a result
of the vertical integration (by merger and contract)
between Turner's programming interests and Time Warner's
and TCI's cable distribution interests.


          50.  According to Chairman Pitofsky and
Commissioners Steiger and Varney, the Commission received
evidence that these foreclosure threats were real and
substantial.  There was clearly reason to believe that this
acquisition would increase the incentives to engage in this
foreclosure without remedial action.

          51.  The FTC noted that the vertical foreclosure
problems raised by the proposed merger were particularly
troublesome in the market for all-news programming, where
CNN held what Chairman Pitofsky called a "monopoly
position."  According to the FTC:


Of the types of programming in which the post-merger Time
Warner will have a leading position, the one with the
fewest existing close substitutes is the all-news segment,
in which CNN is by far the most significant player.  There
are actual or potential entrants that could in the future
erode CNN's market power, but their ability to do so is
partly dependent on their ability to secure widespread
distribution.  Without access to Time Warner's extensive
cable holdings, such new entry may not be successful.  Time
Warner's acquisition of CNN gives it both the ability and
incentive to make entry of competing news services more
difficult, by denying them access to its extensive
distribution system.


          52.  Chairman Pitofsky highlighted this likely
anticompetitive effect on September 12, 1996, when he said
that  [w]hat we are saying was that now that CNN, which
dominates cable news, is owned by somebody [Time Warner]
who has something like 17% or more of the cable subscribers
in the country, that raises a threat of entrenching the
monopoly position of CNN.

          53.  Notwithstanding these substantial
anticompetitive effects, the FTC preliminarily decided not
to file suit to enjoin the proposed merger's consummation.
Rather, the FTC entered into a proposed  Agreement
Containing Consent Order  ("proposed consent order") with
the merging parties that was issued for public comment on
September 26, 1996. The public comment period will not
expire until on or about November 22, 1996.  The FTC's
proposed consent order would provide only limited and
ineffective relief from the anticompetitive effects of the
merger.  As a result, Fox News was forced to bring this
lawsuit.

          54.  For example, to remedy the anticompetitive
effect of Time Warner's post-merger ability and incentive
to block the entry of a competing all-news service,
Paragraph IX of the proposed consent order would require
Time Warner to place a news channel on certain of its cable
systems at specified roll-out and market penetration rates.
Specifically, if Time Warner chooses to fulfill Paragraph
IX by increasing carriage for an existing channel, it must
achieve penetration of 50% of total basic subscribers by
July 30, 1999.  Alternatively, if Time Warner seeks to
fulfill this provision by carrying a channel not currently
carried by Time Warner, it must achieve penetration of 50%
of total basic subscribers by July 30, 2001.  In short,
Paragraph IX's remedy  is to allow Time Warner to establish
a duopoly in all-news programming on Time Warner cable
systems reaching just 50% of its subscribers, and to enjoy
a CNN monopoly in the other 50%.


Time Warner's Carriage of MSNBC

          55.  Shortly after the FTC issued its complaint
and proposed consent order, Time Warner advised Fox News
for the first time that it would not honor its agreement to
carry the Fox News Channel.  Time Warner told Fox News that
it had decided to carry the mixed format MSNBC as its sole
"all-news" alternative to CNN.  Further, Time Warner
maintained that MSNBC satisfied the requirements for being
an all-news service in Paragraph IX of the proposed consent
order.

          56.  MSNBC does not meet the requirements in
Paragraph IX, because it is not a "24-hour per day service
consisting of current national, international, sports,
financial and weather news and/or information, and other
similar programming."  In fact, MSNBC itself claimed that
it is not an all-news service when it was arguing with
cable systems over whether MSNBC could utilize carriage
rights granted to its predecessor, America's Talking. Even
after MSNBC premiered, its management described it in ways
that make clear that it is not a true competitor of CNN and
fails to meet the requirements of Paragraph IX of the
proposed consent order:  Andrew Lack, NBC News President,
described criticism of MSNBC's failure to provide
programming similar to CNN as "stupid" because "I said
since day one that we are not going to do CNN."

          57.  Time Warner's agreement to carry MSNBC
exposes the insufficiency of the proposed consent order to
remedy the harms to competition identified by the FTC.  The
proposed consent order requires only that Time Warner
distribute a single all-news alternative on Time Warner
cable systems reaching 50 percent of Time Warner's
subscribers by July 30, 1999, abandoning the remaining 50
percent to an all-news monopoly.  On information and
belief, Time Warner misled the FTC by representing that
Time Warner could only offer 50 percent of its viewers a
competing all-news channel by that date.  In fact, the
proposed consent order requires Time Warner to provide a
second all-news channel to fewer cable subscribers than
required by the Time Warner-Fox News agreement.

          58.  Time Warner's plan to allow MSNBC to reach
3.5 million Time Warner subscribers by July 1, 1997 leaves
50 percent fewer Time Warner subscribers able to enjoy a
second all-news channel as of that date than the agreement
with Fox News would require. Similarly, Time Warner's plan
to allow MSNBC to reach 5.75 million Time Warner
subscribers by July 30, 1999 affords the benefits of a
second all-news channel to 60 percent fewer subscribers as
of that date than the agreement with Fox News would
require.  In short, by reneging on the agreement to carry
the Fox News Channel, Time Warner will insulate CNN from
meaningful competition.

          59.  Significantly, when Murdoch expressed
disappointment over Time Warner's breach of its agreement
to carry the Fox News Channel, Ted Turner launched another
intemperate attack on Murdoch.  Specifically, Turner
compared Murdoch to the "late Fuhrer" and described
journalists who work for Murdoch as "yellow journalists."
Turner also claimed that Murdoch's global media holdings
are "like Germany in 1942 with black lines across Europe."
According to Turner, the merged entity of Time Warner and
Turner is "like 1944, and the Americans are coming in."
Turner's offensive and absurd analogy and Time Warner's
steadfast refusal to carry the Fox News Channel reveal the
true motivation behind the proposed Time Warner-Turner
merger -- to use the market power of the post-merger Time
Warner to further foreclose legitimate and robust
competition from Fox News and other competitors.  As noted
above, Turner evidently anticipates that he will be able to
abuse Time Warner's vertically integrated monopoly power to
follow through on his threat to "squish" News Corporation
and Fox News:  He recently recommended that investors
"short" News Corp.'s stock.


TIME WARNER'S CONTINUING REFUSAL TO PROVIDE THE FOX NEWS
CHANNEL TO NEW YORK CITY SUBSCRIBERS

          60.  Time Warner's anticompetitive intent is
reconfirmed by its refusal even to consider the City of New
York's recent request for permission to carry the Fox News
Channel on one of the five municipal-access cable channels
the City controls.  Even though Time Warner would incur no
costs in connection with the City's proposal, it has
rejected the City's request due to its desire to keep the
Fox News Channel out of New York and thereby to prevent the
Fox News Channel from reaching Time Warner's 1.1 million
New York City subscribers.  As Time Warner knows,
distribution to this market of subscribers is critical to
the Fox News Channel's ability to succeed.


RELEVANT MARKETS

          61.  There are three product markets that are
relevant to this action: (a) the market for the sale of all
cable television programs to multi-channel video
programming distributors, which enables MVPDs to purchase
cable television programming from producers such as Fox
News, Time Warner and Turner Broadcasting and, in turn, to
retransmit those programs to subscribers in their systems;
(b) the market for the sale of all-news cable programming
to MVPDs, in which MVPDs purchase all-news cable
programming for retransmission to subscribers in their
systems; and (c) the market for the sale of multiple
channels of video programming services to households (the
"MVPD market").

          62.  The cable television programming services
market is relevant because over- the-air broadcast
television, video cassette rentals, and other forms of news
and entertainment do not have a sufficient price
constraining effect on the sales of cable television
programming services to MVPDs.

          63.  The all-news cable programming services
market is relevant because the demand for such programs is
highly inelastic.  All-news cable programming is unique in
that it provides comprehensive and up-to-the-minute
reporting of domestic and international news, sports,
business and weather, supplemented with in-depth reports,
analysis and commentary. Because of the unique content and
features of all-news cable shows, MVPD customers do not
view other types of cable programming as suitable
substitutes for all-news cable programming.  In determining
the mix of cable programming to distribute to their
customers, therefore, MVPDs have a particular and distinct
demand for all-news cable programming, and do not view
other types of cable programming as suitable substitutes
for such all-news programming.

          64.  The geographic dimensions of the relevant
markets in this action are as follows:  (a) the United
States for the cable television programming and all-news
cable programming markets; and (b) the geographic area
encompassed within each governmentally awarded cable
television franchise for the MVPD market.

          65.  The local areas in which MVPDs retransmit
cable television programming are relevant markets because
MVPDs provide cable programming to subscribers within
franchise territories defined by state or local
governmental entities.  Accordingly, MVPD customers
typically purchase their cable programming services
exclusively from the MVPD franchised in the defined
territories in which the customers live.  MVPDs in one
defined franchise territory do not compete with MVPDs in
another defined franchise territory.  Moreover, the same
MVPD operating in different franchise territories may
purchase different cable programming for distribution in
each separate territory for distribution to their separate
groupings of customers. Each state or locally-drawn
franchise territory, therefore, is a relevant geographic
market.


COUNT I
FOR VIOLATION OF SECTION 7 OF THE CLAYTON ACT, 15 U.S.C.
Sec. 18 AGAINST ALL DEFENDANTS

          66.  Fox News repeats and realleges each and
every allegation contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 with
the same force and effect as if fully set forth herein.

          67.  The effect of the merger of Time Warner and
Turner Broadcasting may be substantially to lessen
competition in interstate trade and commerce in violation
of Section 7 of the Clayton Act, U.S.C. Sec. 18, in the
following ways, among others: It will decrease competition
in the cable television programming market and the all-news
cable television programming market by providing the
combined Time Warner-Turner Broadcasting entity with the
ability and the incentives to exploit Time Warner's power
in the MVPD and programming markets to restrict access to
cable television subscribers by providers of cable
programming services and thereby redound to the detriment
of not only Fox News and other vendors of cable programming
services, but also consumers of cable television.  To
eliminate these anticompetitive effects, the merger should
be permanently enjoined.


COUNT II
(FOR VIOLATION OF SECTION 1 OF THE SHERMAN ACT AGAINST ALL
DEFENDANTS)

            68.  Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
complaint with the same force and effect as if fully set
forth herein.

            69.  The agreement between Ted Turner, Turner
Broadcasting and Time Warner that Time Warner would not
carry the Fox News Channel is an unlawful combination and
conspiracy in restraint of trade and thus constitutes a
violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. Sec.
1.

            70.  As a direct and proximate result of this
unlawful combination and conspiracy, interstate commerce
has been and will be restrained and impeded in the
following respects, among others: (a) substantial barriers
to entry into, and participation in, the markets for cable
television programming services and for all-news cable
television programming services will be erected and
maintained in the relevant markets; and (b) the Fox News
Channel will be restrained and prevented from competing
effectively with CNN.

            71.  Cable television subscribers have been and
will continue to be adversely affected as a result of this
unlawful combination and conspiracy.

            72.  By reason of the unlawful combination and
conspiracy described in this Count, Fox News has sustained
or will sustain damages in the amount of at least
$250,000,000 prior to trebling.

            73.  As a result of the continuing nature of
the unlawful combination and conspiracy described in this
Count, Fox News has suffered and will continue to suffer,
unless the activities complained of are enjoined, immediate
and irreparable injury and damage to its business,
including loss of business, goodwill and revenue, for which
Fox News is without an adequate remedy at law.


COUNT III
(FOR VIOLATION OF THE DONNELLY ACT - CONSPIRACY AGAINST ALL
DEFENDANTS)

            74.  Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
complaint with the same force and effect as if fully set
forth herein.

            75.  The effect of the merger of Time Warner
and Turner Broadcasting may be substantially to lessen
competition in interstate and intrastate trade and commerce
in violation of the Donnelly Act, New York General Business
Law Sec. 340, et seq., in the following ways, among others:
It will decrease competition in the cable television
programming market and the all-news cable television
programming market services by providing the combined Time
Warner-Turner Broadcasting with the ability and incentive
to exploit Time Warner's power in the MVPD and programming
markets to restrict access to other cable television
programming services or other all-news cable television
programming services that compete with Time Warner and
Turner Broadcasting cable television programming services.

            76.  Cable television subscribers have been and
will continue to be adversely affected as a result of the
unlawful combination and conspiracy described in this
Count.

            77.  By reason of the unlawful combination and
conspiracy described in this Count, Fox News has sustained
or will sustain damages in the amount of at least
$250,000,000 prior to trebling.

            78.  As a result of the continuing nature of
the unlawful combination and conspiracy described in this
Count, Fox News has suffered and will continue to suffer,
unless the activities complained of are enjoined, immediate
and irreparable injury and damage to its business,
including loss of business, goodwill and revenue, for which
Fox News is without an adequate remedy at law.


COUNT IV
(FOR VIOLATION OF THE DONNELLY ACT - CONSPIRACY AGAINST ALL
DEFENDANTS)

            79.  Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
complaint with the same force and effect as if fully set
forth herein.

            80.  The agreement between Ted Turner, Turner
Broadcasting and Time Warner that Time Warner would not
carry the Fox News Channel is an unlawful combination and
conspiracy in restraint of trade in violation of the
Donnelly Act, New York General Business Law Sec. 340, et
seq.

            81.  As a direct and proximate result of this
unlawful combination and conspiracy, interstate commerce
has been and will be restrained and impeded in the
following respects, among others: (a) substantial barriers
to entry into, and participation in, the markets for cable
television programming services and for all-news cable
television programming services will be erected and
maintained in the relevant markets; and (b) the Fox News
Channel will be restrained and prevented from competing
effectively with CNN.

            82.  Cable television subscribers have been and
will continue to be adversely affected as a result of the
unlawful combination and conspiracy described in this
Count.

            83.  By reason of the unlawful combination and
conspiracy described in this Count, Fox News has sustained
or will sustain damages in the amount of at least
$250,000,000 prior to trebling.

            84.  As a result of the continuing nature of
the unlawful combination and conspiracy described in this
Count, Fox News has suffered and will continue to suffer,
unless the activities complained of are enjoined, immediate
and irreparable injury and damage to its business,
including loss of business, goodwill and revenue, for which
Fox News is without an adequate remedy at law.


COUNT V
(FOR FRAUD AGAINST TIME WARNER, INC. AND TIME WARNER
ENTERTAINMENT COMPANY, L.P.)

            85.  Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
complaint with the same force and effect as if fully set
forth herein.

            86.  During June, July and August 1996, as
described above in paragraphs 37 through 45 of the
complaint, Time Warner representatives made a series of
representations to Fox News representatives that Fox
intended to carry the Fox News Channel on its cable
television systems and intended to sign a written carriage
agreement with Fox News to carry the Fox News Channel.

            87.  Upon information and belief, the Time
Warner representatives knew or should have known that Time
Warner would not live up to these representations.

            88.  Upon information and belief, at some point
in July or August 1996, Time Warner representatives agreed
with Turner and Turner Broadcasting that Time Warner would
not carry the Fox News Channel; Time Warner reached that
decision pursuant to an agreement with Turner and Turner
Broadcasting.

            89.  On information and belief, the Time Warner
representations described above that Time Warner was going
to carry the Fox News Channel were false at the time they
were made.

            90.  On information and belief, Time Warner and
its agents made such representations to Fox News and its
agents to induce Fox News to rely on those representations.
In particular, Time Warner hoped to hinder Fox News'
ability to compete with CNN by lulling Fox News into a
false belief that Fox News would be carried on Time
Warner's systems.

            91.  The falsity of these representations was
unknown to Fox News at the time they were made.  Fox News
substantially and reasonably relied to its detriment on
Time Warner's promise to carry the Fox News Channel on Time
Warner's cable television systems.  By advising Fox News
just three weeks prior to its planned launch date for the
Fox News Channel that it would not perform its agreement
and carry the Fox News Channel, Time Warner has made it
impossible for Fox News to achieve the widespread
distribution of the Fox News Channel in New York City and
in other areas that were important to Fox News's launch
strategy.  If Fox News knew that Time Warner did not intend
to carry the Fox News Channel on its cable television
systems, which are monopolies in every one of their
franchise areas, including those in New York City, Fox News
would have pursued more aggressively contracts with other
cable system operators to secure desired distribution
levels at the launch date.

            92.  As a result of the false representations
and Fox News's reliance on them, Fox News has sustained or
will sustain damages in an amount to be determined more
precisely at trial, but believed to be at least
$250,000,000.

            93.  The false representations were made
willfully with malicious intent to defraud Fox News.
Accordingly, Fox News is entitled to an award of punitive
damages.  Fox News seeks a punitive damages award of one
billion dollars.


COUNT VI
(FOR BREACH OF CONTRACT AGAINST TIME WARNER INC. AND TIME
WARNER ENTERTAINMENT COMPANY, L.P.)

            94.  Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
Complaint as if fully set forth herein.

            95.  By August 30, 1996, Fox News and Time
Warner entered into an agreement whereby Time Warner would
carry the Fox News Channel on its cable television
operating systems beginning on or about October 7, 1996.

            96.  But for Time Warner's breach of their
agreement, Fox News was ready to perform all of its
obligations under its agreement with Time Warner.

            97.  By virtue of Time Warner's conduct as
described in paragraphs 1 through 65 hereinabove, Time
Warner breached the parties' agreement.

            98.  As a result of Time Warner's breach of the
agreement to carry the Fox News Channel, Fox News has
suffered an injury that is not compensable by money
damages.

            99.  Fox News contracted for and was assured
repeatedly that it would receive access to the Time Warner
cable television operating systems.

            100. Accordingly, Fox News is entitled to
specific performance requiring Time Warner to honor its
agreement with Fox News.


COUNT VII
(PROMISSORY ESTOPPEL AGAINST TIME WARNER INC. AND TIME
WARNER ENTERTAINMENT COMPANY, L.P.)

            101. Fox News repeats and realleges the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 65 of this
Complaint as if fully set forth herein.

            102. After Time Warner and Fox News reached an
agreement pursuant to which Time Warner would carry the Fox
News Channel on its nationwide cable television systems,
Time Warner executives repeatedly promised Fox News that
Time Warner would sign an agreement containing the agreed
upon terms and would carry the Fox News Channel on its
cable television systems.

            103. Time Warner's representations were made by
several senior executives. Accordingly, Fox News reasonably
relied upon Time Warner's promise to sign the agreement and
carry the Fox News Channel on its cable television systems.

            104.  Fox News advised Time Warner that it
believed that carriage on Time Warner's cable television
systems was vital to the success of the launch of the Fox
News Channel.  Moreover, Time Warner, by virtue of its
leading role as both a cable television system operator and
cable television programmer, knew that obtaining widespread
distribution of a new programming service is crucial to
that service's success.  Accordingly, Time Warner knew that
Fox News would rely on Time Warner's promise to carry the
Fox News Channel on Time Warner's cable television systems.

            105. Fox News substantially and reasonably
relied to its detriment on Time Warner's promise to carry
the Fox News Channel on Time Warner's cable television
systems. By advising Fox News just three weeks prior to its
planned launch date for the Fox News Channel that it would
not perform its agreement and carry the Fox News Channel,
Time Warner has made it impossible for Fox News to achieve
the widespread distribution of the Fox News Channel in New
York City and in other areas that were important to Fox
News's launch strategy.  If Fox News knew that Time Warner
did not intend to carry the Fox News Channel on its cable
television systems, which are monopolies in every one of
their franchise areas, including those in New York City,
Fox News would have pursued more aggressively contracts
with other cable system operators to secure desired
distribution levels at the launch date.

            106. As a result of Time Warner's breach of its
promise to carry the Fox News Channel on its cable
television systems, Fox News has suffered an injury that is
not compensable by money damages.

            107. Accordingly, Fox News is entitled to
specific performance requiring Time Warner to honor its
promise to execute the agreement to carry the Fox News
Channel on its cable television systems.

             WHEREFORE, Fox News asks for the following
relief:

            A.   A prompt trial on the merits.

            B.   Expedited discovery.

            C.   A judgment that the proposed merger
violates federal and state antitrust laws.

            D.   A judgment that Time Warner, Turner
Broadcasting, and Ted Turner have violated federal and
state antitrust laws.

            E.   On Counts I through IV,  (1) an injunction
preventing the consummation of the proposed merger or, (2)
if the merger is finalized prior to relief, an injunction
causing divestiture by Time Warner of Turner, and (3) such
other relief as the Court deems just and proper.

            F.   On Counts I through IV, an award to Fox
News of relief including damages sustained in an amount to
be more precisely determined at trial, but of at least $250
million, to be trebled according to the law, plus interest,
reasonable attorneys' fees, and costs of suit, as provided
in Sections 4 and 16 of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. Secs. 15
and 26, and in the Donnelly Antitrust Act, New York Gen.
Bus. Law Sec. 340(5).

            G.   A judgment against Time Warner ordering
specific performance of Time Warner's promise to carry the
Fox News Channel on its cable television systems.

            H.   On Counts V, VI and VII, a judgment
awarding to Fox News damages in an amount to be more
precisely determined at trial, but of at least $250
million.

            I.   On Count V, a judgment awarding to Fox
News punitive damages of at least one billion dollars.

Dated: New York, New York

October 9, 1996

