<img align=left src="http://www.counsel.com/images/lcc.gif"> 
 <blockquote>
<font color=ff0000 size=+2>Perot Fights Debate Snub</font>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


October 8, 1996<P>
<BLOCKQUUOTE><PRE>
GOVERNMENT

[Editor's Note: Seeking inclusion in the presidential debates,
the Perot campaign offers the following theory of the Commission
on Presidential Debates' interpretation of federal campaign
regulation:

"First, given the undisputed facts, it is clear that the
Commission on Presidential Debates ("CPD") has not followed the
requirement of 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.13 to apply only objective
criteria. Second, the regulation is, in any event, ultra vires.
Third, the regulation on its face and as applied is void for
vagueness and an impermissible delegation of standardless
discretion to a private actor, or the CPD is itself a state actor
and has violated the Constitution.]


IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA

ROSS PEROT, PAT CHOATE, and
PEROT '96, INC.,

Plaintiffs,

vs.

FEDERAL ELECTION COMMISSION,
and the COMMISSION ON
PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES,

Defendants.

Civ. No. 96-02196 (TFH)

PLAINTIFFS' MEMORANDUM IN OPPOSITION TO DEFENDANTS'
MOTIONS TO DISMISS AND REPLY MEMORANDUM IN SUPPORT
OF PLAINTIFFS' MOTION FOR TEMPORARY RESTRAINING
ORDER AND PRELIMINARY INJUNCTIVE RELIEF


I. INTRODUCTION

Plaintiffs seek this Court's assistance in vindicating
their legal right to a selection process for the 1996
presidential debates in which objective criteria are
lawfully applied and constitutional requirements are met.
In seeking to safeguard these rights, plaintiffs' intention
is not to prevent presidential debates from occurring;
rather. plaintiffs seek to ensure that debate selection
processes are fair and impartial so that when debates are
held they are consistent with the principles upon which our
democracy was founded. Adherence to these principles will
not make the debates unwieldy or uninteresting, as
defendants claim. In fact, if debate participants are
selected consistent with legal requirements, no more than
two additional presidential candidates would be added.

There is no doubt that this Court has subject matter
jurisdiction over plaintiffs' claims under either 28 U.S.C.
Sec. 1331 or 2 U.S.C. Sec. 437g of the Federal Election
Campaign Act ("FECA"). The ultimate role of the federal
judiciary is to hear constitutional claims, and defendants
can make no persuasive arguments that this Court does not
have jurisdiction over plaintiffs' constitutional claims as
well as over the ancillary nonconstitutional claims. In
addition, the statutory grant under FECA confers
jurisdiction on this Court without exhaustion of
administrative remedies because plaintiffs' claims are
constitutional or purely legal, and the administrative
process is both unnecessary, for no factual investigation
is required and because it will prevent the vindication of
plaintiffs' rights.

With respect to plaintiffs' substantive claims, plaintiffs
have demonstrated that injunctive relief is appropriate on
three independent bases. First, given the undisputed facts,
it is clear that the Commission on Presidential Debates
("CPD") has not followed the requirement of 11 C.F.R. Sec.
110.13 to apply only objective criteria. Second, the
regulation is, in any event, ultra vires. Third, the
regulation on its face and as applied is void for vagueness
and an impermissible delegation of standardless discretion
to a private actor, or the CPD is itself a state actor and
has violated the Constitution. Without injunctive relief,
plaintiffs will be irreparably harmed, and the relief
requested by plaintiffs threatens no harm whatsoever to the
debates, but rather promises to enrich and broaden our
public discourse.


II. THIS COURT HAS JURISDICTION OVER THIS CASE

The Supreme Court as well as this Court have clearly stated
that exhaustion of administrative remedies, even if
statutorily mandated, cannot and should not be absolutely
required in every case. McKart v. United States, 395 U.S.
185 (1969); Dorn's Transp., Inc. v. I.A.M. Nat'l Pension
Funds, 578 F.2d 1222 (D.D.C. 1984), aff'd, 753 F.2d 166
(D.C. Cir. 1985). Courts have not hesitated to rule that
they have subject matter jurisdiction to provide relief to
litigants who have not exhausted administrative remedies
under the FECA, as well as the National Labor Relations Act
("NLRA") -- the statute from which the administrative
procedures of FECA were modeled -- and many other statutes
with elaborate administrative schemes to resolve disputes.
Dolbeare v. F.E.C., No. 81 Civ. 4468-CLB, slip op.
(S.D.N.Y. March 9, 1982) (attached hereto at Tab 1) (court
did not require exhaustion where plaintiff raised ultra
vires and constitutional claims regarding the FECA).
Indeed, federal courts have virtually uniformly held that
exhaustion is unnecessary when a colorable constitutional
claim is brought, particularly when the administrative
process can provide no effective remedy. See McCarthy v.
Madigan, 503 U.S. 140, 148 (1992); Dorn's, 578 F.2d at
1226. In those instances, courts have also taken
jurisdiction over ancillary nonconstitutional claims.
Dolbeare, supra, at 16.

Defendants ask this Court to create a jurisdictional rule
clearly at odds with this precedent. The extreme theory
advanced by defendants here is that no federal court has
jurisdiction to redress egregious violations of election
laws, unless they first yield to the primary authority of
the Federal Election Commission ("FEC"). Even if the action
of the FEC or the CPD is blatantly unconstitutional and
unlawful, and regardless of how severe the impact on the
presidential election, defendants contend that no immediate
private right of action is available, but rather that any
possible jurisdiction under 2 U.S.C. Sec. 437g(a)(8) must
follow at least a 120-day waiting period. In short,
defendants submit that the CPD can take any action it wants
with regard to the presidential and vice- presidential
debates -- no matter how contrary to the law and the public
interest -- and elude the nettlesome gaze of the federal
courts.1/

As demonstrated below, defendants' theory that there are no
exceptions to statutorily-mandated exhaustion for
administrative processes, such as that contained in the
FECA, is clearly wrong. This case is precisely of the type
in which federal courts have excused compliance with
administrative remedies because it involves constitutional
questions, and resort to the administrative process would
be futile because plaintiffs' rights cannot be vindicated
there. Moreover, agency expertise will not advance
resolution of the issues presented here. In addition, the
administrative processes contained in the FECA are not
designed to cover constitutional claims in which the
complaint is against the FEC itself or the CPD acting as a
government entity or in a public function, particularly
when a constitutional issue is raised. Finally, even if
jurisdiction is not conferred under the FECA, this Court
has jurisdiction over the constitutional claims and
ancillary nonconstitutional claims under 28 U.S.C. Sec. 1331.


A. Federal Courts Recognize Exceptions to
Statutorily-Mandated Exhaustion

The Supreme Court in numerous cases has established the
principle that statutorily-mandated exhaustion should not
always be required. The Supreme Court and lower federal
courts have long recognized that exceptions to the
exhaustion requirement exist when administrative remedies
are inadequate, and that these exceptions can extend to
cases involving statutes that set up a carefully crafted
administrative process that generally should be pursued
first.

In McKart, petitioner failed to appeal an administrative
decision by his draft board, and was faced with the
argument that his key defense to a criminal charge was
unavailable because he did not exhaust administrative
remedies, as provided by statute. The Court noted that
"[p]erhaps the most common application of the exhaustion
doctrine is in cases where the relevant statute provided
that certain administrative procedures shall be exclusive."
McKart, 395 U.S. at 193. It further noted that exhaustion
is required, among other reasons, when the rights of the
complaining party can be vindicated in the administrative
process.

Notwithstanding the statutory process for administrative
exhaustion and the formidable list of policies served by
exhaustion described in the opinion, the Court in McKart
excused petitioner from the exhaustion requirement and
reached the merits of his lawsuit. In part, to be sure,
this holding rested on the fact that the case was a
criminal one, but the Court also stressed that the issue
before it was "solely one of statutory interpretation" that
"does not require any particular expertise on the part of
the [selective service] appeal board ...." Id. at 197-98.
In that respect, this case was judged "different from many
Selective Service classification questions" that involve
the need for expertise of the agency. Id. at 198.

McKart is only one of the Supreme Court decisions
recognizing that in cases involving statutes setting up an
exclusive agency process justice would not be served by
hewing formalistically to a requirement of initial
administrative exhaustion. In Coit Indep. Joint Venture v.
Federal Savings & Loan Ins. Corp., 489 U.S. 561 (1989), a
federal savings and loan association's claims were
dismissed below on the theory that a statute granted the
FSLIC exclusive jurisdiction. The Supreme Court reversed.
Coit's exhaustion discussion starts with broad language
about how "exhaustion of administrative remedies is
required where Congress imposed an exhaustion requirement
by statute," citing cases also cited by defendants. Id. at
579; Weinberger v. Salfi, 422 U.S. 749, 766 (1975); Myers
v. Bethlehem Shipbuilding Corp., 303 U.S. 41, 50-51 (1938).
Yet, later in the opinion, Coit states the-
well-established, critical corollary proposition:
"[a]dministrative remedies that are inadequate need not be
exhausted." Coit,  489 U.S. at 587 (citing Greene v. United
States, 376 U.S. 149,163 (1964) and Smith v. Illinois Bell
Tel. Co., 270 U.S.587, 591-92 (1926)). In Coit, the Court
reached the judgment that exhaustion would not be required
because there was a "lack of a reasonable time limit in the
current administrative claims procedure" confronting the
savings and loan association. The Court observed:


First, it [the current administrative claims procedure]
allows FSLIC to delay the administrative processing of
claims indefinitely, denying a litigant its day in court,
while the statute of limitations runs.


Id.

In Mccarthy, 503 U.S.140 (1992), the district court
dismissed a federal prisoner's Bivenstype damage action for
failure to exhaust administrative procedures before the
U.S. Bureau of Prisons. These procedures were established
by agency regulation, and in that sense this case does not
precisely involve a statutorily-mandated agency process.
Nevertheless, it was plain that the agency expected
prisoners to bring their complaints about prison conditions
to the prison officials first, and only thereafter to the
court. Once again, the Supreme Court started its exhaustion
discussion with the broad language that "[w]here Congress
specifically mandates, exhaustion is required." Id. at 144
(citing Coit, 489 U.S. at 579 and Patsy v. Board of Regents
of Florida, 457 U.S. 496, 502 n.4 (1982)). But the Court
then proceeded to employ judicial discretion to assess
whether exhaustion should be required. After turning to
McKart's discussion of ,exhaustion policies, McCarthy
elaborated situations in which exhaustion requirements have
given way to the individual interests in judicial relief:
"[r]equiring resort to the administrative remedy may
occasion undue prejudice to subsequent assertions of a
court action. Such prejudice may result, for example, from
an unreasonable or indefinite timeframe for administrative
action." Id. at 146-47.

In Bowen v. City of New York, 476 U.S. 467 (1986), the
Supreme Court again did not require exhaustion of
statutorily-required administrative remedies. In Bowen,
individuals who were denied social security disability
benefits, or whose benefits were terminated, brought a
class action. Even though certain class claimants had not
exhausted an elaborate statutory mechanism for
administrative decision-making prior to judicial review,
these claims were allowed to proceed without exhaustion of
the agency process. Relying heavily on Mathews v. Eldridge,
424 U.S. 319 (1976), the Court reasoned that as long as a
claim for benefits was presented to the Secretary, the
administrative remedies prescribed by the Secretary may not
be required to be exhausted "where a claimant's interest in
having a particular issue resolved promptly is so great
that deference to the agency's judgment is inappropriate."
Bowen, 476 U.S. at 483 (citing Mathews, 424 U.S. at 330).
As in Mathews, the Court also notes that exhaustion was
unnecessary when the constitutional challenge is "entirely
collateral" to the substantive claim under the
administrative scheme and the plaintiff stands to suffer
irreparable harm if forced to exhaust his administrative
remedies. In short, the Supreme Court has established that
statutorily-based exhaustion requirements are not absolute
and that principled exceptions exist and should be applied
in appropriate circumstances.

This Supreme Court precedent has been followed under the
FECA as well as other federal statutes with similar
statutorily-mandate administrative processes. In Dolbeare,
plaintiffs challenged certain actions of the FEC as ultra
vires and unconstitutional, and defendant sought to dismiss
the action. Because plaintiffs had not exhausted
administrative remedies, defendant argued that the court
lacked subject matter jurisdiction over the claim. The
court did not require exhaustion, stating:


Plaintiffs, however, have no administrative remedy for
these claims. They must wait, and suffer in silence, until
the FEC eventually decides that it has completed its
investigation, and makes a "probable cause" finding, if its
does. Until that time, plaintiffs and their contributors
can be subjected to endless discovery and delay by the FEC,
without being able to determine the scope or facts of the
FEC's investigation. Since there is no appropriate
administrative remedy, there can be no claim that
exhaustion is required.


Dolbeare, supra, at 18. See NCPAC v. F.E.C., 626 F.2d 953
(D.C. Cir. 1980).

The reasoning in Dolbeare tracks that of the Supreme Court
in Leedom v. Kyme, 358 U.S. 184 (1958), which interprets
the exhaustion requirements of the NLRA. As explained by
the Court in In Re Carter-Mondale Reelection Comm., Inc. v.
F.E.C., 642 F.2d 538, 545 n.9 (D.C. Cir. 1980), the
exclusive jurisdiction provision in the FECA was modeled on
that of the NLRA. The Court in Leedom upheld the original
district court jurisdiction without requiring exhaustion of
the administrative review provisions of the NLRA, because
the claim in that case was that the Board had acted in
excess of its power. See also Elm City Broadcasting Corp.
v. N.L.R.B., 123 F. Supp. 838 (D. Conn 1954).2/


B. The Exceptions To The Exhaustion Doctrine Apply In This
Case

This case is precisely of the type in which exhaustion of
administrative remedies is not required.3/ First, because
the case involves serious constitutional claims, exhaustion
of administrative remedies is ordinarily not appropriate.
Second. requiring exhaustion of administrative remedies
would be futile as the FEC has taken the position it cannot
resolve plaintiffs' claims prior to the election, much less
prior to any debates. Third, resort to the agency is not
needed to resolve factual issues because the claims here
are purely legal. Fourth, the interests of the plaintiffs
in receiving prompt judicial attention outweigh other
institutional interests which might favor exhaustion.
Fifth, not requiring exhaustion in this unusual case will
not open a floodgate of election law litigation in the
federal courts.


1. Statutorily-mandated exhaustion is ordinarily not
required for constitutional claims.

As noted by the Supreme Court in Califano v. Sanders, 430
U.S. 99, 109 (1977), "when constitutional questions are in
issue, the availability of judicial review is presumed." As
a result, exhaustion of administrative remedies is
ordinarily not required when a constitutional claim is
brought. McCarthy, 503 U.S. at 148.

In Dorn's, 578 F. Supp. at 1222, this Court granted
judicial review of the constitutionality of a statutory
provision prior to the exhaustion of the mandated
administrative remedy of arbitration. The court noted that
where the "complaint poses a facial challenge to the
constitutionality of the Act, the purpose of exhaustion
doctrine would not be served by its application." Id. at
1226. The court noted that "purely constitutional questions
generally are thought beyond the ambit of administrative
proceeding." Id. at 1227; see Blitz, 538 F. Supp. at 1124
(citing Oestereich v. Selective Syc. Local  Bd., 393 U.S.
233 (1968) (Harlan, J., concurring)). The court need not
decide that the constitutional claims are meritorious to
take jurisdiction over them. Rather, the court must accept
jurisdiction over the constitutional claims unless it is
immaterial and alleged solely as a means of obtaining
federal jurisdiction, or is wholly insubstantial and
frivolous. Bell v. Hood, 327 U.S. 678, 683 (1946).

Defendants rely upon Daly v. Costle, 661 F.2d 959, 963
(D.C. Cir. 1981) to argue that the administrative process
can provide plaintiffs with a remedy, and therefore
plaintiffs must exhaust their administrative remedies
before bringing their constitutional claims before this
Court. But Daly provides that allegations of constitutional
deprivation will only change exhaustion analysis "so long
as effective remediation" of plaintiffs problem could be
achieved in the administrative process. Id. As explained
below, since the administrative process cannot be concluded
until after the election, an administrative determination
after the election that Perot and Choate should have been
included in the debates would hardly provide an effective
remedy for them. Accordingly, there is no basis for
requiring an exhaustion of the administrative process for
plaintiffs' constitutional claims.

Once the Court has jurisdiction over the constitutional
questions raised by plaintiffs, it also acquires
jurisdiction over plaintiffs' other causes of action, even
though the Court would not independently have jurisdiction
over those other claims standing alone. See, Dolbeare,
supra at 16.

The existence of a constitutional claim has been cited as
grounds for jurisdiction, even where an "exclusive" remedy
was delegated to a governmental agency. In an action where
plaintiff sought to enjoin an election mandated by the
National Labor Relations Board ("NLRB") so that he
(plaintiff) would have an opportunity to participate in the
election, Chief Judge Learned Hand of the United States
Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit ruled:


The first question is as to the jurisdiction of the
District Court which the defendant disputes, invoking our
decision in Fitzgerald v. Douds. We there held that, since
the only review of a "certification" proceeding under Sec. 9
was an incident to a petition to review an order of the
Board under Sec. 10, the remedy created was exclusive;
although we recognized that the result might be otherwise,
if a constitutional question were raised. The plaintiff at
bar does raise such a question; .... If this assertion of
constitutional right is not transparently frivolous. it
gave the District Court jurisdiction: and. having once
acquired jurisdiction. the court might. and should. dispose
of all other questions which arose. even though they would
not have been independently justiciable.


Fay v. Douds, 172 F.2d 720, 723 (2d Cir. 1949) (emphasis
added) (citing Township of Hillsborough v. Cromwell, 326
U.S. 620, 629 (1945)). The assertion of a constitutional
claim does not automatically create jurisdiction over all
other claims -- "[t]here must also be the necessity for
equitable relief." Elm City, 123 F. Supp. at 840.

In the present case, the necessity for equitable relief is
apparent -- if plaintiffs are required to exhaust their
administrative remedies prior to commencing their claims in
this Court, they will suffer irreparable harm. Accordingly,
it is proper for this Court, which clearly has jurisdiction
over plaintiffs' constitutional claims, also to consider
"all other questions which arose, even though they would
not have been independently justiciable." Fay, 172 F.2d at
723.


2. Exhaustion of administrative remedies would clearly be
futile in this case.

The debates are scheduled to commence shortly, and the
general election will occur on November 5, 1996, just 36
days from the date of this filing. In this instance, where
the two-party-controlled CPD excludes a third-party
candidate who secured 19 percent of the popular vote in
1992 and has qualified for $29 million in federal election
funds, the Court's mandate is to consider the very special
circumstances of this case in determining whether
plaintiffs must essentially forfeit their claims on the
altar of the exhaustion doctrine.4/ McCarthy, 503 U.S. at
147 ("Even where the administrative decision making
schedule is otherwise reasonable and definite, a particular
plaintiff may suffer irreparable harm if unable to secure
immediate judicial consideration of his claim."): Dorn's,
578 F. Supp. at 1226 ("[T]he exhaustion requirement must be
evaluated in light of the circumstances presented by each
case.").

When forced to exhaust administrative remedies, a litigant
ordinarily has his day in court delayed and suffers the
financial costs of pursuing an independent litigation track
before reaching the federal courts. Candidates Perot and
Choate, however, face the prospect of losing their claimed
right to participate in the debates entirely,5/ and
becoming holders of what the defendants derisively call
"generalized grievances," which they would then presumably
argue do not provide standing for plaintiffs to allege
them.

This "catch-22" of administrative procedure is not what the
exhaustion doctrine is designed to accomplish. While the
additional inconvenience and expense of fully pursuing an
administrative remedy would in no way provide sufficient
grounds to avoid exhaustion, an impending injury -- such as
the complete loss of adequate relief -- can necessitate
that relief be granted prior to the time that the harm can
be undone. As the Supreme Court has clearly established:
"[a]dministrative remedies that are inadequate need not be
exhausted." Coit, 489 U.S. at 587 (citations omitted).


3. Resort to agency processes is not needed to develop a
factual record as purely legal issues are presented here.

In some instances, the administrative record developed by
an agency proceeding is essential to a federal court being
able to adequately assess matters which are within the
everyday expertise of the agency. In this instance, though,
the facts are all undisputed and a matter of the public
record, and there appear to be no difficult or technical
issues that should lead the Court to feel ill-equipped to
handle this matter. Where the claims are purely legal, this
Court has previously held that the purpose of honoring the
exhaustion requirement -- avoidance of "premature
interference with the administrative process"-- would not
be served. Dorn's, 578 F. Supp. at 1226; Farquhar v.
F.D.A., 616 F. Supp. 190, 193 (D.D.C. 1985).


4. Plaintiffs' interest in prompt resolution outweighs the
interest of requiring agency review prior to court review

The present case presents a situation "where a claimant's
interest in having a particular issue resolved promptly is
so great that deference to the agency's judgment is
inappropriate." Bowen, 476 U.S. at 483. A prompt resolution
of this issue offers the only possible remedy for
plaintiffs. Delaying review (and resolution) of this issue
will only cause irreparable and serious injury, justifying
an exception to the exhaustion doctrine. Rafeedie v.
I.N.S., 880 F.2d 506, 518 (D.C. Cir. 1989).

In McCarthy, the Supreme Court counsels that the
determination of whether to relieve a litigant of her
exhaustion burden should be part of an "intensely
practical" balancing test between the interests of the
individual in receiving prompt judicial attention and the
countervailing institutional interests which favor
exhaustion. McCarthy, 503 U.S. at 146. The Court's
recognition that the importance or significance of
plaintiffs' need for a judicial hearing can outweigh the
efficiencies furnished by exhaustion are directly
applicable to the plight of Perot and Choate. The Court
held that:


Administrative remedies need not be pursued if the
litigant's interests in immediate judicial review outweigh
the government's interests in the efficiency or
administrative autonomy that the exhaustion doctrine is
designed to further.


McCarthy, 503 U.S. at 146 (citing West v. Bergland, 611
F.2d 710, 715 (8th Cir. 1979), cert. denied, 449 U.S. 821
( 1980)).6/ Given the irreparable harm to plaintiff of
requiring exhaustion and the fact that the FEC
administrative process cannot contribute to resolution of
this dispute, an exception to exhaustion requirements is
clearly warranted here.


5. Not requiring exhaustion will not open the floodgates of
election law litigation in the federal courts.

The exception to exhaustion that is being advanced in this
case is a narrow one, and allowing this case to proceed
without futile exhaustion of administrative remedies will
not, as the FEC suggests, open a floodgate of election law
litigation in the federal courts that would ordinarily
remain at the agency because of jurisdictional and
procedural requirements. FEC's Motion to Dismiss, at 8-9.
The plaintiffs' action is more than unique. involving the
highly-charged arena of presidential debates, and the
conduct of an entity acting under the regulatory direction
of the FEC itself. In particular, one must contrast this
case with the ordinary election law case in which one
private party sues another for arguable lack of compliance
with the election law. First, plaintiffs have sued the FEC
a public agency, for lack of compliance with governing
regulations, statutes and constitutional principles.
Second, although plaintiffs also sued the CPD, the focus of
those claims relates to the CPD's performance of a
governmental or public function. There is thus a sharp
distinction between this lawsuit and the garden variety
suit subject to administrative procedures between two
campaign organizations or when the FEC is enforcing the
Act. Moreover, the Supreme Court's McCarthy decision
expressly authorizes courts to consider the importance and
nature of a particular litigant's claim and the particular
administrative procedure provided. McCarthy, 503 U.S. at
146. There is no reason to believe that using this
balancing test to permit consideration of plaintiffs'
claims would necessarily mean that courts would be
duty-bound to ignore the exhaustion doctrine in all, or any
other, instance.


C. Statutorily-Mandated Exhaustion Is Not Required For
Plaintiffs' Claims Because There Is No Administrative
Remedy To Exhaust

In addition to the fact that this case fits within
virtually every recognized exception to exhaustion
requirements, plaintiffs further submit that actions
against the FEC and CPD of this type should not be subject
to administrative review. The purpose of the FEC
administrative process is to guide the FEC in enforcement
of the Act and to resolve disputes between private parties;
for instance, actions by one campaign organization
challenging another campaign organization for violating a
provision of the FECA. Congress did not contemplate that
constitutional challenges to actions of the FEC and CPD as
an actor performing a public or governmental function would
be subject to the FECA's administrative process.

Defendants cite several cases which appear to suggest that,
unless administrative remedies are exhausted, this Court
cannot exercise jurisdiction. What defendants fail to point
out is that those cases differ fundamentally from the case
before this Court. Those cases each involve a complaint
brought against a "person" covered by the administrative
procedures of FECA. The FEC and the CPD (an entity
operating under the FEC's regulatory direction) are not
"persons" under the FECA and thus there is no
administrative process to exhaust.

The elaborate enforcement scheme embodied in 2 U.S.C. Sec.
437g is applicable only to those complaints that allege
that a "person" has violated the statute. Section 437g(1)
requires the FEC to notify the person alleged to have
committed a violation, give the "person" 15 days to respond
in order to demonstrate that the FEC should not take action
against it, and Section 437g(4)(A)(i) requires the FEC to
attempt to correct any apparent violations through
conciliation before considering formal action. The statute
deliberately and explicitly excludes from the definition of
person the "Federal Government or any authority of the
Federal Government." 2 U.S.C. Sec. 431(11) That is because
the special statutory enforcement mechanism is not designed
to resolve complaints where the FEC itself, or any other
federal entity, is the target. To the extent that the
Complaint seeks relief against the FEC itself, or the CPD
in its capacity as a governmental surrogate, the provisions
of Sec. 437g should not be controlling.7/


D. Even if the FECA Does Not Confer Jurisdiction, This
Court Clearly Has Jurisdiction Under 28 U.S.C. Sec. 1331

While plaintiffs submit that this Court clearly has
jurisdiction over its constitutional and nonconstitutional
claims under the FECA, subject matter jurisdiction over
plaintiffs' claims that the debate is ultra vires and
unconstitutional clearly and indisputably exists under 28
U.S.C. Sec. 1331. See Dolbeare, supra (finding precisely such
jurisdiction exists in precisely this type of case).
Dolbeare is directly on point.


Although a Congressionally created "statutory scheme" for
judicial review of the provisions of the statutes may
exist, as the FEC claims, under 2 U.S.C. Sections 437g and
h, and 26 U.S.C. Section 9041(a), this "scheme" does not
provide the sole means for challenging the statutes or the
actions of the FEC or its bureaucrats taken purportedly
pursuant to the statute but in effect alleged to be ultra
vires. The FEC's claims in this regard are without merit.


Id. at 6.

As in Dolbeare, plaintiffs here "have no administrative
remedies to exhaust to resolve the claims at issue herein."
Id. (citing Brown v. G.S.A., 425 U.S. 820 (1976) and
Preiser v. Rodriguez, 411 U.S. 475 (1973)). Jurisdiction
over plaintiffs' claims that the debates regulation is
ultra vires and unconstitutional "is not committed
exclusively to the FEC," and "jurisdiction is not
specifically barred under sec. 1331." Id. (citation
omitted). The court must accept jurisdiction of such a
claim under Sec. 1331 unless (a) the constitutional claim is
immaterial and alleged solely as a means of obtaining
federal jurisdiction; or (b) the claim is wholly
insubstantial and frivolous. Id. (citing Bell, 327 U.S. at
683). Neither is the case here. As in Dolbeare, plaintiffs
"have no opportunity to enjoy an immediate adjudicatory
administrative forum in which to resolve the dispute and a
prompt resolution which will vindicate their rights...."
Since there is no appropriate administrative remedy, there
can be no claim that exhaustion is required. Even if an
administrative remedy existed, the exhaustion requirement
is displaced since plaintiffs' claims involve acts beyond
the scope of the FEC's delegated powers." Id at 10 (citing
Leedom, 358 U.S. at 184 and Fairchild, Arabatzis & Smith,
Inc. v. Sackheim, 451 F. Supp. 1181 (S.D.N.Y. 1978)).

Federal question jurisdiction of the district courts under
28 U.S.C. Sec. 1331 is available unless the FECA precludes
judicial review or prescribes a particular form of action.
There is no indication anywhere in the FECA that Congress
intended to foreclose review of constitutional issues.8/

Because this Court clearly has jurisdiction over the
constitutional claims, it also should take jurisdiction
over nonconstitutional claims, as discussed in section
II.B.1, supra.


III. PLAINTIFFS' PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION REQUEST SHOULD BE
GRANTED

A. Plaintiffs Have Demonstrated A Likelihood Of Success On
The Merits

1. The CPD's selection criteria plainly do not comply with
applicable FEC regulations.

The CPD's strained interpretation of the FEC's mandatory
criteria for candidate selection, and its contention that
it may turn to a host of "subjective" factors to help guide
its "objective" decision turns the use of language on its
head. While blithely stating that all of its selection
criteria are "objective within the ordinary meaning of that
term," CPD Memorandum, at 25, the CPD vainly attempts to
justify its use of subjective criteria to undertake an
"objective approach" in arriving at a fundamentally
subjective conclusion "whether a candidate has a realistic
chance of election." Id at 26.

That the CPD actually uses a mixture of objective and
subjective factors in order to determine whom to invite to
participate in its presidential and vice presidential
debates is without question. Indeed, in a televised press
conference on September 10, 1996, the co-chairmen of the
CPD openly conceded that this very mix of factors --
plainly prohibited by 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.1 3(c) -- was at
work in the decision making process. "There are many
objective and subjective criteria," noted Co-Chairman Frank
J. Fahrenkopf, Jr. And, as Co-Chairman Paul J. Kirk noted,
"the subjective aspect is really studying what's been said
and what's been reported about." C-Span Presentation,
September 18, 1996, Transcript at 22-23 (a copy of which is
annexed hereto as Tab 2).9/

The CPD's assertion that "some subjective judgment on the
part of [the] evaluators" must be tolerated in the process
of making an objective determination is, indeed, the
exception that swallowed the rule. CPD Memorandum, at 25.
In fact, the CPD criteria allow for consideration of: the
opinions of Washington media bureau chiefs, political
campaign managers and pollsters, and political scientists;
the amount of newspaper front-page and network news
coverage afforded particular candidates; and the views of
"prominent political commentators." CPD Criteria, Numeral
2. That these subjective factors, specifically delineated
in writing by the CPD, are only the leading edge of the
iceberg was made clear in further media interviews given by
Co-Chairman Kirk.

Mr. Kirk was asked in a National Public Radio interview on
September 18, 1996 how to assess Perot's 1996 debate
exclusion in light of the fact that he was allowed entry in
1992:


That is a good question. It was the very same criteria ....

* * *

[Y]our question is why then and not now. In 1992 I think
the mood of the country was quite different. There was a
great -- I think more of an urgency for change than perhaps
we see now, greater fascination, if you will, with Ross
Perot who at that point was a new candidate on the scene.
The budget deficit issue was much more burning than it is
perhaps today even. Ross Perot basically had that as the
lead plank in his platform if you will. It was commanding
the kind of attention it deserved.

* * *

Now we come to 1996. It's the same candidate, but I think
a different feeling in the country about him, probably not
the same sort of attraction at least perceptively that he
might have had in 1992.

* * *

I think the committee felt that . . . it really would be
unrealistic to think that he could do better than he did in
1992, so they recommended that he not be invited to debate
in 1996.


Paul G. Kirk, Co-Chairman, CPD, September 18. 1996,
National Public Radio's Talk of the Nation, at 5-7
(emphasis added) (a copy of which is annexed hereto as Tab
3).[10/]

If, as it appears, the CPD is now in the business of
assessing the "mood" of the country. the public's
"fascination" with a particular candidate. and the relative
desirability of his positions as front-burner political
issues, the FEC's directives contained in 11 C.F.R. Sec.
110.13(c) are no longer even at issue. The CPD argues that
it must retain a "modicum of judgment in applying its
'objective criteria' so as to ensure the avoidance of a
potentially 'bizarre' or unwelcome result." CPD Memorandum,
at 25. Yet, the temperance and moderation described in the
CPD's pleadings does not resonate in the apparently
wide-ranging, subjective decision-making process which
excluded Perot and Choate from the 1996 debates.

The CPD's apparently wide-ranging and fast-mutating view of
what constitutes "objective criteria" for the purposes of
the debates understandably leaves it feeling that
plaintiffs in this proceeding have adopted "a cramped
construction of objective criteria." CPD Memorandum, at 23.
After all, the CPD notes, the term is not even defined
within the pertinent C.F.R. provision. Yet, the criteria
which the CPD adopted to guide its mandated "objective"
determination bare little resemblance to how federal courts
have defined "objective" data. Such information should be
"independent of what is personal or private in our
apprehension and feelings, that use facts without
distortion by personal feelings or prejudices and that are
publicly or intersubjectively observable or verifiable,
especially by scientific methods." Association of the Bar
of the City of New York v. I.R.S., 858 F.2d 876, 880 (2d
Cir. 1988) (citation omitted). The CPD's criteria, chock
full of opinions and views from various observers, and its
apparent references to the "mood" of the country and its
various "fascinations," simply cannot meet the standard
mandated by 11 CFR Sec. 110.13(c).[11/]

Further, the CPD's reliance on Wilson v. H.H.S., 770 F.2d
1048, 1052 (Fed. Cir. 1985) and DePauw v. I.T.C., 782 F.2d
1564, 1566 (Fed. Cir.), cert. denied, 479 U.S. 815 (1986)
is misplaced. The CPD argues that both Wilson and DePauw
stand for the proposition that "objective criteria," as
mentioned in statutes and regulations, can allow for
application of certain degrees of subjective judgment. That
may be true when, as in these two cases, a statutory
provision states that performance standards will "to the
maximum extent feasible, permit the accurate evaluation of
job performance on the basis of objective criteria...." 5
U.S.C. Sec. 4302(b)(1) (emphasis added). Here, the FEC's
criteria for candidate selection do not explicitly provide
for the latitude which the CPD apparently wishes it had;
the regulation flatly states that "staging organizations
must use pre-established objective criteria to determine
which candidates may participate in a debate." 11 C.F.R. Sec.
110.13(c) (emphasis added). Nothing could be clearer.

Quite simply, while the CPD purports to make what it
considers "objective" determinations as to which candidates
will participate in the debates, it wants to be able to
gather and consider volumes of subjective data to inform
that decision. That process is incongruous, not permitted
by regulation, and has led to the inappropriate exclusion
of Perot and Choate from the 1996 debates.


2. Ultra Vires and Constitutional Arguments

a. Because FECA prevents corporations from funding
bipartisan debates, the regulation is ultra vires and the
CPD's scheduled debates are illegal.

The FECA categorically bans any and all corporate campaign
contributions and expenditures in presidential elections,
allowing for a few definitional exceptions. 2 U.S.C. Sec.
441(b). The purpose of this sweeping provision is to block
corporate control and manipulation of democratic elections
through direct campaign contributions or independent
expenditures.12/ The categorical ban on corporate money
dominance in elections is designed to combat the real and
symbolic fusion of political power with corporate power in
order to preserve public confidence in the integrity of our
democracy.

This ban thus arguably forbids corporate-funded debates
even if a corporation does invite all legally qualified
candidates to participate. After all, the evil targeted by
the statute is not just private corporations choosing to
boost one candidate over another, but private corporations
having any involvement at all with political candidates and
acting "in connection with" federal elections. Indeed,
corporate funding and staging of debates may be the most
insidious kind of corporate dominance of all because it
tends to be invisible and thus the public cannot determine
for itself what impact the corporations have had on the
framing of the candidate choices and substantive topics.13/

The structure of the statute furnishes a most compelling
argument for this interpretation. The only explicit
definitional exception FECA provides to the ban on
corporate involvement in federal elections is for internal
corporate communications and not for external action with
the public. See 2 U.S.C. Sec. 431 (9)(B)(iii). It is quite a
leap from a corporation communicating with its
"stockholders, or executive or administrative personnel" to
communicating with all of the American people. Id

At the very least, FECA's ban on corporate dollars in
federal elections means that no corporation may spend money
on campaign election debates unless it invites every
legally qualified and electable candidate to participate.
On this theory, the purpose of the ban on corporate money
in elections is to prevent corporations from playing
favorites in campaigns and tilting elections in one
direction or the other. As a result, a corporation could
sponsor and fund a wide-open nonpartisan educational debate
and forum in which every single legally qualified candidate
was invited. As noted in Plaintiffs' moving brief, this was
the precise position taken by the FEC before it succumbed
to outside pressure and wrote its first debate regulation.

The FEC has thus ventured beyond its proper role and
written a regulation that is ultra vires.14/ Amazingly, it
now does not even bother to defend its regulation on the
basis of any actual language in the statute but instead
makes a series of irrelevant jurisdictional arguments, see
CPD Memorandum, at 12-14, that are clearly defeated by
Dolbeare, supra (finding federal jurisdiction to challenge
allegedly ultra vires and unconstitutional actions by the
FEC). It also rather gingerly invokes Chevron v. NRDC, 467
U.S. 837 (1984) to suggest that deference to the FEC's
"u-turn" is due here, see FEC's Memorandum, at 13. However.
an agency receives no deference at all when "the intent of
Congress is clear" and the agency is simply acting outside
of the terms of the statutory command. See Chevron, 467
U.S. at 842 ("If the intent of Congress is clear, that is
the end of the matter; for the court as well as the agency,
must give effect to the unambiguously expressed intent of
Congress."). Nor does focusing on the result -- as opposed
to the standard -- in Orloski v. FEC, 795 F.2d 156 (D.C.
Cir. 1986), do the FEC much good. See id. at 161 (standard
to be applied in reviewing FEC decision is whether it has
acted "contrary to law. under Sec. 437g(a)(8)(c)). An
administrative delegation is not a license to amend the
statute; and even if it were, it would violate the
separation of powers. Be that as it may, a legally
qualified and electable federal candidate has a right under
FECA to be invited to any corporate-funded debate, for if
he or she is not invited, the debate simply constitutes a
dressed-up campaign contribution to, or expenditure on
behalf of, his or her rivals.15/ See FECA, 2 U.S.C. Secs.
431(8)-(9).

The CPD at least makes a faint effort to argue that the
debate regulation falls under FECA's separate exemption for
"nonpartisan activity designed to encourage individuals to
vote or to register to vote ...." CPD's Memorandum, at 40
(citing 2 U.S.C. Sec. 431(9)(B)(ii)). This might work except
that this provision says nothing about debates, the debates
regulation says nothing about voting or voter registration,
and debate sponsors never register a single person to vote.
As legal reasoning goes, the argument offends a basic
principle of statutory construction -- Expressio unius est
exclusio alterius. ("The expression of one thing is the
exclusion of a different thing.")

The regulation must fail as ultra vires, which means that
CPD corporate expenditures -- and the contributions of
their large corporate donors -- amount to illegal campaign
contributions to the Democratic and Republican candidates
or illegal expenditures in connection with the election.
They must be enjoined, and the court cannot wait for the
FEC to do it because it is the FEC's own unlawful
regulation which created the violation.


b. The regulation is void for vagueness and violates due
process and the First Amendment by vesting standardless
discretion over presidential debates in private
corporations and the political parties that work with them.

(1) The regulation vests standardless discretion over
presidential debates in private corporations and the
political parties that work with them.

Even assuming the FEC had statutory authority to carve out
the exception at 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110. 13, its regulation
violates the First Amendment and is void for vagueness
because it delegates almost completely standardless
discretion over decisions affecting fundamental political
speech interests to private entities. See 60 Fed. Reg.
64,260, 64,262 (1995) (stating that the "choice of which
objective criteria to use is largely left to the discretion
of the staging organization," and that criteria may be
fixed "to control the number of candidates participating in
a debate if the staging organization believes there are too
many . . .").

One easy way to understand the First Amendment violation is
to hypothesize that the FEC had enacted the debate
regulation for itself, declaring that it was going to
sponsor debates and would select candidates to participate
using unspecified "objective criteria." Such an imprecise
standard would be void for vagueness since it would vest
"standardless" discretion in the FEC to run debates without
requiring it to provide specific "reasons, findings or
reasoned conclusions" as to its selection criteria, much
less why this or that candidate was included or excluded.
We could put it no better than the CPD itself, whose
astonishingly honest formulation captures perfectly the
nature of the regulations it operates under: "the
regulations do not define the phrase 'objective criteria'
at all. . ." CPD's Memorandum, at 23.

If it would be unconstitutional for the FEC to adopt this
empty standard for itself, it surely is much worse to
delegate it to a private actor, as in Larkin v. Grendel's
Den, 459 U.S. 116, 125 ( 1982) (striking down on First
Amendment grounds a state statute that allowed private
churches veto power over award of liquor licenses for
premises within 500-foot radius of their property). The FEC
has vested wide-open standardless discretion in the CPD to
determine which candidates will have the opportunity to
participate in presidential debates. The "objective
criteria" command is dangerously loose and can be employed
-- as it was in this case -- for explicitly political and
partisan goals. See id. at 125 (the veto power "could be
employed for explicitly religious goals" because the
statute "does not by its terms require that churches' power
be used in a religiously neutral way. "'[The] potential for
conflict inheres in the situation'; and appellants have not
suggested any 'effective means of guaranteeing' that the
delegated power 'will be used exclusively for secular,
neutral and nonideological purposes."') (citations
omitted). Just as the First Amendment establishes a
governmental "neutrality" principle as to religion, see
id., so does it establish a governmental "neutrality"
principle as to elections, where it takes on even greatest
force and urgency.16/

In this case, the vague "objective criteria" directive
fails to provide any real guarantee to candidates that the
power delegated to the CPD will be used for "neutral and
nonideological purposes."17/ Rather, their constitutional
rights are put at the mercy of a private corporation made
up of five Democrats and five Republicans and funded by
large corporations which may or may not have reason to
oppose particular candidates.

In this sense, plaintiffs' situation is closely analogous
to that of the plaintiffs in Lakewood v. Plain Dealer
Publ'g Co., 486 U.S. 750 ( 1988) (striking down as facially
invalid a city ordinance authorizing mayor to issue or deny
permits to newspaper publishers to place news racks on
public property and, if refused, requiring only that the
Mayor "state[d] the reasons for such denial"). The Court in
Lakewood held that the "danger" of "content and viewpoint
censorship" is "at its zenith when the determination of who
may speak and who may not is left to the unbridled decision
of a government official." Id. at 763. Without "standards
governing the exercise of discretion, a government official
may decide who may speak and who may not based upon the
content or viewpoint of the speaker." Id. at 763-64 Here,
the First Amendment danger is even worse since the
government officials have turned their decision over to
putatively private actors, against whom there is no
meaningful check against political discrimination at all.


(2) The regulation permits private corporations, like the
CPD, to - adopt an unconstitutional definition of
"electability."

In order to understand why the criteria applied against
plaintiffs were "non-neutral" and "ideological," see
Grendel's, 459 U.S. at 125, it is critical to see that
there are two potential definitions of "electability," the
word which now appears to be the pivotal concept in the
case. That is, there are two available meanings of
"electability"" that a corporate debate donor might employ
in developing criteria for debate inclusion: we propose to
call them the criterion of "legal electability" and the
criterion of "political electability," the former kind
perfectly consistent with -indeed warranted by -- the
Constitution, the latter kind wholly vague, discriminatory
and unconstitutional. Yet, the FEC has clearly invited
corporations to choose between these lawful and unlawful
alternatives. See 60 Fed. Meg. 64,260, 64,262 (1995)
(stating that the "choice of which objective criteria to
use is largely left to the discretion of the staging
organization," and that criteria may be fixed "to control
the number of candidates participating in a debate if the
staging organization believes there are too many," thus
plainly rejecting the constitutional approach); CPD's
Memorandum, at 26 (showing CPD's belief that FEC's debates
regulation authorizes its "nonpartisan, objective standard"
of "whether a candidate has a realistic chance at
election.")

The constitutionally permissible definition of
"electability" is whether a candidate is actually electable
as defined by the Constitution and federal law. Thus, the
following objective criteria are properly applied to
potential candidate debaters: (I) Is the candidate
constitutionally eligible to serve if elected? See U.S.
Const. art. II, Sec. 1, cl. 4 ("No person except a natural
born Citizen. . . shall be eligible the Office of
President; neither shall any person be eligible to that
Office who shall not have attained to the age of thirty
five Years . . ."); (2) Has the candidate qualified on
sufficient state ballots such that he or she could actually
collect a majority in the electoral college? See U.S.
Const. art. 11, Sec. 1, cl. 2; see also U.S. Const. amend.
XII;[18/] and (3) Has the candidate qualified for federal
funding for his or her campaign under the provisions of the
Presidential Campaign Fund Act?

These are the constitutionally acceptable criteria
corporate actors may use to select candidates to
participate in debates. The first two are absolute
objective prerequisites to the candidate taking and
assuming office and the third represents the closest that
FECA itself has to a definition of seriousness.19/

Clearly unconstitutional, however, is the creation of extra
constitutional and non-legislative criteria that focus on
the political "electability" of the candidate. There are
four decisive constitutional problems with this seductive
but deeply flawed version of electability.

First, as the Eighth Circuit pointed out in Forbes, this
notion of electability as "political viability" is "so
susceptible of variation in individual opinion" as to
"provide no secure basis for the exercise of governmental
power consistent with the First Amendment." Forbes v.
Arkansas Educ. Television Comm'n, 93 F.3d 497,504 (8th Cir.
1996). Indeed, few things are more unknowable than the
outcome of an election and few things so subjective and
arbitrary as guesses about it. At best, pollsters and
pundits take small snapshots of a political universe whose
history is marked by fluidity, comebacks, and stunning
upsets. One need only recall the famous photo of President
Truman brandishing the "Dewey Wins" headline to give pause
to the whole enterprise.

Second, it is fundamentally antidemocratic to use
predictions of election results to limit and restrict
political debate and thus alter the outcome of the
election. The Constitution delegates to Congress the job of
setting election day and it may set only one. See U.S.
Const. art. II, Sec. 1, cl. 3 ("The Congress may determine
the Time of choosing the Electors, and the Day on which
they shall give their Votes; which Day shall be the same
throughout the United States."). It is per se impermissible
to replace this public election process with a private
selection process. See. e.g., Terry v. Adams, 345 U.S.461
(1953) (invalidating exclusionary political process set up
by private group of citizens to narrow the public's field
of choices). In American democracy, debate comes before the
voters' decision, not after. Indeed, political debate over
the public agenda and who shall preside over us is one of
the principal purposes of the First Amendment.20/

Third, even if we had a computer that could tell us with
absolute certainty who was going to win an election, it
would still violate the constitutional rights of other
candidates to exclude them from organized debates because
they were going to lose. Losers have First Amendment
rights, too, and may not be ejected from public debate
after having lost -- much less so before losing. The equal
rights of losers presumably prevent government from
enacting a law requiring all candidates trailing by more
than 30% in public opinion polls in presidential races to
return their federal funds or from passing a law denying
otherwise qualified candidates who are behind 30% in the
polls the right to invoke the equal-time provisions of FCC
law.

There is a critical reason why government cannot treat
future "winners" and future "losers" differently in this
way. The goal of "winning" the election, that is, capturing
the office, is often not the principal -- and is almost
never the exclusive -- reason for a candidate's running.
Candidates run for a myriad of other perfectly legitimate
reasons, including: (1 ) to inject messages and issues into
the campaign that would not otherwise be aired and that
other candidates might prefer to ignore;21/ (2) to improve
the quality of political debate and dialogue;22/ (3) to
establish legitimacy for a future run for office;23/ (4) to
begin to build the political infrastructure of a new party
to contest offices at a host of different levels; (5) to
influence the outcome of the election in a direction more
favorable to the candidate's supporters;24/ and (6) to be
offered the Vice-Presidency or a cabinet post at some later
point.25/ It would clearly violate the First Amendment to
prevent citizens from running for office if they had these
motives; there is no constitutional compulsion to run
exclusively to collect the most number of votes.

Fourth, by excluding legally electable candidates, the
standard of political electability ends up discriminating
on a viewpoint basis against candidates who represent
unpopular political views, interests or tendencies. It will
almost always be third parties who find themselves in
Perot's position -- that is, with a critical mass of
support but needing broader social exposure to grow and
institutionalize. Had he not debated in 1992, Perot would
never have won 19% of the vote. See David Firestone,
Perot's Impressive Loss, Newsday, Nov. 4, 1992, at 29
(noting that Perot's impressive debate performance buoyed
his campaign). If he does not qualify to debate, having
obtained ballot access in all 50 states and the District of
Columbia, and securing nearly $30 million dollars in
federal funds, what third party candidate ever will? How
will the Reform Party qualify for federal funds next
election if it fails to meet the 5% threshold this
election? See Affidavit of C. Mulford, Para. 9. attached
hereto at Tab 4. It takes time, over the course of several
elections, to build up a new party, especially given the
tough requirements for obtaining ballot access and
qualifying for federal campaign funds.26/


(3) This case shows how. as applied. the FEC's vague
regulation and delegation of standardless discretion to
private actors will burden First Amendment rights.

This case provides a textbook illustration of how
discriminatory and unconstitutional results will follow
from the FEC's decision to allow corporate debate sponsors
to adopt the seductive definition of "objective" as
"politically electable." The CPD almost got the criteria
for legal electability right--it began by focusing on the
eligibility requirements of Article II, Section I and
whether a candidate has a mathematical chance of winning in
the electoral college -- but then tacked on a host of
criteria that allow it, and its various delegates and
interviewees, to descend into almost comic arbitrariness
and partisan discrimination. See CPD Candidate Selection
Criteria for 1996 General Election Debate Participation.

For example, seeking "signs of national newsworthiness and
competitiveness," the CPD purportedly solicited the
"professional opinions of the Washington bureau chiefs of
major newspapers, news magazines, and broadcast networks."
Even assuming this took place,27/ it seems hard to
understand why the participation of a constitutionally
eligible candidate on the ballot in fifty states who just
received nearly $30 million in federal funds should rest on
the reactions over the telephone of a small group of
Washington bureau chiefs. Why are their views more legally
significant than those of any other group of American
citizens?

The CPD Criteria also require it to seek out the opinions
of "professional campaign managers and pollsters not then
employed by the candidates under consideration" Amazingly,
this "factor" does not even require that these consultants
and pollsters have no conflict of interest in terms of
other campaigns they may be working on. For example, a
consultant who is approached by the CPD might be working on
a House or Senate campaign whose outcome could be affected
by the presence or absence of a large group of Independent
or third party voters at the polls. If such a consultant
wants to depress turnout by Independents, he or she could
simply tell the CPD interviewer, for example, that Perot
should not be included in the debates because he has no
realistic chance to win.

The Criteria also have the CPD examining the "[c]olumn
inches on newspaper front pages and exposure on network
telecasts in comparison with the major party candidates."
This is a blatantly discriminatory "factor" that again
delegates an important public decision to the media. How
can a candidate who is not yet an elected official compete
on these terms against the President of the United States
and the Senate Majority Leader?

The Criteria also allow the CPD to rely on "findings of
significant public opinion polls conducted by national
polling and news organizations." Even if it were
constitutional to give legal effect to polls (could a state
conduct a poll instead of an election to fill a public
office?), we would have every reason to doubt their
"objectivity" and utility. See Christopher Hitchens, Voting
in the Passive Voice in For the Sake of Argument, at 42-43,
50 (1993) (concluding that, since everything follows from
the formulation of the question, "polling is not a benign,
detached mapping of the political landscape but, rather, a
powerful means of cultivating and reshaping it," and
quoting former pollster Pat Caddell to the effect that
polling is "an instrument for deception whereby the truth
is obscured and the public will excluded and ignored.").
See also, Affidavit of G. Black, Paras. 17-20.

In sum, by allowing, even encouraging, corporations to
adopt the "politically electable" standard for debate
inclusion, the FEC regulation both defeats the purpose of
the statute and violates the First Amendment.


c. The CPD is a state actor.

The CPD disclaims its status as a state actor exercising
control over an integral part of the electoral process. It
emphasizes that it "is a private corporation with a
voluntary board of directors" and "receives no federal
funds." CPD's Memorandum, at 32. These features do not make
it less of a state actor than the Jaybird Association, a
private and self-funded unincorporated group deemed to be
a state actor because of its exclusion of disfavored
citizens from "an integral part" of "the elective process
that determines who shall rule and govern ...." Terry, 345
U.S. at 461. But, in its Memorandum, the CPD completely
bypasses the entire white-primary line of authority whose
contemporary relevance was just restated by the Supreme
Court in Morse v. Republican Party of Virginia, _U.S._, 116
S. Ct. 1186 (1996). It prefers to analogize its situation
to that of the U.S. Olympic Committee.

It is simply not true that "there can be no finding of
'governmental action' where, as here, the government has
exercised no control over the selection of participants in
CPD's debate." CPD's Memorandum, at 35. This assertion
disregards the whole teaching of the white-primary cases,
which is that state action in politics can take place when
"the government" formally exercises no legal power but
where individual state actors play a role in excluding
other citizens in the electoral process. Yet the CPD
quickly glosses over its very own constitution and
composition as a (bi)partisan agency with elected members
of the United States Senate and United States House of
Representatives serving as Commissioners.

No further discovery is needed in this case to establish
the relevance of Justice Frankfurter's rule that state
action exists when "somewhere, somehow, to some extent,
there be an infusion of conduct by officials, panoplied
with state power ...." Terry, 345 U.S. at 473. The
information we have been able to cull from public records
indicates that the CPD is not only a state actor because of
its well-documented subservience to the Democratic and
Republican Parties, but because it is composed
self-consciously of the two Democratic and Republican
co-chairs and four Democratic and four Republican
Commissioners, three of whom are presently sitting members
of the U.S. Congress, where they exercise federal
legislative power under Article I of the Constitution. The
following CPD Commissioners are currently members of
Congress:28/ Senator Paul Coverdell (R. Ga.);29/
Congresswoman Barbara Vucanovich (R. Nev.);30/ and
Congressman John Lewis (D. Ga.).31/

Each of these three Commissioners took an oath of office
swearing to uphold and defend the Constitution, a
constitutional obligation they retained during their
service at meetings of the CPD. U.S. Const. art. VI, cl.3.
Moreover, by assuming a central role in the CPD's
deliberations, they not only established clear state action
in the CPD's control over debates but effectively created
a constitutional error analogous to the one made originally
in FECA and corrected in Buckley v. Valeo, 424 U.S. 1,
109-143 (holding that FECA's provision for appointment of
FEC members by President pro tempore of Senate and House
Speaker violated appointments Clause); see also F.E.C. v.
NRA Victory Fund, 6 F.3d 821 (D.C. Cir. 1993) (stating that
it is well settled that Congress may not appoint members of
an agency with executive powers). If the CPD takes the
position that full and formal participation by three
elected members of Congress as CPD members does not
establish state action, then by extension all of the seats
on the Commission could be filled by members of Congress.
On the other hand, if the CPD agrees that filling the
Commission entirely with members of Congress would create
state action, then state action exists if even only one of
the Commissioner positions is filled by a member of
Congress. See id. (striking down the presence of even
non-voting members of the FEC appointed by Congress on the
grounds that it violated separation of powers because their
mere presence would influence the executive entity).

Given the fiercely partisan membership of the CPD and the
infusion of important elected officials throughout its
process, including selection of candidates for presidential
debates, it is hard to credit CPD's protestation that its
decision "was made independently, free from government
influence over the outcome, and without any governmental
authority." CPD's Memorandum, at 35. On the contrary, the
"Commission on Presidential Debates," which has everywhere
tried to be seen as official as possible, has gotten its
wish and must be treated as a formal part of the state
apparatus governing elections. Furthermore, the FEC and
Democratic and Republican Parties may not escape their own
complicity with this arrangement: they, too, have "elected
to place" their "power, property and prestige behind" this
unlawful discrimination. Burton v. Wilmington Parking
Authority. 365 U.S. 715, 725 (1961).


B. Plaintiffs Meet Other Requirements for Injunctive Relief

1. Plaintiffs will suffer irreparable harm in the absence
of the preliminary relief requested.

After violating statutory and constitutional law in
excluding Perot from the 1996 presidential debates, and
then contending that his challenge in this Court is
improperly lodged because he did not exhaust a
time-consuming and futile administrative process, the CPD
completes its circular argument by contending, in any
event, that Perot and his running mate will not suffer
"irreparable harm" if the requested relief is denied. The
CPD's argument is, quite simply, too cute to be clever.
Absent a preliminary injunction, the CPD will proceed to
use corporate funds unlawfully to stage presidential
debates that have been tailored to suit the specifications
of the two major parties and from which Perot has been
excluded by means of a process that blatantly violated FEC
regulations. Unless this Court intervenes, the debates will
occur as scheduled, without the participation of Perot or
Choate. Their rostrum at the debates cannot be recovered
once lost, and is in every sense the "imminent," "certain,
great, and actual, not theoretical," injury which the CPD
contends is absent. See Housing Study Group v. Kemp, 736 F.
Supp. 321, 330, opinion clarified on other grounds,
739F.Supp. 633 (D.D.C. 1990).32/ Examples of specific
injuries resulting to Plaintiffs are described in the
Affidavit of Clay Mulford, attached hereto at Tab 4.

The CPD improperly relies upon Lujan, 504 U.S. at 573 in
maintaining that candidates excluded from the debates lodge
merely a "generalized grievance," where the complaints are
no different in kind from what might be asserted by any
other citizen regarding the CPD's failure to follow its own
procedures. Yet, this so-called "standing the shoes of the
public" argument fails, for what Lujan truly means to
preclude are instances where a party seeks "relief that no
more directly and tangibly benefits him than it does the
public at large." Id. Here, while including the Reform
Party's candidates in the debates would certainly benefit
the public's analysis of the upcoming elections, it is
Perot and Choate who would directly and tangibly benefit
from the relief requested herein.33/

Moreover, where it appears substantially likely to the
Court that a statutory or regulatory violation has
occurred, it may be presumed that an irreparable harm
sufficient to support injunctive relief is present. Gresham
v. Windrush Partners, Ltd., 730 F.2d 1417, 1423 (11th Cir.
1984); see also Reply Brief of Plaintiffs Hagelin,
Tompkins, and the Natural Law Party of the United States of
America at 23-25; United States v. Haves International
Corp., 415 F.2d 1038, 1045 (5th Cir. 1969) ("irreparable
injury should be presumed from the very fact that the
statute has been violated"); Atchison. Topeka and Santa Fe
Railway Co. v. Lennen, 640 F.2d 255, 259 (10th Cir. 1981)
(same); Heublein. Inc. v. F.T.C., 539 F. Supp. 123, 128 (D.
Conn. 1982) ("When Federal statutes have been violated, it
has long been the rule that a court need not inquire into
the traditional requirements for equitable relief."); 7
Moore's Federal Practice, Moore's Federal Practice, Sec.
65.04(1) n. 7b. Presumption of harm also is warranted when
constitutional violations have occurred. Elrod v. Burns,
427 U.S. 347, 373 (1976) ("loss of First Amendment
freedoms, for even minimal periods of time, unquestionably
constitutes irreparable injury.").


2. Requiring The CPD To Apply Only Objective Criteria If It
Is To Sponsor A Presidential Debate is Clearly In The
Public Interest.

The CPD contends that granting a preliminary injunction to
plaintiffs would "be highly disruptive of the on-going
debate process" and would create a "very significant
potential" that President Clinton and Senator Dole would
"refuse to participate." The CPD further argues that the
public interest will be served by allowing the presidential
debates to go forward. CPD's Memorandum, at 44-46.

First, plaintiffs do not in any way seek the elimination of
debates altogether. Candidates Perot and Choate indeed see
the debates as being the most important vehicle in this
election year for allowing the electorate to make informed
balloting decisions as to whom they will support for
President and Vice President. Perot and Choate view the
debates to be in the "supreme" public interest. They also,
however, consider the public interest to be best served by
requiring that only lawful standards be used to determine
debate participation eligibility. To allow the debates to
proceed as presently constituted will not serve the public
interest in ensuring "fairness and integrity" in the
process at issue.

Furthermore, to suggest that this Court's intervention at
this late date will cause such disruption as to potentially
cancel the debates wholly ignores the circumstances of 1992
when Perot's participation in the debates was not confirmed
by the CPD until October 7, 1992, just four days prior to
the first debate on October 11, 1992.[34/] There is hardly
anything unduly "disruptive" about adding another chair to
the platform. The rapid and changing pace at which the
presidential debates are negotiated and scheduled is well
known. Requiring the application of lawful criteria to
debate participants can be accomplished quickly, with
minimal disruption, under the supervision of this Court.

Finally, for the CPD to suggest that the two major party
candidates might "refuse to participate" if others are
included in the debates flies in the very face of the
purpose of the subject regulation in the first place.35/
This case is not about a debate sponsor inviting only those
whom the two major political parties wish to be included.
It is about the application of lawful selection criteria,
applied fairly and equally to all concerned. For the CPD to
suggest that President Clinton and Senator Dole may refuse
to participate if this Court intervenes to protect the
integrity of this process is to ignore the very reason 11
C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(c) was promulgated. The public interest
will best be served by this Court's enforcement of this
regulation.


IV. REMEDY

Plaintiffs recognize that this Court should not
unnecessarily intrude into the election process, and does
not have authority to order that debates occur or select
the participants in those debates. This Court, however,
does have jurisdiction to guide the decision making process
of the CPD to ensure that it conforms to legal
requirements. Because the CPD has illegally provided for
the automatic inclusion of candidates of the two major
parties, and because the CPD must apply "preestablished"
criteria, plaintiffs suggest that this Court review the
criteria and inform defendants of the criteria it considers
objective. It is plaintiffs view that only three of the
criteria are objective: (1) the candidate satisfy
eligibility requirements of Article II, Section 1; (2) that
the candidate be placed on the ballot in enough states to
have a mathematical chance of obtaining an electoral
college majority; and (3) the candidate be eligible for
federal election funding. Because it cannot be disputed
that plaintiffs Ross Perot and Pat Choate meet these
requirements, plaintiffs suggest that the Court order the
CPD allow these candidates to participate in the debates.
At a minimum, the Court should identify the criteria set
forth above as the only "pre-established" objective
criteria, enjoin the CPD from applying any debate selection
criteria other than these pre-established objective
criteria in selecting participants for the debates; and
maintain continuing jurisdiction over this case and require
that the CPD provide this Court at least five days before
the staging of any debate with a written report of its
determination of eligibility for debate participation under
the permissible pre-established objective criteria. Because
the CPD is composed solely of members of the Democratic and
Republican parties, it is inherently biased and this Court
must maintain jurisdiction over the selection process to
ensure that an impartial, nonpartisan decision is made,
consistent with regulatory requirements.

In the alternative, this Court should declare the FEC's
debate regulation to be ultra vires and unconstitutional
and enjoin any further CPD or corporate spending on these
presidential debates or "in connection with" the
presidential election unless and until all legally
qualified candidates, according to Qualification for
Federal Campaign Funding and appropriate constitutional
criteria, are invited to appear at the October 6th, October
9th and October 16, 1996 debates.


V. CONCLUSION

For the foregoing reasons, the plaintiffs respectfully urge
that this Court grant the injunctive relief they seek.

