ENDNOTES

1/ For example, had the CPD applied to major party
candidates the same criteria it applied to others and
determined, through an examination of its objective and
subjective factors, that Senator Dole's campaign efforts,
his standing in the polls and his money supply rendered him
no "realistic chance" of winning the election, it could
exclude him from the debates, and instead hold a debate
between President Clinton and Jim Lehrer. If, as
defendants' claim, Congress' intent with respect to federal
elections is that the federal courts can have no role in
policing such emergent situations, Mr. Dole would watch the
debates on television with the rest of the electorate. It
can certainly be argued that this situation is fanciful
because the CPD would never take such a position -- after
all, its members are evenly split between the Republican
and Democratic parties. Yet, to someone not steeped in the
jurisprudence of the FEC's "exclusive jurisdiction," it
would seem just as perverse for the two parties to sit down
together and subjectively determine to exclude competition
from the debates safe in the knowledge that the only body
with oversight authority would do nothing until after the
election results were in.

2/  In numerous other decisions, federal courts have
recognized exceptions to exhaustion where a statute
mandates initial resort to an administrative process. A
number of these cases are collected and presented in a
table attached as an exhibit to the brief filed by
plaintiffs Hagelin, et al.

3/ Nor is this a case where the Court should feel bound to
defer to the FEC under notions of "primary jurisdiction,"
a discretionary doctrine whereby an issue within the
special competence of an agency may be referred to it for
more efficient disposition. Reiter v. Cooper, 507 U.S. 258,
267 (1993). In this case, as noted elsewhere herein, the
Court is confronted with an array of legal issues. Referral
to an agency under "primary jurisdiction" does not cede a
court's jurisdiction, and is most appropriate where factual
determinations and analysis in areas of agency expertise
are required. Ricci v. Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 409
U.S. 289, 305 (1973); Port of Boston Marine Terminal Ass'n
v. Rederiaktiebolaget Transatlantic, 400 U.S. 62, 68
(1970). This is not the case here.

4/  If plaintiffs are required to fully pursue the
administrative process in this instance, they will by
definition lose all of their claims because the general
election will have come and gone before any relief can be
fashioned. This situation presents the prospect of
litigants losing constitutional rights without receiving a
day in court, and it is well- settled that statutes should
be construed -- where possible -- so as to avoid such
serious issues of constitutionality.

5/  Defendants claim that the upholding of exhaustion
requirements in two FEC cases -- National Conservative Poll
Action Comm. v. F.E.C., 626 F.2d 953 (D.C. Cir. 1980)
("NCP") and Sierra Club v. F.E.C., 593 F. Supp. 166, 169
(D.D.C. 1984) -- counsel that this Court should do the
same. However, neither NCP (which involved debt retirement
issues) nor Sierra Club (which involved in-kind
contributions to federal candidates) present the type of
time-sensitive claims alleged here.

6/ Plaintiffs endorse, and include herein as if fully set
forth, plaintiffs Hagelin, et al.'s discussion and citation
of numerous instances where exhaustion procedures deemed to
be jurisdictional are nonetheless deemed waivable by
federal courts. Hagelin, et al.'s Reply Brief, at 17-18.
See. e.g., Walker v. Southern Ry. Co., 385 U.S. 196, 198
(1966); Information Resources v. United States, 950 F.2d
1122 (5th Cir. 1992).

7/ Carter-Mondale. 642 F.2d at 538, a case the defendants
claim supports their position, strongly suggests judicial
intervention in the instant case would be proper. In
Carter-Mondale, the court had under review the prototypical
complaint by one political campaign committee against
another. The court concluded that resolution of the
complaint rested in the exclusive jurisdiction of the FEC
until the FEC had acted. The court observed that vesting
exclusive, albeit temporary, jurisdiction in the FEC was
designed "not only to allow development of the record, but
also because the FEC's resolution of this matter may be
satisfactory to all concerned and thereby preclude the need
for any appellate consideration. Id. at 542. In contrast,
in the instant case. the controversy does not require
record development and the FEC is clearly unable to resolve
the controversy to Mr. Perot's satisfaction in the time
available. The Carter-Mondale court did not address the
issue of respective jurisdiction of the court and the FEC
in cases where the FEC was the subject of the complaint
rather than the dispute resolution tribunal of first
instance. Indeed, the court expressly declined to address
"the authority and duty of the FEC in other circumstances."
Id.

8/  The Supreme Court has made clear in numerous cases that
it disfavors statutory regimes that foreclose judicial
review, particularly of constitutional claims and has been
unwilling to construe statutory provisions to preclude
court examination of constitutional claims. See. e.g.,
Johnson v. Robinson, 415 U.S. 361 ( 1974) (court entertains
claims under the First and Fifth Amendments despite
statutory language that forecloses court review of decision
by the Veteran's Administration "on any question of law or
fact under any law administered by the Veterans
Administration providing benefits for veterans and their
dependents or survivors"); Webster v. Doe, 486 U.S. 592
(1988) (Court construes National Security Act of 1947 to
preclude judicial review except for "colorable
constitutional claims").

9/ Plaintiffs endorse, as if fully included herein. the
thorough discussion of subjectiveness on the part of the
CPD which set forth in Hagelin, et al.'s Reply Brief, at
10-15.

10/ CPD Co-Chairman Kirk's comments run counter to the
CPD's position in its brief -- that the CPD does "not rely
on the 'personal' or private"feelings of its members." CPD
Memorandum, at 25.

11/ The CPD apparently believes that by assuring the Court
that its criteria do not reply on the "personal" or
"private" "feelings" of its members, there should be no
concern over their use. To the contrary, the CPD plainly
gathers exactly these type of opinions, views and
impressions from various media and political figures to
inform its judgments. Thus, it wishes to usher in through
the back door what it is not permitted to bring through the
front. This, the Court should not permit.

12/ See Pipefitters Local Union No. 562 v. United States,
407 U.S. 385, 416 (1972) (purpose of Sec. 441(b) is to
"eliminate the effect of aggregated wealth on federal
elections"); United States v. Int'l Union United
Automobile. Aircraft and Agricultural Implement Workers of
America, 352 U.S. 567, 585 (1957) (purpose of Sec. 441(b) to
restrict the political influence of "those who exercise
control over large aggregations of capital"); FEC v.
National Right to Work Comm., 459 U.S. 197, 207 (1982)
(purpose of Sec. 441(b) to control the "substantial
aggregations of wealth amassed by the special advantages
which go with the corporate form of organization"); F.E.C.
v. Massachusetts Citizens for Life. Inc., 479 U.S.238, 239
(1986) (legislative history "makes clear that Congress has
long regarded it as insufficient merely to restrict
payments made directly to candidates or campaign
organizations.").

13/ For example, according to the Institute for Policy
Studies, several of the CPD's major corporate contributors,
including Phillip Morris, Upjohn and Dow Chemical are also
members of USA*NAFTA, the business lobbying consortium that
promoted congressional approval of NAFTA in 1993. In that
year, Mr. Perot and Ralph Nader were the two leading public
opponents of NAFTA and both of them have been excluded from
the debates this year by the CPD. Unfortunately, there is
no way of knowing whether there is any connection between
these events which supports the more categorical reading of
the statute. See Press Release by Institute for Policy
Studies, Sept. 26, 1996. According to news reports, the
CPD's sponsorship of presidential debates in 1992 also
featured dramatic breaches of the statutory wall between
corporations and electoral democracy. See Jonathon Groner
and Sheila Kaplan, Buying Smoke and Mirrors at the Debates,
American Lawyer, Nov.2, 1992 (describing how the "two main
donors," the Philip Morris Cos. and Prudential Insurance
Company, gave $250,000 each and Philip Morris, the world's
leading cigarette manufacturer, not only sponsored debate
receptions but was allowed to hang a "large banner" with
its name on it that was "visible during post-debate
interviews" on television, all of which prompted a CPD
spokeswoman who asked not to be named to remark, "We are
very grateful to them.")

14/ The FEC even slips up momentarily and confirms this
point in the course of denying the Plaintiffs'
constitutional claim: "the Commission has no governmental
power over presidential debates to delegate," FEC
Memorandum, at 15, which is precisely Plaintiffs' argument
about why the regulation is ultra vires. Otherwise deft in
walking the tightrope between asserting a statutory basis
for its regulation over debates but denying that it has any
regulatory power over debates to share. the FEC here falls
off the high wire. It is hard to see where its authority to
regulate presidential debates comes from if it "has no
governmental power over" them, and it cites no authority
for the brazen, if subtly stated, proposition that it has
the power to amend the statute's painstaking definition of
what kinds of corporate expenditures and contributions are
illegal. See id.

15/ Contrary to the FEC's argument on standing, see FEC
Memorandum, at 12, plaintiffs clearly have standing to
challenge the FEC's regulation since the ban on corporate
manipulation of elections is meant to liberate candidates
from the unequal intervention of corporate wealth in
political campaigns and they are clearly injured by effects
directly traceable to the FEC's lawless regulation. There
is clear redressability. simply by declaring the regulation
invalid. Lujan v. Defenders of Wildlife, 504 U.S. 555
(1992).

16/ The First Amendment requires that government legislate
"generally applicable and evenhanded restrictions that
protect the integrity and reliability of the electoral
process itself," Anderson v. Celebrezze, 460 U.S. 780, 788
n.9 (1983), and are designed to make elections "fair and
honest." Storer v. Brown, 415 U.S. 724,730(1974). Without
neutral election rules, we cannot maintain democratic
self-government through a meaningful and robust marketplace
of ideas and views--if we cut off the "extremes" of debate,
then we have no debate at all. Thus, the Constitution
compels government to remain absolutely neutral as between
political actors. See. e.g., First Nat'l Bank of Boston v.
Bellotti, 435 U.S. 765 (1978) (striking down ban on
corporate campaign expenditures relating to speech that did
not affect the "material interests" of the corporation);
Carrington v. Rash, 380 U.S. 89, 94 (1965)(striking down
ban on voting by military personnel stationed in Texas and
holding that "'fencing out' from the franchise a sector of
the population because of the way they may vote is
constitutionally impermissible."); Davis v. Bandemer, 478
U.S. 109, 139 (stating that government may not stack
political process to benefit a political party to such
extent that one party has "essentially been shut out of the
political process"); Miller v. Johnson, _ U.S. . 115 S. Ct.
2475 (1995) (striking down congressional districts drawn in
a process where the principle of racial neutrality is
disregarded); Anderson. 460 U.S. 480 (1983) (striking down
early filing deadlines that rigged system against minor
parties). The principle requiring official neutrality
pervades constitutional law. See. e.g., Romer v. Evans,
__U.S.__, No. 94-1039, 1996 WL 262293 (May 20, 1996)
(striking down state constitutional amendment attempting to
exclude homosexuals from political process). This is why it
is disappointing, if not surprising, that Defendant CPD
tries to torture out of the case law permission to
consecrate the Democratic and Republican Parties. See CPD
Memorandum, at 30 n.28. Fortunately, the FECA provisions
cited by CPD, and upheld by the Court in Buckley,
distinguish between "major" and "minor" parties and do not
overtly discriminate on behalf of the Democrats and
Republicans, the way the CPD does. See id.

17/ The prohibition on automatic debate inclusion on the
basis of political party is legitimate and mirrors the
constitutional command. However, by allowing corporate
debate sponsors to take political party into account at all
-that is, as one factor in a candidate's favor -- the
regulation runs afoul of the ban on viewpoint-specific
regulation in the political field. There must be objective
criteria applied equally as to all candidates. If political
party could ever be a "plus" factor for a candidate, then
theoretically a minor party candidate otherwise equal in
every respect to a major party candidate could be excluded
while the major party would be included. Such a result
would be aggressively offensive to the First Amendment. See
supra note 18. If the response is that the "political
party" factor could never operate as a "plus" factor, then
the regulation's language allowing it to be weighed so long
as it is not the "sole" factor is simply meaningless and
surplusage.

18/ Arguably this criterion itself is constitutionally
vulnerable since, under the arcane procedures of the
Twelfth Amendment, a presidential candidate who finished
second or third in the electoral college election could
theoretically capture the presidency by prevailing in a
contingent election in the House of Representatives. Such
elections in the House are few and far between -- the last
one was when Thomas Jefferson defeated Aaron Burr in 1800
after a tie in the electoral college.

19/ A candidate who satisfied the first two criteria but
not the third could make a plausible argument that the
Constitution will not tolerate any extra constitutional
criteria in the determination of debate participation, but
the thresholds for qualifying for federal funds have been
upheld already by the Supreme Court, Buckley v. Valeo, 424
U.S. 1, 109-143 (1976) and a legislative definition of
seriousness appears valid at this point. The link between
receiving statutory federal funds to run and debating is
widely accepted. See Senator Dole's remarks quoted in
Federal News Service, Federal Information Systems Corp.,
Sept. 29, 1992. ("A candidate refusing debate under
controlled circumstances should lose his claim on the money
of those he refuses to inform"); Senator Pryor's remarks
(American people "have come to expect debates and they
deserve debates. For those who give and check off that box
on the tax forms each year to the tax collector, we feel
that the least they should -- or that they do expect is a
debate by the candidates for president who receive this
money."). At any rate, this is a question that need not be
settled in the case of Messrs. Perot and Choate since they
have already qualified for federal funding under the
Presidential Campaign Fund Matching Act, 26 U.S.C. Sec. 9001,
et seq., and have received nearly a $30 million payment
from the United States Treasury for the conduct of their
campaign.

20/ See. e.g., Thomas 1. Emerson, Toward a General Theory
of the first Amendment. 72 Yale L.l. 877, 883 (1963)
("Freedom of expression" is "indispensable to the operation
of a democratic form of government. Once one accepts the
premise of the Declaration of Independence -- that
governments derive "their just powers from the consent of
the governed" -- it follows that the governed must, in
order to exercise their rights of consent, have full
freedom of expression both in forming individual judgments
and in forming the common judgment."); Alexander
Meiklejohn, Free Speech and its Relation to Self-Government
(1948) (principle of free speech "is a deduction from the
basic American agreement that public issues shall be
decided by universal suffrage.").

21/ See. e.g., Citizen Perot. Newsweek, November 9. 1992,
at 23, 28 (before Perot reentered the 1992 campaign, "there
was little or no sign that George Bush and Bill Clinton
were prepared to discuss [the] primal issues" of deficit
reduction and generational equity, but deficit reduction
became a leading theme of the Clinton presidency); J. David
Gillespie, Politics at the Periphery, 27 (1993) (showing
how advocacy by losing Socialist Party candidates, like
Eugene V. Debs, of woman suffrage and a progressive income
tax in the early 1900s nonetheless led to the Sixteenth and
Nineteenth Amendments).

22/ See Eleanor Clift and Ginny Carroll, Perot: Pulling the
Race Out of the Mud. Newsweek, Oct. 26, 1992, at 34 (by
focusing attention on the deficit, "Perot . . . helped
elevate the last stage of a race that might otherwise have
been preoccupied entirely with mudslinging.").

23/ See. e.g., David Maraniss, After Latest Repudiation.
Clinton Hopes Past Is Prologue. Washington Post, November
27, 1994, A-1 (observing that Bill Clinton "emerged from"
his first electoral defeat in a congressional election
"with a can't-miss label as the next golden boy of Arkansas
Democratic politics"); Harold Holzer, The Lincoln-Douglas
Debates 24 (1993) (discussing Abraham Lincoln's
unsuccessful run for U.S. Senate in Illinois in 1858 and
his participation in the famous debates with Douglas,
noting the "stubborn historical suspicion that Lincoln
shrewdly used the debates mainly to position himself for
the presidency two years later.").

24/ See Gillespie, supra at 108-09 (explaining how George
Wallace in 1968 was able to deny a popular vote majority to
either Richard Nixon or Hubert Humphrey, sending a national
message).

25/ See. e.g., Dan Balz Democrats Prepared to Contest
Election in All Areas of Country, July 10, 1992 (by
choosing Albert Gore as running mate in 1992, Clinton
picked "someone who ran for president in 1988, and who
experienced some of the intensity, scrutiny, and hardball
tactics of a national campaign," and thus "minimized the
danger of an embarrassment from his running mate"); Laying
the Groundwork, Orlando Sentinel Tribune, Dec. 25, 1992
(explaining selection of Bruce Babbitt, who ran for
president in 1988, as Secretary of Interior as logical
since he rose "from the grass-roots").

26/ The bitter chill cast on third parties by use of the
standard of political electability cuts against the grain
of our constitutional values. As Chief Justice Warren
remarked. "All political ideas cannot and should not be
channeled into the programs of our two major parties.
History has amply proved the virtue of political activity
by minority, dissident groups, who innumerable times have
been in the vanguard of democratic thought and whose
programs were ultimately accepted. Mere unorthodoxy or
dissent from the prevailing mores is not to be condemned."
Sweezy v. New Hampshire, 354 U.S. 234, 251 (1957).

27/ Plaintiffs have been unable to locate any bureau chiefs
who were actually contacted.  See Declarations of Al Ortiz
(CBS Bureau Chief never contacted); R.W. Apple (New York
Times Bureau Chief never contacted); Jim Toedtman (Newsday
Bureau chief never contacted); Peter Beinart (Managing
Editor of New Republic never contacted).

28/ Other CPD members are former elected officials. Kay Orr
is the former Republican Governor of Nebraska. John
Danforth, a distinguished former Republican Senator from
Missouri, is known as a strong Republican partisan. The
other three Commissioners, while not holding office, are
also intimately involved with Democratic or Republican
Party politics -- Antonia Hernandez, President of the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund and
Democratic Party activist; Newton Minow, a lawyer and
former aide to Adlai Stevenson, has been active in
Democratic politics four decades; and Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg is the daughter of former President John F.
Kennedy and President of the John F. Kennedy Library
Foundation.

29/ Senator Coverdell has had a distinguished career in
Republican Party politics. See generally The Almanac of
American Politics 349(1996).

30/ Vucanovich has been a member of the House 1982. In
1994, Vucanovich was chosen by her Republican colleagues to
be the Secretary of the Republican Conference. See
generally The Almanac of American Politics 825 (1996).

31/ Lewis is a famed veteran of the civil rights movement
and a fierce Democratic Party stalwart. See generally The
Almanac of American Politics 368(1996).

32/ The CPD's suggestion that this Court's determination in
Fulani v. Brady, 729 F. Supp. 158, 162 (D.D.C. 1990),
aff'd, 935 F.2d 1324 (D.C. Cir. 1991), is controlling
misses the mark. Fulani. the CPD states, found it
impossible to  say whether a third-party candidate would
suffer injury by missing out on increased political stature
and media attention because it was "doubtful" that major
party candidates would deign to participate in such an
event. The argument is plainly inapposite to plaintiffs, as
Perot participated in the 1992 debates at the agreement of
the major parties, and received a substantial polling bump
as a result of the appearance. See Affidavit of R. Vemey,
Para. 15; Affidavit of G. Black, Paras. 12, 14 and 15.
Furthermore, the Circuit Court found in Fulani that the
plaintiff had alleged "injury in fact," and based its
standing denial solely upon the conclusion that the relief
sought would not redress the injury. 935 F.2d at 1328-29.
As pointed out in plaintiffs' moving brief (p. 23), the
Court's ruling against standing in Fulani is irrelevant to
the instant action, since the plaintiffs here are doing
exactly what the Court suggested that Fulani do in 1988,
i.e. to address the FEC's debate regulation. Id at 1329.

33/ The CPD's assertion that excluding debate participants
is a "process" injury is misguided. The gist of the
argument is that Perot and Choate's injury derives merely
from the fact that the CPD has failed to properly follow
its selection procedures, and has thus injured the public.
What Lujan counsels is that plaintiffs be "among the
injured," Lujan, 504 U.S. at 562 (quoting Sierra Club v.
Morton, 405 U.S. 727, 735 (1972)) and have a "personal
stake in the outcome." Id. (quoting Los Angeles v. Lyons,
461 U.S.95, 101 -02 (1983). The imminent exclusion of Perot
and Choate from the debates is no "conjectural" or
"hypothetical" injury. Lyons, 461 U.S. at 101-02.

34/ See Verified Complaint. Para. 17.

35/ The CPD falsely states that certain of plaintiffs'
arguments "would rule out debates in 1966 that include the
major party candidates." CPD Memorandum, at 45. The truth
is, the Dole and Clinton campaigns are free to stage
debates any time they want, but at their expense. Not only
are self-supported debates lawful under the FECA, the FCC
has ruled that the broadcasting of candidate-paid-for
debates is exempt from the equal opportunities requirements
of the Communication's Act of 1934. See. e.g.,  WCVB-TV, 2
FCC Rcd 4778 (M.M. Burl 1987) (New Hampshire Democratic
Party debates sponsored and controlled by the two sole
participants, Governor Dukakis and Congressman Richard A.
Gephardt). In short, the CPD has no equities in its favor
to continue perpetrating a fraud on the American
electorate. Ordering it to comply with clear cut legal
standards is not cognizable prejudice, and if the major
party candidates want to debate by themselves, they can do
so without illegal campaign contributions paying the costs
and without an indirect subsidy from the Treasury based
upon the CPD's tax exempt status.



</PRE>
