<HtML>
<title>Counsel Connect Web - Hagen v. AOL</title>
<BODY bgcolor=ffffff text="000000" link="000080" vlink="ff0000">
<img width=100 height=92 align=left src="/images/spotlight/spt2.gif"> 
<PRE>

</PRE>
<P>Editor's Note: This stipulation provides more detail on the settlement
between America Online and a class of users alleging that AOL used unfair
billing practices.</P>
<PRE>



</PRE>

<B><P>SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA COUNTY OF SAN FRANCISCO </P>

<P>STEPHEN E. HAGEN, et al., individually, as private attorneys general, and
on behalf of all 12 others similarly situated, </P>

<P>Plaintiffs,</P>

<P>v.</P>

<P>AMERICA ONLINE, INC., et al.,</P>

<P>Defendants.</P>

<P>No. 971047</P>

<P>Class Action</P>

<P>STIPULATION OF SETTLEMENT</P></B>


<P>This Stipulation of Settlement and Exhibits (the "Stipulation") is made by
and among individual and representative plaintiffs Stephen Anderson, Todd
Bandrowsky, John Przygoda, Steven Craig Smith, Paul Boni, Frederick J.
DiMarco, David L. Feige, First M. Corp., Fred Glick, Stephen E. Hagen, Marc
L. Hoffman, Craig Smith, Kenneth Crystal, and Heather Buchfirer
(collectively, the "Plaintiffs"), on behalf of themselves, and on behalf of
the Settlement Class as defined herein, on the one hand, and defendant
America Online, Inc. ("America Online"), a Delaware corporation, on the
other hand, by and through their respective counsel. </P>


<P><H3>I. BACKGROUND</H3></P>

<P>A. On July 14, 1995, Stephen Hagen commenced the action entitled Stephen
Hagen v. America Online. Inc., Superior Court of California, City and
County of San Francisco, Case No. 971047, which included allegations
regarding the charges for and disclosures about America Online services, as
more fully set forth below; </P>

<P>B. After July 14, 1995, the following additional actions were filed against
America Online making similar allegations (collectively, the "Actions"):
Stephen Anderson v. America Online, Inc., Superior Court of California,
County of San Diego, No. 693803; Todd Bandrowsky, John Przygoda, and
Stephen Craig Smith v. America Online. Inc., Superior Court of New Jersey,
Law Division, Burlington County No. L-2441-95; Paul Boni v. America Online,
Inc., Superior Court of Delaware, New Castle County, No. 95C-07-142;
Kenneth Crystal and Heather Buchfirer v. America Online. Inc., Superior
Court of Massachusetts, Suffolk Division No. 95-8095B; Frederick J. DiMarco
v. America Online, Inc., Superior Court of New Jersey, Burlington County
No. Bur-L-2439-95; David L. Feige v. America Online, Inc., Supreme Court of
New York, New York County, No. 95-118333; First M. Corp. v. America Online.
Inc., Chancery Court of Delaware, New Castle County, No. 14476; Glick v.
America Online, Inc., Pennsylvania Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia
County, Civil Division, No. 95-10-0074; Marc L. Hoffman v. America Online.
Inc., Pennsylvania Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Civil
Division, No. 95-08-SD-0076; and Craig Smith v. America Online. Inc.,
Pennsylvania Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Civil Division,
No. 95-08-SD-0059. The Actions assert, inter alia, purported claims against
America Online for common law fraud and negligent misrepresentation, breach
of contract, unjust enrichment, and alleged violations of state consumer
protection and consumer fraud statutes. </P>

<P>C. In connection with settlement, the Plaintiffs are filing an Amended
Complaint in the Hagen Action, on behalf of all of the Plaintiffs, in the
form attached as Exhibit 8 to this Stipulation (the "Amended Complaint"),
including allegations that America Online did not adequately disclose its
policies of adding a fifteen-second connection and disconnection time to
the length of each session for billing purposes, and of billing customers
in one-minute increments rounded up to the nearest minute; that America
Online's billing methods and practices caused subscribers to incur
additional charges for downloading of image files, for delays in connection
time caused by America Online software, and for time spent in "free" areas;
that America Online failed to refund unused membership charges to customers
who cancel their subscriptions prior to the end of a billing period; that
customers who canceled their subscriptions near the end of a billing period
were erroneously charged for an additional monthly fee; that America
Online's billing system unfairly calculated service charges on a
per-session basis; that America Online made withdrawals from customers'
checking accounts without proper authorization; and that America Online's
advertising of its hourly rate as $2.95 per hour was misleading
(collectively, the "Claims"). As used throughout this stipulation, the
"Hagen Action" shall refer to the Hagen Action, including the Amended
Complaint. </P>

<P>D. Plaintiffs have engaged in an investigation of the claims underlying the
Actions, including reviews of America Online documents, and interviews with
representatives, officers, and employees of America Online. Plaintiffs'
counsel's investigation was conducted with the assistance of technical
experts to assist them in their investigation of America Online practices. </P>

<P>E. In March 1996, pursuant to an understanding reached by the parties,
America Online made certain changes to its online disclosures, which
addressed a number of the allegations raised in the Actions. </P>

<P>F. On April 4, 1996, the Hagen Action was assigned to Plan 3, and on April
17, 1996, Judge A. James Robertson, II was appointed as Plan 3 Judge. </P>

<P>G. On May 7, 1996 and on June 7, 1996, counsel for the parties in the Hagen
Action met with Judge Robertson at informal status conferences. </P>

<P>H. Plaintiffs have now completed their investigation, and the parties have
reached an agreement on the terms of the settlement set out in this
Stipulation. </P>

<P>I. Plaintiffs' counsel have examined the benefits to be obtained under the
terms of the proposed Settlement and have considered the costs, risks and
delays associated with the continued prosecution of this litigation and the
likely appeals of any rulings. Plaintiffs' counsel believe that, in
consideration of all the circumstances and after prolonged and serious
arms' length negotiations with America Online, the proposed Settlement
embodied in this Stipulation is fair, reasonable, adequate and in the best
interest of all members of the Settlement Class, as defined below. </P>

<P>J. America Online vigorously denies all liability with respect to any and
all of the facts or Claims alleged in the Actions, denies that its billing
practices or any of its actions were at any time unlawful, unfair, or
fraudulent, denies that it breached any contract, generally denies that it
engaged in any wrongdoing, and contends that it has agreed to the
settlement embodied in this Stipulation and Exhibits thereto (the
"Settlement") in order to avoid needless litigation costs and disruption.
While America Online vigorously denies the allegations of the Amended
Complaint, America Online acknowledges that the terms and conditions of the
Settlement were agreed to as a result of the efforts of Plaintiffs and
their counsel after extensive negotiations between the parties. The parties
agree that certain of the consideration to be approved as part of this
Stipulation has either already been implemented or will be implemented
before the Effective Date, as defined below, because of the need for
providing prompt and expeditious relief to members of the Settlement Class
and the general public. </P>

<P>NOW, THEREFORE, IT IS HEREBY AGREED by and between the parties, through
their respective counsel, that the Actions be dismissed with prejudice,
settled or compromised as applicable on the terms set forth herein, as
between Plaintiffs and the Settlement Class Members, as defined below, and
America Online, upon approval of the Court in the Hagen Action after
hearing as provided for in this Stipulation, all on the following terms and
conditions: </P>


<P><H3>II. DEFINITIONS</H3></P>

<P>In addition to the foregoing defined terms, the following terms shall have
the meanings as set forth below: </P>

<P>A. "America Online Services" means the proprietary subscription service
providing access to America Online's databases and communication and
information services, including electronic mail, computer conversations
about numerous topics, access to information, access to publications,
entertainment, and access to the Internet. </P>

<P>B. "Class Period" means the period beginning on July 14, 1991, and ending
on March 31, 1996. </P>

<P>C. "Defendants" means America Online, Steve Case and James Kimsey. </P>

<P>D. "Effective Date" means the first date after which all of the following
events and conditions have been met or have occurred: </P>

<P>1. All parties have executed this Stipulation; </P>

<P>2. The Amended Complaint, in the form attached as Exhibit 8 to this
Stipulation, has been filed in the Hagen Action; </P>

<P>3. The Court in the Hagen Action has preliminarily approved this
Stipulation and the method for providing notice to the Settlement Class by
entry of an order substantially in the form attached hereto as Exhibit 1 </P>

<P>4. The Court in the Hagen Action has entered a judgment and order of
dismissal substantially in the form attached hereto as Exhibit 2 ("Final
Judgment and Order of Dismissal"), finally approving this Stipulation,
releasing the Released Parties from the Released Claims, and dismissing
with prejudice the Hagen Action and all claims asserted therein against the
Defendants; </P>

<P>5. The Final Judgment and Order of Dismissal has become Final, as defined
in paragraph II(E), below; </P>

<P>6. The orders of dismissal in the Actions other than the Hagen Action have
become Final, as defined in paragraph II(E), below; </P>

<P>7. Plaintiffs' counsel has verified in writing that fewer than a certain
number (the "Tip-Over Number") of the potential Settlement Class Members
have requested exclusion from the Settlement Class. The Tip-Over Number
shall be stated in a confidential letter from Defendants' counsel to
Plaintiffs' counsel prior to the signing of this Stipulation. In the event
that any of the events or conditions listed in paragraphs II(D)(1-7),
above, are not met or do not occur, this entire Stipulation shall become
null and void, except that America Online shall have the option to give
written notice to Plaintiffs' undersigned counsel that Defendants elect to
proceed with such settlement' in which event the Effective Date shall be
deemed to have occurred on the date of said notice. </P>

<P>E. "Final" means the latest of: (i) the date of final affirmance on an
appeal, the expiration of the time for a petition of certiorari and, if
certiorari is granted, the date of final affirmance following review
pursuant to that grant; or (ii) the date of final dismissal of any appeal
or the final dismissal of any proceeding on certiorari; or (iii) if no
appeal is filed, the expiration date of the time for the filing or noticing
of any appeal from the court's judgment dismissing the action. </P>

<P>F. "Heavy User" means a Settlement Class Member who paid $300.00 or more in
charges to America Online during the Class Period. </P>

<P>G. "Person" means any natural person, individual, corporation, association,
partnership, trust, or any other type of legal entity. </P>

<P>H. "Released Claims" means any and all claims, rights (including rights to
reimbursement or restitution), demands, actions, causes of action, suits,
makers, issues, debts, liens, contracts, liabilities, agreements, costs,
expenses or losses of any nature, including Unknown Claims, whether under
Federal law or regulation, or the laws or regulations of any and all states
or subdivisions, which are alleged in the Amended Complaint, or which could
or might have been alleged in the Amended Complaint and arise out of or are
related to the makers referred to in the Amended Complaint. </P>

<P>I. "Released Parties" means the Defendants, and each of the Defendants'
past and present officers, directors, or employees, and their predecessors,
successors, parents, subsidiaries, affiliates, agents, attorneys,
accountants, spouses, advisors, representatives, partners, heirs and
assigns. </P>

<P>J. "Settlement Class" means all persons in the United States who at any
time during the Class Period were Subscribers of America Online Services. </P>

<P>K. "Settlement Class Member" means a person who fits within the definition
of the Settlement Class who has not validly and timely requested exclusion
from the Settlement Class pursuant to paragraph IV, below. </P>

<P>L. "Subscriber" means a person who has been a customer of America Online
Services. </P>

<P>M. "Unknown Claims" means any Claims which a Plaintiff or Settlement Class
Member does not know or suspect to exist in his or her favor at the time of
the release of the Released Persons which, if known by him, her or it,
might have affected his/her or its settlement with and release of the
Released Persons, or might have affected his, her or its decision not to
object to this Stipulation. </P>


<P><H3>III. APPOINTMENT OF LEAD COUNSEL AND CERTIFICATION OF PLAINTIFF CLASS</H3> </P>

<P>A. For settlement purposes only, the parties agree, and the parties shall
request, that as part of the Settlement Notice and Hearing Order referred
to herein, the Court in the Hagen Action enter an order certifying the
Settlement Class, appointing Plaintiffs as representatives of the
Settlement Class, and appointing the following Plaintiffs' Counsel as
co-lead counsel: </P>

<P>Brian W. Newcomb<BR>
Attorney At Law<BR>
770 Menlo Avenue, Suite 101<BR>
Menlo Park, California 94025<BR>
Telephone: (415) 322-7780<BR>
Facsimile: (415) 327-0619</P>

<P>Stephen E. Hagen<BR>
Attorney At Law<BR>
1436 Hamilton Avenue<BR>
Palo Alto, California 94301<BR>
Telephone: (415) 324-3300<BR>
Facsimile: (415) 327-1719</P>

<P>Bernstein Litowitz Berger & Grossmann LLP Max W. Berger Rochelle Feder
Hansen 1285 Avenue of the Americas New York, New York 10019 Telephone:
(212) 554-1400 Facsimile:(212) 554-1444 </P>

<P>Zwerling, Schachter, Zwerling & Koppell, LLP G. Oliver Koppell Oren S.
Giskan 767 Third Avenue New York, New York 10017 Telephone: (212) 223-3900
Facsimile: (212) 371-5969 </P>

<P>B. For settlement purposes only, the complaint in the Hagen Action shall be
deemed amended in the manner provided in the Amended Complaint attached as
Exhibit 8 hereto. The allegations in Exhibit 8 shall be deemed to be
generally denied by the Defendants. </P>

<P>C. America Online does not consent to certification of the Settlement
Class, or the filing of the Amended Complaint in the Hagen Action, for any
purpose other than to effectuate the settlement or dismissal of the
Actions. Nor does America Online waive any argument regarding whether
California is a proper forum other than to effectuate this Settlement. If
this Stipulation is terminated pursuant to its terms, the Effective Date
does not occur, or for any reason the Settlement described in this
Stipulation is not effectuated, any order certifying the Settlement Class
shall be vacated upon notice of termination of the Settlement to the Court,
the Amended Complaint withdrawn and the original complaint reinstated in
the Hagen Action, and the Actions shall proceed as though the Settlement
Class had never been certified and the Amended Complaint had never been
filed, without prejudice to any party to either request or oppose class
certification, or to oppose the appropriateness of any of the fore in which
the Actions have been brought. </P>


<P><H3>IV. ENTRY OF SETTLEMENT NOTICE AND HEARING ORDER AND NOTICE TO THE
SETTLEMENT CLASS</H3> </P>

<P>Promptly upon execution of the Stipulation, the parties shall jointly apply
to the Court in the Hagen Action for entry of an Order in the form of
Exhibit 1 hereto (the "Settlement Notice and Hearing Order"): </P>

<P>A. Finding that the Hagen Action meets all the prerequisites of Section 382
of the California Code of Civil Procedure, including numerosity,
ascertainability, community of interest, predominance of common issues, and
typicality, and that Plaintiffs and their counsel are adequate
representatives of the Settlement Class, and certifying the Hagen Action
for settlement purposes only; </P>

<P>B. Approving the form of the Notice to the Settlement Class (the "Notice")
substantially in the form annexed hereto as Exhibit 7; and ordering that
the Notice to the Settlement Class be disseminated substantially in the
manner set forth in the Settlement Notice and Hearing Order; </P>

<P>C. Approving the form of the Final Judgment and Order of Dismissal, the
Proof of Claim for participation by Former Users in the Settlement, and the
Notice, substantially in the forms attached as Exhibits 2, 6 and 7 hereto; </P>

<P>D. Providing that members of the Settlement Class who do not file valid and
timely requests for exclusion will be bound by the Final Judgment and Order
of Dismissal dismissing the Hagen Action on the merits and with prejudice; </P>

<P>E. Finding that the notice to be given in accordance with the Settlement
Hearing and Notice Order constitutes the best notice practicable under the
circumstances and constitutes valid, due and sufficient notice to all
members of the Settlement Class, complying fully with the requirements of
Section 382 of the California Code of Civil Procedure, the California
Constitution and the Constitution of the United States, and any other
applicable law; </P>

<P>F. Scheduling a hearing (the "Final Settlement Hearing") to be held by the
Court in the Hagen Action to consider and determine whether the proposed
Settlement under the terms of this Stipulation should be approved as fair,
reasonable and adequate, and whether a judgment approving the Settlement
and dismissing the Hagen Action on the merits and with prejudice, against
Plaintiffs and Settlement Class Members, should be entered, and to consider
Plaintiffs' request for payment of attorney's fees and reimbursement of
expenses; </P>

<P>G. Providing that the Final Settlement Hearing may, from time to time and
without further notice to the Settlement Class, be continued or adjourned
by order of the Court; and </P>

<P>H. Providing that objections by any Settlement Class Member to the proposed
Settlement or the payment of attorneys' fees and reimbursement of expenses
to Plaintiffs' counsel, shall be heard and any papers submitted in support
of said objections shall be considered by the Court at the Final Settlement
Hearing only if, on or before a date to specified in the Settlement Notice
and Hearing Order, such objector files with the Court a written notice of
his, her or its intention to appear, submits documentary proof that he, she
or it is a member of the Settlement Class, states the basis for the
objections, and serves copies of the foregoing papers and all other papers
in support of objections upon counsel for the parties, as directed by the
Notice, in such a manner as to ensure that such papers are actually
received by designated counsel by the deadline set by the Court in the
Settlement Notice and Hearing Order. </P>


<P><H3>V.  AMERICA ONLINE'S OBLIGATIONS UNDER THE SETTLEMENT</H3> </P>

<P>In consideration for the agreement to resolve and have judgment entered in
the Hagen Action and to dismiss all of the Actions other than the Hagen
Action under the terms of this Stipulation, and to entry of the Final
Judgment and Orders of Dismissal in all of the Actions, releasing all
Released Claims against the Released Parties, and after providing notice to
the Settlement Class in accordance with the terms of the Settlement Notice
and Hearing Order and holding a Final Settlement Hearing, America Online,
on behalf of the Defendants, agrees to the following: </P>

<P>A. Disclosures: Except as provided below in V(A)(2)(iii), V(A)(3)(i) and
V(A)(3)(iii), commencing upon execution of this stipulation by all
Plaintiffs' counsel and for a period ending no earlier than one year after
the Effective Date, America Online will make available the following
information as part of America Online's online service: </P>

<P>1. Additional Billing Disclosures: America Online will provide general
information relating to its billing practices, together with disclosures in
its Terms of Service Agreement, in a manner substantially as provided in
Exhibit 3 hereto. </P>

<P>2. Rounding Up: So long as America Online maintains its practice of
charging subscribers in one minute increments by rounding up the online
time for each session to the nearest whole minute: (i) America Online will
include in the information provided in its online billing information
screens a disclosure that the subscriber will be charged in one-minute
increments by rounding up the length of each session to the nearest whole
minute, in a manner substantially as provided in Exhibit 3 hereto; (ii)
America Online will include a disclosure as part of the clock screen that
can be accessed during an America Online session (the "Online Clock")
indicating that the online time is an estimate only, and that the
subscriber should see keyword Billing for billing policies, in a manner
substantially as provided in Exhibit 3 hereto; and (iii) America Online
shall, commencing two weeks after this Stipulation is executed by all of
the parties hereto, include a message at the end of a session (the "End of
Session Message") which indicates the subscriber's total billed time online
for the session after rounding up to the nearest whole minute. </P>

<P>3. Connection/Disconnection Time: So long as America Online maintains its
practice of adding to the subscriber's total time online fifteen-seconds or
some other amount of time as a charge for connection/disconnection: (i)
America Online shall, commencing two weeks after this Stipulation is
executed by the parties hereto, include in the information provided in its
online billing information screens a disclosure that the length of each
session will include the additional time charged, in a manner substantially
as provided in Exhibit 3 hereto; (ii) America Online will include a
disclosure as part of the Online Clock indicating that the online time is
an estimate only, and that the subscriber should see keyword Billing for
billing policies, in a manner substantially as provided in Exhibit 3
hereto; and (iii) America Online shall, commencing two weeks after this
Stipulation is executed by all of the parties hereto, include an End of
Session Message which indicates the subscriber's total billed time online
for the session after adding any amount of time as a charge for
connection/disconnection. </P>

<P>4. Cancellation of Accounts: So long as America Online maintains its
current practice of canceling subscriber's accounts within a reasonable
time after receipt of a request for cancellation, America Online's online
information will include a disclosure, in a manner substantially as
provided in Exhibit 3 hereto, that (1) if a subscriber decides to cancel
his or her account, America Online will cancel the account within a
reasonable time after receipt of the notification of termination; (2) the
subscriber has already been billed for service through the end of the
current billing month, and such amount will not be refunded; (3) a
subscriber who cancels within the last 72 hours of a billing month may be
erroneously charged an additional monthly fee; and (4) if the subscriber
has a problem with termination of the account, has been erroneously billed,
or wishes to handle termination by telephone, he or she may call a 1-800
telephone number, to be provided by America Online, for assistance. America
Online will include in the materials used to train its telephone
representatives an instruction that subscribers who call to cancel their
account at a time when America Online cannot immediately process the
request for cancellation should be informed that America Online will
process the request within a reasonable time, and that the subscriber
should check to ensure that the cancellation was processed properly. </P>

<P>5. Current Bill Summary: During the first session of a subscriber's billing
month, the Current Bill Summary available as part of America Online's
service will indicate that this is the first session of a new billing
period and that only in subsequent sessions can the subscriber view the
Current Bill Summary screen to see the amount of unused time remaining in
the billing month, in a manner substantially as provided in Exhibit 3
hereto. America Online will include in the information provided in the
"Explain Billing Terms" screen a disclosure that its billing period ends at
10:00 a.m. Eastern time on the last day of the billing period. </P>

<P>B. Current Users: During the period beginning on the Effective Date and
ending 30 days after the Effective Date: </P>

<P>1. America Online will credit the accounts of Settlement Class Members who
have open America Online accounts at the time of crediting ("Current
Users") with one hour of additional free time (in addition to the time
included in the monthly minimum service charge), to be used within a
four-month period after such time is credited to each subscriber. </P>

<P>2. America Online will credit 1.36 million free hours to the accounts of
Current Users who, based on America Online's computerized records as of May
5, 1996 ("the Database"), qualify as Heavy Users, to be used within a
four-month period after such time is credited to each subscriber. The
amount of free time credited to each such Current User's account will be
determined according to the formula described in Exhibit 4. </P>

<P>C. Former Users: Following the Effective Date, America Online will provide
to Settlement Class Members who are not Current Users ("Former Users") as
follows: </P>

<P>1. America Online will pay up to $500,000 in cash for claims made by Former
Users who submit, pursuant to paragraph V(C)(3), below, Proofs of Claim
verifying that each is a Heavy User. The amount to be paid by America
Online to each such claimant will be determined based on the formula
described in Exhibit 5. In the event the total dollar amount of all valid
claims exceeds $500,000, the claims will be prorated so that the total
amount paid by America Online for all claims equals $500,000. In the event
the total dollar amount of all valid claims is less than $500,000, the
remainder will be used to pay for the review provided in paragraph VI(C),
below. In the event that the total amount of all valid claims plus the cost
for such review is less than $500,000, the remainder will be paid to
consumer-oriented charitable organizations engaged in issues involving the
online and Internet media, subject to Plaintiffs' consent, which will not
unreasonably be withheld. </P>

<P>2. Former Users who are not Heavy Users or who do not wish to make a claim
under paragraph V(C)(I), above, and who re-subscribe within four months
after the Effective Date, shall, upon request and affirmation that they
were subscribers of America Online Services during the Class Period, have
each of their accounts credited, upon re-subscription, with an additional
one hour of free time (in addition to the time provided to such individuals
for re-subscribing) to be used within the first four months after
re-subscription. Nothing in this agreement requires any change by America
Online in its standards for re-subscription. </P>

<P>3. Each Settlement Class Member who is a Former User and who wishes to
participate in the Settlement shall submit to America Online a Proof of
Claim substantially in the form of Exhibit 6 hereto, according to the
procedures set out in Exhibit 6 hereto. To be valid, a Proof of Claim must
be: (1) completed in a manner that permits America Online to determine that
the claimant is a Former User and is otherwise eligible to make a claim;
(2) signed with an affirmation that the information provided is true and
correct; and (3) postmarked for delivery to America Online no later than
the date set forth in the Settlement Notice and Hearing Order. </P>

<P>D. The disclosures, distributions, and other consideration described in
paragraphs V and VI, and the attorneys' fees and expenses described in
paragraph IX, are the only consideration America Online shall give on
behalf of the Defendants, in connection with this Settlement. </P>


<P><H3>VI. NOTICE AND ADMINISTRATION COSTS</H3></P>

<P>A. America Online shall be responsible for providing notice to the
Settlement Class, in the manner set forth in the Settlement Notice and
Hearing Order. America Online shall pay all costs for providing such
notice. </P>

<P>B. America Online shall be responsible for the administrative costs which
arise from the following: </P>

<P>1. Distributing Proof of Claim forms to Settlement Class Members who
request them; </P>

<P>2. Obtaining and maintaining a post office box for the receipt of Proofs of
Claim; </P>

<P>3. Maintaining custody of all Proofs of Claim and the envelopes in which
they were sent; </P>

<P>4. Calculating, based on the Proofs of Claim submitted, the total amount of
all valid claims; </P>

<P>5. Calculating, pursuant to paragraph V(C)(I), the amount to be paid to
each claimant who submits a valid claim; </P>

<P>6. Distributing checks to each claimant who submits a valid claim; and </P>

<P>7. Providing a 1-800 telephone number to respond to requests by Class
Members regarding Proofs of Claim and/or other similar administrative
matters. </P>

<P>C. A large-sized national accounting firm which does not provide services
to America Online and who is agreeable to the parties, shall review the
administrative tasks referred to in paragraph VI(B) and the crediting of
free time to Current Users referred to in V(B) to reasonably assure that
these benefits have been properly completed. America Online will pay up to
$50,000 for the cost of said review provided, however, if the reasonable
costs of such review were to exceed $50,000, America Online will pay
subject to Court order, up to an additional $25,000 for such review. </P>


<P><H3>VII. THE FINAL JUDGMENT AND ORDERS OF DISMISSAL</H3> </P>

<P>A. Upon the preliminary approval of this settlement by the Court in the
Hagen Action by entry of an order substantially in the form of Exhibit I
hereto, all discovery and other proceedings in the Hagen Action shall be
stayed until further order of the Court, except such proceedings as may be
necessary to implement the settlement or comply with or effectuate the
terms of this Stipulation. </P>

<P>B. As soon as practicable after execution of this Stipulation, Plaintiffs
in each of the Actions other than the Hagen Action (the "Other Actions")
shall stipulate to the entry and submit to each of the courts in which the
Other Actions are pending an order dismissing with prejudice all claims
against the Defendants, subject to final non-appealable approval of the
Settlement. Each order of dismissal shall provide for the dismissal of each
action without costs being awarded to either party. If court approval is
necessary to dismiss any of the Other Actions, Plaintiffs' counsel shall
use their best efforts to obtain such an order on the grounds that such
actions are being resolved as part of the Settlement set forth in this
Stipulation. Plaintiffs in all of the Actions agree not to request
exclusion from the Settlement Class. Upon the final approval of this
Stipulation and the settlement set forth herein by the Court in the Hagen
Action the Final Judgment and Order of Dismissal in substantially the form
attached hereto as Exhibit 2 shall be entered providing for the dismissal
with prejudice and the release by Plaintiffs and the Settlement Class of
all Released Claims against all Released Parties. </P>


<P><H3>VIII. RELEASES</H3></P>

<P>A. Upon the Effective Date, the Plaintiffs, for themselves and as
representatives of the Settlement Class, and on behalf of each Settlement
Class Member and their respective agents, successors, heirs, or assigns,
shall be deemed to have, and by operation of the Final Judgment and Order
of Dismissal in the Hagen Action, shall have fully, finally, and forever
released, relinquished and discharged all Released Claims against the
Released Parties. </P>

<P>B. Upon the Effective Date, the Plaintiffs, on their own behalf and on
behalf of all Settlement Class Members, represent and acknowledge that they
fully understand that if any fact relating to any matter covered by this
Stipulation is found hereafter to be other than or different from the facts
now believed by any of them to be true, that each of them expressly accepts
and assumes the risk of such possible differences in fact and agrees that
this Stipulation shall nevertheless remain in effect, and that each such
person expressly waives all of the rights and benefits of Section 1542 of
the California Civil Code, which reads as follows: </P>


<P>"Section 1542. Certain Claims Not Affected by General Release. A general
release does not extend to claims which the creditor does not know or
suspect to exist in his favor at the time of executing the release, which
if known by him must have materially affected his settlement with the
debtor." </P>


<P>C. Each of the Plaintiffs and the Settlement Class Members, upon the
Effective Date, shall be deemed to have, and by operation of the Final
Judgment and Order of Dismissal in the Hagen Action shall have waived any
and all provisions, rights and benefits conferred by Section 1542 of the
California Civil Code or any law of any state or territory of the United
States, or principle of common law, which is similar, comparable or
equivalent to Section 1542 of the California Civil Code. </P>


<P><H3>IX. ATTORNEYS' FEES AND DISBURSEMENT OF EXPENSES</H3> </P>

<P>A. As part of the Settlement, counsel for Plaintiffs and the Settlement
Class request payment for both attorneys' fees and reimbursement of
reasonable expenses in an amount not to exceed $2,750,000. America Online
has agreed not to oppose either in Court or in any public forum the request
for payment of fees and reimbursement of expenses not exceeding $2,750,000.
Within 5 days after the entry by the Court of the Settlement Notice and
Hearing Order, defendant America Online shall transfer $2,750,000 into a
trustee account in the name of Morrison & Foerster ("Trust Fund") with
interest to run from the date the Court approves the fees. Nothing
regarding the Court's decision on the application for attorneys' fees and
expenses shall operate to terminate or cancel this Stipulation or have any
effect on the Final Judgment. </P>

<P>B. Plaintiffs' counsel agree that they will not seek any additional fees or
costs from any of the Defendants. If any application is made to any court
by any other Person for an award of attorneys' fees or expenses with regard
to the settlement or the claims settled thereby, Defendants shall not be
restricted from opposing it. </P>

<P>C. America Online, on behalf of the Defendants, will pay out of said Trust
Fund, within five business days after the Effective Date, the fees and
expenses actually ordered by the Court in the Hagen Action up to the
foregoing maximum amount together with interest on approved fees as
provided in paragraph IX(A). </P>

<P>D. Other than the attorneys' fees and reimbursement of expenses described
in paragraphs IX(A-C), America Online will have no obligation to pay any
attorneys' fees or reimbursement of expenses to any of the Plaintiffs or
their counsel. </P>


<P><H3>X. DEFENDANTS' DENIAL OF LIABILITY</H3></P>

<P>A.   Defendants have indicated their intent vigorously to contest each and
every claim in the Action. Defendants maintain that they have consistently
acted in accordance with governing laws at all times and further maintain
that there has been no finding of any wrongdoing of any kind on Defendants'
part. Defendants continue vigorously to deny all of the material
allegations in the Amended Complaint, and assert that the Claims are
without merit. Defendants nonetheless have concluded that it is in their
best interest that the Actions be settled on the terms and conditions set
forth in this Stipulation. Defendants claim that they reached that
conclusion after considering the factual and legal issues in the Action,
the substantial benefits of a final resolution of the Action, the expense
that would be necessary to prosecute the Action through trial and through
any appeals that might be taken, the benefits of disposing of protracted
and complex litigation, and the desire of Defendants to conduct their
business unhampered by the distractions of continued litigation. </P>

<P>B. Defendants enter into this Stipulation without in any way acknowledging
any fault, liability, or wrongdoing of any kind. Neither this Stipulation,
nor any of its terms or provisions, nor any of the negotiations or
proceedings connected with it, shall be construed as an admission or
concession by Defendants of the truth of any of the allegations in any of
the Actions, or of any liability, fault, or wrongdoing of any kind. </P>

<P>C. Neither this Stipulation, nor any of its terms or provisions, nor the
Final Judgment, shall constitute an admission by the Defendants of any
liability of wrongdoing whatsoever, nor is this Stipulation a finding of
the validity or invalidity of any Claims in the Actions or a finding of any
wrongdoing by the Defendants. Neither this Stipulation nor the Final
Judgment shall be used or construed as an admission, concession, or
presumption or inference of any fault, liability or wrongdoing by any
Person. Neither the Final Judgment, this Stipulation, the fact of
settlement and the settlement proceedings, nor the settlement negotiations,
nor any related document, shall be offered or received in evidence as an
admission, concession, or presumption or inference against any party in any
proceeding other than (i) in such proceedings as may be necessary to
consummate or enforce this Stipulation, or (ii) in any subsequent action
against or by the Released Parties, or any of them, to support a defense of
res judicata, collateral estoppel, release, or other theory of claim
preclusion, issue preclusion, or similar defense. </P>


<P><H3>XI. OTHER PROVISIONS OF THE SETTLEMENT</H3></P>

<P>A. Upon the entry of the Settlement Notice and Hearing Order, the parties
and their undersigned counsel agree to undertake their best efforts to
immediately dismiss, stay or abate all discovery, injunction proceedings
and other proceedings and court deadlines in the Hagen Action and in each
of the other Actions, except such formal or informal proceedings by the
parties in the Hagen Action that may be necessary either to implement this
Settlement or to comply with or effectuate the terms of this Stipulation. </P>

<P>B. Within seven (7) business days after the deadline established by the
Court in the Settlement Notice and Hearing Order for members of the
Settlement Class to request exclusion from the Settlement Class,
Plaintiffs' Counsel shall furnish America Online's counsel with a complete
list of all timely and valid requests for exclusion received by Plaintiffs'
Counsel. Counsel for the parties shall cooperate to the fullest extent
possible to ensure that a complete list of requests for exclusion is
compiled for the Court by the time of the Final Settlement Hearing. </P>

<P>C. In the event that this Settlement Stipulation is not approved by the
Court in its present form, or the conditions required for the settlement to
be consummated do not occur, then the parties hereto, including all
plaintiffs in the Non-California Actions, shall be restored to their
respective positions as of June 20, 1996, the terms and provisions of the
Settlement Stipulation shall have no further force and effect with respect
to the parties and, to the extent permitted by law, shall not be used in
any action or proceeding for any purpose and any orders entered by the
Court in accordance with the terms of the Settlement Stipulation shall be
treated as vacated, nunc pro tune. </P>

<P>D. The parties acknowledge that it is their intent to consummate this
Stipulation and agree to cooperate to the extent necessary to effectuate
and implement all terms and conditions of the Stipulation and to exercise
their best efforts to accomplish the foregoing terms and conditions of the
Stipulation. </P>

<P>E. Plaintiffs and their counsel shall not encourage any third party to
institute any claims or litigation against any party hereto that in any way
relates to any activities or practices that are the same or similar to
those underlying the Actions. </P>

<P>F. All of the exhibits to this Stipulation are material and integral parts
hereof, and are fully incorporated herein by reference. </P>

<P>G. The undersigned counsel represent that they are fully authorized to
execute and enter into the terms and conditions of this Stipulation on
behalf of their respective clients. </P>

<P>H. This Stipulation (along with the exhibits thereto) contains the entire
agreement among the parties hereto and supersedes any prior agreements or
understandings between them. All terms of this Stipulation are contractual
and not mere recitals and shall be construed as if drafted by all parties
hereto. The terms of this Stipulation are and shall be binding upon and
inure to the benefit of each of the parties hereto, their agents,
attorneys, employees, heirs, successors, and assigns, and upon all other
persons claiming any interest in the subject matter hereto through any of
the parties hereto, including any Plaintiff or Settlement Class Member.
This Stipulation may be amended or modified only by a written instrument
signed by or on behalf of all parties hereto or their successors in
interest. Amendments and modifications may be made without notice to the
Settlement Class, unless notice is required by the Court. </P>

<P>J. This Stipulation may be executed in counterparts or by fax, with each
counterpart or fax signature having the same force and effect as an
original. All executed counterparts and each of them shall be deemed to be
one and the same Instrument. Counsel for the parties to this  Stipulation
shall exchange among themselves original signed counterparts and a complete
set of original executed counterparts shall be filed with the Court in the
Hagen Action. </P>

<P>K. The Court in the Hagen Action shall have exclusive and continuing
jurisdiction over the implementation, interpretation, and execution of this
Stipulation and all exhibits thereto, with respect to all parties hereto,
including all Settlement Class Members. </P>

<P>L. The rights and obligations of the parties to the Stipulation shall
construed and enforced in accordance with, and governed by the laws of the
State of California. </P>

<P>Dated: June 20, 1996</P><HR>
