<P>           Questions Presented</P>

<P> 1.   Should the federal judiciary discard the teaching of Regentsof the
University of California v. Bakke, and prohibit state institutions of
higher learning from even considering race, among other factors, in
individualized admissions decisions, despite the institutions' long-settled
educational interest in promoting dialogue and learning by selecting a
diverse student body with varied backgrounds and experiences?</P>

<P> 2.   When a State's officials determine that they have a sufficient
evidentiary basis for concluding that remedial race-conscious action is
needed at one of the State's graduate schools, which itself had practiced
de jure discrimination in the past, and whose legacy of having done so
continues to affect its ability to attract and educate the best students of
all races, do the Fourteenth Amendment and principles of federalism permit
the federal judiciary: (a) to insist that those officials disregard the
additional current effects, on that graduate school's applicant pool, of de
jure discrimination in the public education of Blacks and Mexican Americans
in that State at the primary, secondary, and college levels, and (b) to
demand that those officials heed only findings made by the State
Legislature itself rather than, as state law permits, acting on findings
made by the Governor and the State Higher Education Coordinating Board?</P>

<P> 3.   Are Texas higher education admissions officials, following United
States v. Fordice, precluded from taking race into consideration even
though a race-blind admissions process would predictably recreate a system
that is effectively segregated, with almost no minorities at the State's
flagship law school and almost no white students at the law school that the
State created to avoid integration?</P>


<P> 4.   Is Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, enacted under the
Spending Clause of Article I, capable of abrogating a State's Eleventh
Amendment immunity from suit in federal court without its consent, in light
of Seminole Tribe of Florida v. Florida?</P>

<P> 5.   May a federal court, consistent with Carey v. Piphus, impose a
presumption of compensatory damages for plaintiffs who complain of the
process that was applied to them, but who have not shown any likelihood
that they would have received a different result under a constitutionally
flawless process?</P>

<P> 6.   May a federal court, consistent with Article III, award prospective
relief against a State and its officials regarding a law school admissions
policy, when the effects of that policy are not before the court and the
"case" or "controversy" requirement is not met by any showing of actual
harm the litigants would be likely to suffer in the future without such
prospective relief?</P>

<P>         Parties to the Proceeding</P>

<P>     The petitioners (defendants-appellees in the courts below) are:</P>

<P>     The State of Texas</P>

<P>     The University of Texas Board of Regents</P>

<P>     Bernard Rapoport, Ellen C. Temple, Lowell H. Lebermann, Jr., Robert J.
Cruikshank, Thomas O. Hicks, Zan W. Holmes, Jr., Tom Loeffler, Martha E.
