<P>Reasons for Granting the Writ ...12</P>

<P>1.   This Court should correct the court of appeals' misperception that
Bakke is no longer the law and  should reaffirm that  diversity remains a
compelling  interest that justifies individualized consideration  of race,
among other factors, in higher education admissions decisions......12</P>

<P>2.   This Court should clarify what State education officials may consider
as a "strong basis in the evidence" to conclude that individualized
consideration of race is necessary to remedy the present effects of the
State's own past discrimination in education..16</P>

<P>3.   This Court should clarify whether admissions officers in states having
practiced de jure segregation may, consistent with United States v.
Fordice, take race into account to ameliorate the segregative effects of
seemingly "race- neutral" admission standards......20</P>

<P>4.   This Court should settle whether, in view of Seminole Tribe of
Florida, a federal court may entertain suit against a State without its
consent under Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964  .......22</P>

<P>5.   This Court should settle whether Carey v. Piphus requires plaintiffs
to bear the ultimate burden of proving concrete injury before compensatory
damages may be awarded...25</P>

<P>6.   This Court should clarify the Article III limits on the power of a
federal court to issue prospective relief....28</P>

<P>Conclusion....30</P>

