<P> Miscellaneous</P>

<P>Janet Elliott & Gordon Hunter,  Buying Time After Hopwood,<BR>
  Texas Lawyer, March 25, 1996......... 27</P>

<P>             Introduction</P>

<P> In the decision below, the Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit held
that an institution of higher learning, the University of Texas School of
Law, is prohibited from considering race in any manner in its admissions
processes. This decision is the first of its kind by any federal court. In
promulgating its far-reaching rule, the court of appeals took it upon
itself to overrule, anticipatorily, the holding of a five-Justice majority
in Regents of the University of California v. Bakke, 438 U.S. 265 (1978),
and called into question the permissibility of considering race in
admissions programs in public colleges, universities, and professional
schools throughout the country. The national significance of the decision
is obvious. Moreover, even apart from the equal protection issue, this case
presents fundamental questions of state sovereignty and federal judicial
power.</P>

<P> There is more than a touch of irony that this case should arise out of the
same institution, the University of Texas School of Law, that provided the
basis for this Court's decision in Sweatt v. Painter, 339 U.S. 629 (1950),
overturning the official state ban on he admissin of Blacks to the School
of Law. There is also a harsh irony that this case should arise from the
State of Texas. The undisputed record shows that Texas students applying to
the challenged 1992 incoming class were largely the products of a  public
school system that was still under court supervision for  failing
effectively to remedy unconstitutional de jure segregation.</P>

<P>Not contested below, but unmentioned in the Fifth Circuit's opinion, is the
effective resegregation of the University of Texas  School of Law that
would result if the Fifth Circuit's decision were left intact. The School
of Law is the State's flagship institution, charged with training the
leaders of the State and beyond. The Fifth Circuit's decision would have
produced, in a State whose population approaches forty percent Blacks and
Mexican Americans, a 1992 incoming class with at most a handful of Blacks
and Mexican Americans, out of more than five hundred students.</P>


<P> The central question before this Court is whether the Constitution compels
this result.</P>

<P> Opinions Below</P>

<P> The opinion of the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit,
filed March 18, 1996 (Appendix A), is to be reported at 78 F.3d 932. The
opinion of the United States District Court for the Western District of
Texas, dated August 19, 1994 (Appendix B), is reported at 861 F. Supp. 551.
On April 4, 1996, the Court of Appeals entered an order denying rehearing
en banc and indicating that a dissent from the denial of rehearing en banc
was forthcoming. Appendix C. On April 19, 1996, the Court of Appeals,
pursuant to Fed. R. App. Proc. 41, stayed its mandate until May 13, 1996,
to permit the filing and disposition of a petition for certiorari. Appendix
D. On April 23, 1996, the Fifth Circuit released two opinions, joined by a
total of seven of the Court of Appeals' seventeen active judges (one of
whom had recused himself), dissenting from the Court's failure to grant
rehearing en banc. Appendix E.</P>

<P> Jurisdiction</P>

<P> The judgment of the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit
was filed on March 18, 1996. This Court has jurisdiction pursuant to 28
U.S.C. &#167; 1254(1).</P>

<P> Constitutional and Statutory Provisions Involved</P>

<P> United States Constitution, Art. III</P>

<P> United States Constitution, amendment XIV</P>

<P> United States Constitution, amendment XI</P>

<P> Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,</P>

<P> 42 U.S.C. &#167; 2000d-7(a)(1)</P>

<P> 42 U.S.C. &#167; 1981</P>

<P> 42 U.S.C. &#167; 1983</P>

<P> These provisions are printed in Appendix F.</P>

<P> Statement of the Case</P>

<P> Proceedings Below</P>

<P> Respondents are four white applicants denied admission to the 1992
entering class at The University of Texas School of Law (the "Law School").
This action was filed in the United States District Court for the Western
District of Texas. Respondents alleged that petitioners administered a
racially discriminatory admissions program at the Law School, in violation
of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution; Title VI of
the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. &#167; 2000d; and 42 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1981 and
1983. But for the Eleventh Amendment, the district court would have had
subject matter jurisdiction under 28 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1331 and 1343.</P>

<P> Petitioners moved for summary judgment on the ground, inter alia, that the
Eleventh Amendment precluded this action against the State of Texas, its
subdivisions, and officers acting in their official capacities. The
district court denied that motion in an unpublished opinion dated October
28, 1993. R. 588-605.</P>

<P> After an eight-day bench trial in May 1994, the district court declared
invalid the Law School's 1992 admissions procedure insofar as it employed a
separate subcommittee for evaluating minority applicants. App. at B58-59.
The court held this aspect of the 1992 procedure constitutionally infirm
because it was not narrowly tailored to meet the State's compelling
interests in seeking the educational benefits that flow from having a
diverse student body and in redressing the continuing effects of
discriminatory practices by the educational hierarchy of Texas.  The
district court held that it did not need to decide the constitutionality of
a second feature of the 1992 procedure the use of different presumptive
denial scores for minority and nonminority candidates because "none of the
plaintiffs in this lawsuit was affected directly by this aspect of the 1992
procedure." Id. at B52 n.71. The State did not appeal the district court's
ruling with respect to the 1992 policy, having abandoned that policy in
1994 in favor of one that treated race as simply a factor in the
individualized consideration and comparison of applicants to the Law
School.</P>

<P> In crafting a remedy, the district court awarded respondents nominal
damages only, because the State had shown "that legitimate,
nondiscriminatory grounds exist for the Law School's denial of admission to
each of the four plaintiffs and that, in all likelihood, the plaintiffs
would not have been offered admission even under a constitutionally
permissible process." App. at B65.  The court explained that 109
nonminority residents with numerical scores lower than Hopwood's were
offered admission, and that sixty-seven nonminority residents with
numerical scores lower than the other three plaintiffs were admitted,
leading to the inference that weaknesses in respondents' applications,
completely apart from their numerical scores, had triggered the Law
School's decision not to admit them. Id. at B63-64. In fact, the court
observed that "it appears that the majority of applicants, both minority
and nonminority, made considerable effort to inform the admissions
committee of their special qualifications through extensive answer to the
questions on the application form or through personal statements," and
"[m]ost files contained one, if not several, letters of recommendation."
Id. at B64. Respondents' files were notably bare. "In fact, of all the
applications the Court reviewed, Hopwood's provides the least information
about her background and individual qualifications and is the least
impressive in appearance, despite her relatively high numbers." Id.</P>

<P> The court declined to impose prospective injunctive relief with respect to
the Law School's admissions policy because the Law School had adopted a new
admissions policy during the litigation that "appears to remedy the defects
the Court has found in the 1992 procedure," App. at B67, and because
"neither a plaintiff denied admission under the new system nor evidence of
the practical application of the new procedure is before this Court."  Id.
Under the new policy, the Law School does not use a separate minority
subcommittee or different presumptive admission or denial scores for
minority and nonminority applicants. Id. at B67 n.87. Each candidate is
given fully individualized treatment on his or her own merits; race is
considered, along with myriad other matters, such as socio-economic status,
employment history, extra-curricular  activities as an undergraduate, and
other factors that make up a person's life experiences and affect what the
person can contribute to the educational dialogue, both inside class and
out. Although the Law School attempts to meet the targets (established by
the Office for Civil Rights of the U.S. Department of Education) of ten
percent Mexican American students and five percent Black students in an
entering class, these targets are purely aspirational.</P>

<P> The district court ordered that respondents be permitted to reapply under
the new policy without being charged an application fee. App. at B67-68.
But the court denied attorney's fees to respondents, on the ground that
they had "failed to prove they would have been offered admission under a
constitutional procedure" and "the de minimis nature of the relief the
plaintiffs received is insufficient to justify an award of attorney's
fees." Hopwood v. State of Texas, No. A-92-CA-563, mem. op. at 2, 4 (Nov.
14, 1994).</P>

<P> The court of appeals for the Fifth Circuit reversed, holding broadly that
"the law school may not use race as a factor in law school admissions."
App. at A3. With respect to the State's interest in enriching the
educational experience of all its law students by encouraging the admission
of, among others, Blacks and Mexican Americans, the court of appeals held
that "the use of ethnic diversity simply to achieve racial heterogeneity,
even as part of a number of factors, is unconstitutional. . . . [T]he use
of race per se is proscribed . . . ." Id. at A27. The Fifth Circuit opined
that the consideration of race to promote diversity "is no more rational on
its own terms than would be choices based upon the physical size or blood
type of applicants." Id. at A26.</P>

<P> With respect to remedying the present effects of de jure discrimination in
Texas public education, the court held that the Law School was the only
"relevant . . . past discriminator." App. at A40. "As a result, past
discrimination in education, other than at the law school, cannot justify
the present consideration of race in law school admissions." Id. at A45.</P>

<P> The court of appeals ruled that the district court erred in requiring the
plaintiffs to prove that they had been injured by the Law School admissions
procedures in place in 1992. Instead, the court held that "once
discrimination is proved, the defendant bears the burden of proving no
damage." Id. at A49 n.53. Accordingly, the court remanded to the district
court the task of calculating compensatory damages.</P>

<P> The court of appeals also issued a series of "judicial instruction[s]" to
the Law School, commanding it not to consider race as a factor in the
admissions process "for the purpose of (1) obtaining a diverse student
body; (2) altering the school's reputation in the community; (3) combating
the school's perceived hostile environment toward minorities; or (4)
remedying the present effects of past discrimination by actors other than
the law school." Id. at A55.</P>

<P> Judge Wiener, specially concurring, "respectfully disagree[d] with the
panel opinion's conclusion that diversity can never be a compelling
governmental interest in a public graduate school." Id. at A64. He
nonetheless concluded that the 1992 Law School admissions process was not
narrowly tailored to this interest.  Judge Wiener also expressed
reservations about the scope of relief issued by the court, warning that
the majority had "inappropriate[ly]" issued "a de facto injunction" against
respondents. Id. at A73. He cautioned that the plaintiffs had challenged
"only the admissions process employed by the law school in 1992 -- not the
admissions process that was in place and employed in 1995, not the
admissions process that is being employed in 1996, and not the admissions
process to be applied in any future years." Id. at A75.</P>

<P> On April 4, 1996, the court of appeals denied rehearing en banc and
announced that a dissent from the denial of rehearing would be released.
Appendix C. On April 19, 1996, the court of appeals granted petitioners a
28-day stay pending the filing and disposition of this petition for writ of
certiorari. In light of "the magnitude of the case" and "the importance of
the issue," the court determined that "there is a reasonable chance that
four Justices will vote to grant certiorari." The court also held that
petitioners had met their burden of demonstrating irreparable injury in the
absence of a stay.</P>

<P> On April 23, 1996, the court of appeals released two opinions dissenting
from the Fifth Circuit's failure to grant en banc rehearing. Chief Judge
Politz, joined by six other judges, filed a dissent warning that the
panel's opinion "will literally change the face of public educational
institutions throughout Texas, the other states of this circuit, and this
nation." App. at E3. The Chief Judge described the court's decision as "a
text book example of judicial activism" and "a frontal assault on contrary
Supreme Court precedent." Id. "[T]he panel charted a path into terra
incognita.  Judicial restraint was the first casualty; it proved to be too
burdensome. The teachings proscribing the consideration of constitutional
issues unnecessary to the decision soon followed.  With these two
limitations adroitly set aside, the panel majority apparently considered
itself positioned to overrule Bakke." Id. at E7:</P>

<P>By tenuously stringing together pieces and shards of recent Supreme Court
opinions that have dealt with race in such diverse settings as minority set
asides for government contractors, broadcast licenses, redistricting, and
the like, the panel creates a gossamer chain which it proffers as a
justification for overruling Bakke. . . . The syllogisms tacked together
and proffered by the majority opinion as proof that Justice Powell's
diversity conclusion is no longer good law do not, under any standards of
which we are aware, qualify as an overruling of Bakke.</P>

<P>App. at E3, 7.</P>

<P> Judge Stewart filed a separate dissent from the Court of Appeals' failure
to grant rehearing en banc, in order "to underscore the [court's] lack of
historical perspective and sensitivity." App. at E9. Judge Stewart observed
that the University of Texas School of Law was the same institution whose
admissions policies were at issue in Sweatt v. Painter, 339 U.S. 629
(1950). He also noted that, in holding that the Law School had violated the
Equal Protection Clause by excluding Heman Sweatt, this Court explicitly
adhered to the " principle of deciding constitutional questions only in the
context of the particular case before the Court,' drawing its decision as
narrowly as possible.' " Id. (quoting 339 U.S. at 631). Judge Stewart
criticized the Fifth Circuit majority for disregarding that guiding
principle here, calling its failure to grant rehearing en banc a
"travesty." Id. at E10.</P>

<P> Statement of Facts</P>

<P> "Texas' long history of discrimination against its black and Hispanic
citizens in all areas of public life is not the subject of dispute." LULAC
v. Clements, 999 F.2d 831, 866 (5th Cir. 1993), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct.
878 (1994); id. at 915 (King, J., dissenting).  The district court
confirmed this history in extensive factual findings that the court of
appeals did not disturb. App. at B3-10.</P>

<P> In 1977, the District Court for the District of Columbia ordered the
Office for Civil Rights (OCR) of the United States Department of Health,
Education and Welfare (HEW) (now the Department of Education or DOE) to
investigate discrimination in Texas' system of higher education. App. at
B6-8; D296. See Adams v. Richardson, 356 F. Supp. 92 (D.D.C.mexican),
modified and aff'd, 480 F.2d 1159 (D.C. Cir. 1973), dism'd sub nom. Women's
Equity Action League v. Cavazos, 906 F.2d 742 (D.C. Cir. 1990). Following a
two-year investigation, OCR found in 1980 that Texas had failed to
eliminate the vestiges of its segregated higher education system and was in
violation of Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C.  2000d.</P>

<P> As a remedy, Texas agreed to adopt the Texas Equal Education Opportunity
Plan for Higher Education (Texas Plan).  OCR required that the Texas Plan
include a commitment to "seek to achieve proportions of Blacks and Hispanic
Texas graduates from undergraduate institutions in the State who enter
graduate study or professional schools in the State at least equal to the
proportion of white Texas graduates from undergraduate institutions in the
State who enter such programs." App. at B9 n.6; D238a at 5.</P>


<P> In 1983, just eight years before respondents applied to the Law School,
Texas agreed, under threat of federal action, to formulate an acceptable
plan to desegregate its higher education system, including the Law School.
But in January 1994, the Department of Education notified Governor Richards
that OCR was still overseeing Texas' desegregation efforts and would review
the Texas system in light of United States v. Fordice, 505 U.S. 717 (1992).
App. at B10. DOE has yet to determine that Texas' higher education system
has come into compliance with Title VI and the Fourteenth Amendment. Id.</P>

<P> In 1983, as a higher education desegregation plan was still being
formulated, respondents Elliott and Rogers were students at the University
of Texas. P153; P171. Respondent Carvell was attending Texas public
schools. P151. As the district court found, during the 1980s most Texas
students lived in school districts whose public schools the federal courts
and the United States Department of Justice had determined were still
unconstitutionally segregated. App. at B46; D434. Over seventy percent of
Blacks in Texas lived in metropolitan areas operating under court-ordered
desegregation plans. 19 Tr. 43; D378B. Many school districts were found to
practice official discrimination against Mexican-American  as well as
against Black students. App. at B4. On the eve of trial, which fell on the
fortieth anniversary of Brown v. Board of Education, 347 U.S. 483 (1954),
federal and private desegregation lawsuits were still pending against over
forty Texas school districts. App. at B4; D457.</P>

<P> The district court found that Texas residents who applied for admission to
the Law School in fall 1992 would have spent most, if not all, of their
pre-college education in a school system suffering the effects of
unconstitutional segregation. App. at B46.  The court found that official
discrimination had "handicapped the educational achievement of many
minorities." Id. Because the State of Texas required that eighty-five
percent of the Law School's 1992 entering class be Texas residents, the
court found that inferior educational opportunity particularly affected the
Law School's current pool of qualified resident minority applicants. Id. at
B46, B23-24.</P>

<P> The district court further found that the pool of qualified resident
minority applicants was artificially constricted not only by Texas'
unconstitutional public school system, but also by the reputation of the
University and the Law School as "white" institutions with an environment
hostile to minorities. App. at B45. The court found that, despite extensive
recruiting efforts, the Law School's legacy of discrimination has hindered
efforts to attract qualified minority students. Id.</P>

<P> The district court also made extensive findings regarding the importance
of diversity in institutions of higher learning. The district court found,
and the court of appeals did not question, that grade point averages and
LSAT scores do not "adequately reflect the qualifications and
characteristics a law school should consider in developing a diverse
student body, which provides substantial educational benefit for all
members of a law school class." App. at B25. In fact, the ABA and American
Association of Law Schools each requires commitment to diversity in the
student body as a prerequisite for membership or accreditation. 18 Tr.
26-28; D387; D389; D391; D395. The district court reached its conclusion
only after considering extensive testimony from deans of law schools across
the country, from current and former law students, and from law professors.</P>

<P> Reasons for Granting the Writ</P>

<P>1. This Court should correct the court of appeals' misperception that Bakke
is no longer the law and should reaffirm that educational diversity remains
a compelling interest that justifies individualized consideration of race,
among other factors, in higher education admissions decisions.</P>

<P> The two-judge majority held that it was unconstitutional for the Law
School even to consider the race of individual applicants "for the purpose
of obtaining a diverse student body," in flat violation of Regents of the
University of California v. Bakke, 438 U.S. 265 (1978). The majority
opinion maintained that, "in significant part," Justice Powell's opinion
"was joined by no other justice," App. at A19; that "Justice Powell's
argument in Bakke garnered only his own vote and has never represented the
view of the majority of the Court in Bakke or any other case," App. at A23;
and that "Justice Powell's view in Bakke is not binding precedent." Id.</P>

<P> But the court of appeals ignored the holding of five Justices, who joined
in Part V-C of Justice Powell's opinion, that it was not impermissible for
the University of California to consider race as a factor in making
admissions decisions:</P>

<P> In enjoining petitioner from ever considering the race of any applicant,
however, the courts below failed to recognize that the State has a
substantial interest that legitimately may be served by a properly devised
admissions program involving the competitive consideration of race and
ethnic origin. For this reason, so much of the California court's judgment
as enjoins petitioner from any consideration of the race of any applicant
must be reversed.</P>

<P> Bakke, 438 U.S. at 320 (opinion of the Court per Powell, J.); id. at 328
(opinion of Brennan, J., joined by White, Marshall, and Blackmun, JJ.,
concurring in the judgment in part and dissenting in part) (joining in Part
V-C of Justice Powell's opinion).</P>

<P> Exercise of this Court's certiorari jurisdiction would be amply warranted
by a lower court's determination, under any circumstances, that a holding
by this Court is no longer good law.  Bakke's landmark status, and the
paramount national interest in establishing, definitively, whether lower
courts remain bound to follow it, represent further compelling reasons for
this Court to review the decision below. For the last two decades,
institutions of higher education have relied on Bakke to include race among
the characteristics considered in composing student bodies that are not
only bright, but diverse, to make education and the dialogue that advances
it more effective and relevant to the society that graduates will enter.
Longstanding and widespread reliance on Bakke counsel against its
overruling, see Planned Parenthood v. Casey, 505 U.S. 833, 861-69 (1992),
and particularly against permitting the lower courts simply to discard it.</P>

<P> Indeed, the Fifth Circuit itself recognized the important need for this
Court's review and was able to declare Bakke's death only on the basis of
concurring and dissenting opinions by the members of this Court and
academic commentary. In fact, however, the Fifth Circuit's report of
Bakke's demise was premature. The compelling interest in promoting
educational diversity was recognized long before Bakke and has been
recognized even by those who reject diversity as a compelling interest in
other contexts. Compare Wygant v. Jackson Bd. of Educ., 476 U.S. 267, 286
(1986) (O'Connor, J., concurring) ("a state interest in the promotion of
racial diversity has been found sufficiently compelling,' at least in the
context of higher education, to support the use of racial considerations in
furthering that interest") and id. at 288 n. (noting the difference between
providing role models and "the very different goal of racial diversity
among the faculty") with Metro Broadcasting, Inc. v. FCC, 497 U.S. 547, 614
(1990) (O'Connor, J. dissenting) (disagreeing with extending the interest
in diversity to the award of broadcast licenses).</P>

<P> Diversity is an especially compelling interest in legal education. No
other discipline deals so fundamentally with the ordering of human
relationships in our society, including racial and ethnic minorities who
have been subjected to discrimination:</P>

<P> [A]lthough the law is a highly learned profession, we are well aware that
it is an intensely practical one. The law school, the proving ground for
legal learning and practice, cannot be effective in isolation from the
individuals and institutions with which the law interacts.</P>

<P> Sweatt v. Painter, 339 U.S. 629, 634 (1950); see also Wygant, 476 U.S. at
314-15 (Stevens, J., dissenting) (endorsing diversity rationale). The First
Amendment dimension of educational policy choices, by State as well as
private higher educational institutions, adds to the compelling nature of
the diversity interest. See Bakke, 438 U.S. at 312 (opinion of Powell, J.)
(noting that "academic freedom" has "long . . . been viewed as a special
concern of the First Amendment").</P>

<P> Whatever the status of Bakke, the issue should be decided by this Court,
so that the same rule applies across the country. The question is so
fundamental as to warrant resolution on a nationwide basis. The Law School,
for its part, is now severely handicapped in competing with, say, Harvard,
Stanford, or Michigan to attract top students and faculty, because it can
no longer ensure a truly diverse student body. Minority students in Texas,
Louisiana, and Mississippi may be given special consideration by colleges
and universities on the east and west coasts, but not in their home states.
This imbalance is as ironic as it is intolerable, given the long history of
official discrimination in the education of minorities in these Gulf Coast
states. See, e.g., App. at B3-10; United States v. Fordice, 505 U.S. 717,
721-25 (1992); United States v. Louisiana, 692 F. Supp. 642, 644-46 (E.D.
La. 1988).</P>

<P> 2. This Court should clarify what State education officials may consider
as a "strong basis in the evidence" to conclude that individualized
consideration of race is necessary to remedy the present effects of the
State's own past discrimination in education.</P>

<P> The district court chronicled Texas' history of official discrimination in
the education of Blacks and Mexican Americans at all levels of the State
system. App. at B3-10. The court carefully assessed the impact of this
undisputed discrimination on the Law School, particularly in view of the
state legislative mandate that eighty-five percent of the Law School's 1992
entering class (eighty percent today) be Texas residents. Id at B23-24 and
n.33. The court found the ultimate effect stark and severe: in the absence
of some attention to race, the 1992 entering class at the Law School would
have included at most a handful of Blacks and Mexican Americans. These
figures, chilling as they are, are overly optimistic, given the Law
School's own history. "[T]he record in this case demonstrates that, without
affirmative action, the perception of the law school as a white'
institution would be exacerbated, which would compound the difficulties of
attracting top minority students." Id. at B48.</P>

<P> Rejecting petitioners' remedial purpose, the court of appeals held that
remedying the ongoing effects even of de jure discrimination can never be a
compelling interest unless the only past discrimination that the remedy is
designed to overcome is discrimination previously practiced by the
governmental actor that installed and administered the remedy in this case,
the Law School itself. The justification for remedial action by the Law
School thus cannot be augmented by findings of official discrimination by
the State of Texas in primary and secondary education or in state higher
education generally. "The Supreme Court . by a specific governmental unit."
App. at A38 n.43.</P>

<P> In fact, this Court has never so severely restrained a state's ability to
remedy the present effects of pervasive past discrimination in its own
public education system. In Richmond v. J.A. Croson Co., 488 U.S. 469
(1989), Justice O'Connor, joined by the Chief Justice and Justice White,
squarely rejected the suggestion that a city was required to "limit any
race-based remedial efforts to eradicating the effects of its own prior
discrimination." Id. at 486 (emphasis added). Instead, the Justices took
the broader view that a state or subdivision "has the authority to
eradicate [even] the effects of private discrimination within its own
legislative jurisdiction," i.e., "within local commerce under its
jurisdiction." Id. at 491-92 (emphasis added). "Thus, if the city could
show that it had essentially become a passive participant' in a system of
racial exclusion practiced by elements of the local construction industry,
we think it clear that the city could take affirmative steps to dismantle
such a system." Id. at 492.</P>

<P> The State of Texas has been no mere "passive participant" in the past
exclusion of Blacks and Mexican Americans from equal opportunity in public
education. Even the court of appeals acknowledged that "Texas state actors
have discriminated against some minorities in public schools" and that
"lingering effects of such discrimination is [sic] not societal,' if that
term is meant to exclude all state action." App. at A39. The court
nevertheless concluded that recognizing any remedial interest in this case
would allow "generalized assertions" of past discrimination, based on
"amorphous claim[s]" and even "sheer speculation," to justify remedial
efforts with "no logical stopping point" aimed at redressing societal
discrimination. Id. at A36-37. This conclusion is refuted by the district
court's extensive fact findings demonstrating the close nexus between
Texas' discrimination and the pool of residents from which the Law School
was required to draw eighty-five percent of its students. See, e.g., id. at
B46.  ("many public schools in Texas continued to have a substantial degree
of racial and ethnic segregation during the 1970s and 1980s, the decades in
which the majority of 1992 law school applicants attended primary and
secondary schools.").</P>

<P> The court of appeals' reasoning conflicts with the decisions of other
circuits recognizing that the extensive factual findings of a district
court, especially when coupled with determinations like those by the Office
for Civil Rights of the Department of Education and the district court in
the Adams litigation, provide ample predicate for a race-conscious remedial
program. The Fifth Circuit's decision in this case also conflicts with
Geier v. Alexander, 801 F.2d 799 (6th Cir. 1986), which upheld the
consideration of race in admissions in a pre-professional program at the
University of Tennessee.</P>

<P> Even though the State of Texas is the lead defendant in this case and the
fountainhead of Texas' past de jure discrimination at all levels of public
education, the court of appeals held that, for the State to be considered
the relevant governmental actor, "the State of Texas, through its
legislature, would have to find that past discrimination has present
effects . . . ." App. at A39 (emphasis added). In fact, the State of Texas,
acting through its governor, effectively made such findings in agreeing to
the higher education remedial program implemented in the Texas plans. See
App. at B8.  More fundamentally, the court of appeals' holding offended
principles of federalism and state sovereignty insofar as it held that the
State of Texas is not free to structure its system of governance for public
education such that the governor, the boards of regents, and other state
officials have some degree of flexibility in deciding for themselves that
the lingering present effects on the Law School of de jure racial
discrimination and segregation practiced largely at lower levels of the
State's educational hierarchy are serious enough to require a
race-conscious remedy in the Law School's own admissions policies. "
Congress need [not] make particularized findings in order to legislate.'"
United States v. Lopez, 115 S.Ct. 1624, 1631 (1995) (citation omitted).
Demanding that a State do so and that it speak expressly and exclusively
through its legislature is unduly intrusive on the State's freedom, under
Art. IV,  4 (the Republican Form of Government Clause) and the Tenth
Amendment, to structure its decisionmaking authority as it sees fit.</P>

<P> In Adarand Constructors, Inc. v. Pea, 115 S.Ct. 2097 (1995), this Court
emphasized that "[t]he unhappy persistence of both the practice and the
lingering effects of racial discrimination against minority groups in this
country is an unfortunate reality, and government is not disqualified from
acting in response to it."  Id. at 2117; see also id. at 2114
(distinguishing between a "No Trespassing" sign and a "welcome mat"). The
record of this case fully demonstrates the Law School's remedial
justification for considering race in its admissions decisions. This
Court's review is amply warranted.</P>

<P> 3. This Court should clarify whether admissions officers in states having
practiced de jure segregation may, consistent with United States v.
Fordice, take race into account to ameliorate the present segregative
effects of seemingly "race-neutral" admission standards.</P>

<P> This is not just an affirmative action case; it is a desegregation case.
Until the court of appeals' opinion, Texas higher education institutions,
including the Law School, continued to operate under a series of
desegregation plans originally mandated and monitored by OCR.</P>

<P> States have an especially compelling interest in remedying the effects of
past discrimination in their own education systems.  Fordice, 505 U.S. at
727-28; see Croson, 488 U.S. at 524 (Scalia, J., concurring)
(distinguishing school desegregation cases from employment set-asides);
Hammon v. Barry, 813 F.2d 412, 421  n.18 (D.C. Cir. 1987) (Starr, J.)
(distinguishing employment set-asides  from "the unique and sensitive area
of education" and "the government's fundamental interest in education" that
may "support the use of racial considerations"), cert. denied, 486 U.S.
1036 (1988). Indeed, states that operated officially segregated systems of
higher education have a broad affirmative duty under both the Fourteenth
Amendment and Title VI to dismantle those systems.  Fordice, 505 U.S. at
727-28. That duty is not satisfied merely by adopting race-neutral
policies. Rather, the state must take affirmative steps to ameliorate
practices and policies that perpetuate the dual system. Id. at 728. That
constitutional duty may require a state either to eliminate, or to
counteract and minimize to the extent possible, strict reliance on test
scores that effectively segregate white and minority students. Id. at
737-38; id. at 744 (O'Connor, J., concurring).</P>

<P> Without consideration of race, the Law School would come perilously close
to this Court's warning in Fordice. As the district court found:</P>

<P> [T]he ultimate effect of abandoning affirmative action at the law school
would be to redirect minorities to the historically separate state law
school at Texas Southern University, thereby resegregating the law school.</P>

<P> App. at B47. TSU, which was created to avoid integrating The University of
Texas and the Law School (and is still called "The House That Sweatt
Built"), today enrolls over half of all minority law students in Texas. Its
student body is nearly seventy-five percent minorities. The evidence was
undisputed that if Texas is compelled to abandon any consideration of race
at its state law schools, it will return to a starkly dual system of legal
education. Few minorities would attend the historically white law schools,
while seventy-seven percent of minority law students in Texas would attend
TSU, whose student body would be eighty-five percent Blacks and Mexican
Americans. 12 Tr. 44-45; D452; D453.</P>

<P> 4. This Court should settle whether, in view of Seminole Tribe of Florida,
a federal court may entertain suit against a State without its consent
under Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.</P>

<P> Respondents brought suit under 42 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1981 and 1983, and under Title
VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. &#167; 2000d et seq. In the
district court, the State raised an Eleventh Amendment defense in its
motion for summary judgment. Although the district court's decision to deny
both injunctive relief and compensatory damages made that jurisdictional
objection less salient, it was error of the first constitutional magnitude
for the court of appeals to proceed as though the Eleventh Amendment limit
on federal court jurisdiction was "simply not before [it]." App. at A52
n.56. To the contrary, the court reversed the trial court's refusal to
award compensatory damages and remanded with instructions that respondents
were presumptively entitled to damages against the State defendants. Id. at
A51.</P>

<P> As this Court squarely held in Seminole Tribe of Florida v. Florida, 116
S.Ct. 1114, 1131 (1996), the Eleventh Amendment is a bar to the exercise of
subject matter jurisdiction by the federal courts in suits brought by
citizens of a State against that State. See Hans v. Louisiana, 134 U.S. 1
(1890). The court of appeals had no subject-matter jurisdiction to
entertain an action against Texas and its officials in clear derogation of
the protections of traditional sovereign immunity contained in the Eleventh
Amendment.</P>

<P> Respondents' claims for damages are predicated solely on Title VI, which
this Court has already determined is a classic Spending Clause statute. In
light of Seminole Tribe, it is plain that Congress lacks constitutional
authority simply to abrogate the State's Eleventh Amendment immunity
pursuant to Article I, whether through mandatory legislation enacted under
the Commerce Clause or through mandatory legislation enacted under the
Spending Clause. See id., 116 S.Ct. at 1126 (no "principled distinction"
may be drawn between various Article I powers). The Spending Clause -- even
more plainly than the Commerce Clause and in stark contrast to the
Fourteenth Amendment's Section 5, which was "adopted well after the
adoption of the Eleventh Amendment," id. at 1127 -- is not "a grant of
authority to the Federal Government at the expense of the States." Id. at
1126. See Steward Machine Co. v. Davis, 301 U.S. 548, 597 (1937)(Spending
Clause, while permitting States to contract "with Congress if the essence
of their statehood is maintained without impairment," does not thereby
reduce state authority, for "[e]ven sovereigns may contract without
derogating from their sovereignty").</P>

<P> State amenability to suit could be drawn only from Congress's 1986
amendment of Title VI to provide, in 42 U.S.C. &#167; 2000d-7(a)(1), that a
"State shall not be immune under the Eleventh Amendment . . . from suit in
Federal court for a violation of . . . Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of
1964 . . . , or the provisions of any other Federal statute prohibiting
discrimination by recipients of Federal financial assistance." In enacting
that provision, Congress sought by legislative dictate to override this
Court's holding in Guardians Ass'n, supra, that limited Title VI remedies
to prospective injunctive relief for unintentional violations of the Act.
463 U.S. at 602.</P>

<P> This assertion of federal legislative power to abrogate sovereign immunity
cannot survive Seminole Tribe. This Court has now ruled that the provisions
of Article I of the Constitution</P>

<P> necessarily including the Spending Clause give Congress no power
unilaterally to overcome the Eleventh Amendment: "Article I cannot be used
to circumvent the constitutional limitations placed upon federal
jurisdiction." 116 S.Ct. at 1131-32.  Plainly, under this analysis, Title
VI, which operates "not [as] a regulatory measure, but an exercise [under
the Spending Clause] of the unquestioned power of the Federal Government to
fix the terms on which Federal funds shall be disbursed,'" Guardians Ass'n,
463 U.S. at 599, is incapable of abrogating the Eleventh Amendment immunity
of the States. The inescapable conclusion is that, when Congress sought in
1986 unilaterally to override state sovereign immunity, it was putting its
power under the Spending Clause of Article I to a use that this Court has
now definitively held impermissible.</P>

<P> 5. This Court should settle whether Carey v. Piphus still requires
plaintiffs to bear the ultimate burden of proving concrete injury before
they may be awarded compensatory damages.</P>

<P> The court of appeals recognized the "well-established rule must prove that
they have been injured." Carey v. Piphus, 435 U.S. 247,254-57 (1978). App.
at A49. Nevertheless, the court held that, because respondents demonstrated
a constitutional violation, under Mt. Healthy City Sch. Dist. Bd. of Educ.
v. Doyle, 429 U.S. 274, 284 (1977), the burden shifted to petitioners to
prove that respondents "would not have gained admittance to the law school
under a race-blind system." Id. at A51. In so holding, the court of appeals
recognized a split among the circuits on what Mt. Healthy means in racial
preference cases, id. at A50 n.54. It then proceeded to err in applying Mt.
Healthy. This Court should settle whether Mt. Healthy relieves plaintiffs
of the burden imposed by Carey to prove that the constitutional violation
they claim caused the injury for which they seek compensation.</P>

<P> In Carey, this Court held that the common law of torts governs the award
of compensatory damages in a  1983 action.  Thus, plaintiffs must prove
not only that their constitutional rights were violated, but also that the
violation caused the injury for which they seek compensation. 435 U.S. at
254-65. Absent proof of concrete damages, only nominal damages may be
awarded. Id. at 266-67.</P>

<P> The district court therefore correctly held that, "[b]ecause the
plaintiffs have failed to establish that they would have been admitted
under a constitutional system, they are not entitled to [compensatory]
damages. Further, had the plaintiffs been entitled to damages, none of them
established monetary damages as required under the law . . . ." App. at
B69. Nothing in the trial or appellate record shows otherwise. A plaintiff
showing a constitutional violation in the process applied to that plaintiff
can "recover compensatory damages only if he prove[s] actual injury caused
by the denial of his constitutional rights." Memphis Comm. School Dist. v.
Stachura, 477 U.S. 299, 307 (1986).</P>

<P> The court of appeals erred in holding that Mt. Healthy and Village of
Arlington Heights v. Metropolitan Housing Development Corp, 429 U.S. 252
(1977), placed on the State the burden to demonstrate plaintiffs' lack of
injury once plaintiffs had shown a violation of the Constitution. To the
contrary, in Mt. Healthy, this Court held only that, once a plaintiff
proves that an impermissible consideration was a "substantial factor" in
causing the plaintiff concrete injury (such as the loss of a job), the
burden then shifts to the defendant to show that it would have reached the
same decision in the absence of the constitutional violation. 429 U.S. at
287.  Here, the consideration of race by the Law School in its admission
decisions was not a "substantial factor" in the respondents' failure to
gain admission. The district court considered evidence that forty-two
nonminority residents with statistical scores higher than or equal to
respondents' were denied admission, and 151 nonminority residents with
scores lower than or equal to respondents' were offered admission. P139.
Accordingly, the burden never shifted to petitioners to show by a
preponderance of the evidence that they would have reached the same
decision on respondents' applications in the absence of a consideration of
race.  Mt. Healthy, 429 U.S. at 287.</P>

<P> Indeed, the court of appeals' decision illustrates why Mt. Healthy should
not be used as the court of appeals used it in cases involving
race-conscious affirmative action. For the circuit court's decision has
placed respondents in a better position than they would have occupied had
the Law School never adopted an affirmative action plan at all, the very
result Mt. Healthy was concerned to avoid. See, 429 U.S. at 285. The court
of appeals has in effect presumed that respondents are entitled to
admission simply because the Law School considered race in its admissions
decisions, despite evidence of "non-race based weaknesses in [their]
applications." App. at B62; D-338.</P>

<P> The mischief this error has created is momentous, even in the instant
case. The court of appeals has now opened the courthouse doors to literally
hundreds of frustrated white applicants, the vast majority of whom would
not have been admitted even under a race-blind policy all of them demanding
substantial damages and/or instant admission to the Law School. The threat
is not hypothetical. The precedential implications for other cases are
sweeping.</P>

<P> 6. This Court should clarify the Article III limits on the power of a
federal court to issue prospective relief.</P>

<P> A final respect in which the court of appeals' judgment warrants this
Court's review arises from the Fifth Circuit's decision to award
prospective relief, in the form of thinly-veiled judicial "directives" to
the University of Texas, regarding the admissions policy for 1995-96 and
beyond a policy which was not before the court of appeals. The district
court properly declined to issue such relief, and the Fifth Circuit's
decision to award it raises grave questions under the "case" or
"controversy" requirement of Article III.</P>

<P> Under Los Angeles v. Lyons, 461 U.S. 95, 105 (1983), and Lujan v.
Defenders of Wildlife Fed'n, 504 U.S. 555, 560 (1992), there is no Article
III case or controversy with respect to prospective relief here. For the
aspect of the 1992 program invalidated by the district court has long since
been discontinued and will not be reinstated. And, as to the current
admissions policy, the first point to note is that the record is barren of
support for the speculation that plaintiffs will reapply under it or be
affected by it in any way. Since make-whole relief would be available, if
warranted, to each individual plaintiff in the form of an order of
admission, there is no standing to seek prospective relief against the
admissions policy as a whole. In order to claim the latter, plaintiffs
would have to assert the rights of other, nonspecific potential parties who
might be adversely affected by that policy in the future. This type of
claim falls outside the case or controversy requirements of Article III.</P>

<P> A second and equally decisive Article III objection to prospective relief
in this case is that, even if plaintiffs had demonstrated a high likelihood
that they would indeed reapply to the Law School, the record contains far
too little information about the current admissions policy the only policy
that could affect them prospectively to evaluate its concrete effect on
their prospects. The record discloses what the new policy does not do:  it
does not use separate committees or statistical benchmarks for minorities.
App. at B67 n.87. The new policy permits race to be considered only on an
individualized basis, as one of many factors needed to produce diversity,
and the percentage goals set by the Texas Plan for Blacks and Mexican
Americans are purely aspirational.</P>

<P> The only "injury" respondents could suffer under the admissions program
the Fifth Circuit halted even assuming that they would reapply, which the
record emphatically does not establish would involve the individualized
consideration of race as one of many factors. But mere exposure to such
consideration of one's race, apart from any effect such consideration might
have on one's concrete situation, would be the kind of diffuse,
unparticularized "harm" that this Court has held does not suffice for
purposes of Article III. See, e.g., United States v. Hays, 115 S.Ct. 2431,
2435-36 (1995).</P>

<P> There was accordingly no justification for the Fifth Circuit to address
the constitutionality, in this prospective context, of the 1996 admissions
process, or to issue elaborate "directives" to the Law School and other
institutions, when the plaintiffs had not begun to satisfy the
prerequisites for such intrusive equitable relief.</P>

<P> Conclusion</P>

<P> The petition for writ of certiorari should be granted.</P>

<P> Respectfully submitted,</P>

<P> April 30, 1996</P>

<P>Laurence H. Tribe*<BR>
Jonathan S. Massey<BR>
Hauser Hall 420<BR>
1575 Massachusetts Ave.<BR>
Cambridge, Mass.  02138<BR>
(617) 661-6868<BR>
Fax: (617) 661-4104</P>

