<html><TITLE> Spotlight - Thomas Hale Boggs Jr.</TITLE><body bgcolor=ffffff
vlink=0000ff><img width=100 height=92 border=0 align=left src="/images/spt2.gif">

<img  border=0 align=right src="/images/spotlight/boggs.gif">


Editor's note: Thomas Hale Boggs Jr. is one of the most prominent lobbyists in
the country. No stranger to the halls of power, he is the son of two members of
Congress. His father was the late Hale Boggs, former House Majority Leader. His
mother, Corinne Claiborne Boggs, served in the 93rd to 101st Congresses as a
Representative from the 2nd District of Louisiana. Boggs is online on Counsel
Connect discussing the role he's played as lobbyist in Washington, D.C., during
the last 30 years. Here he is discussing the usefulness of lobbying. 



<BR clear=all>


<blockquote>
<H2>Virtual Power Lunch: Thomas Hale Boggs Jr</H2>
<H3><a href="/spotlight/boggsform.html"><I>Submit a question</I></a></H3>
<PRE>

</PRE>
<P> Originally From: Eleanor Kerlow -- DC Counsel Connect - Wash<BR>
 Forum: Virtual Power Lunch-Tom Boggs<BR>
 Date: Mon Jun 10 12:04:48 1996<BR>
 Subject: Useful Role of Lobbying</P><BR>


<P>Last Append: Thu Jun 13 12:04:37 1996</P>


<P>A common criticism is that the use of lobbying by special interests is unfair,
that if members of Congress respond to the influence of special interests, they
are somehow acting contrary to the benefit of their constituents as a whole. How
do you respond to that? What legitimate role do lobbyists play in policy-making?</P>





<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: Tom Boggs -- Patton Boggs Blow - Washington<BR> Date: Mon Jun 10
17:51:32 1996<BR> Subject: Useful Role of Lobbying </P>

<P>It is very popular among politicians and media commentators alike to criticize
the influence of "special interests" in Washington.  We are to believe that if
Members of Congress respond to "special interests" they are somehow acting
contrary to the benefit of their constituents as a whole. </P>

<P>I believe that all interests are special.  Every individual and organization has
the right to advance their own interests.  The First Amendment to the
Constitution protects the right to petition the government for redress of your
grievances.  What could be more noble than exercising your constitutional
rights? </P>

<P>Thousands and thousands of registered and unregistered lobbyists work to
represent the interests of tens of thousands of "special" causes.  Most major
religious organizations have representatives in Washington, as do the Boy Scouts
of America, consumers, and environmentalists. </P>

<P>A lot of corporations have lobbyists too.  But is that bad?  Who benefits when
corporate America prospers?  Millions of working men and women who have invested
their pensions in mutual funds which depend on America being profitable to
increase in value, among others. </P>

<P>It is true that some causes don't have sufficient voice in the process.  The
answer is more people fighting for more special interests.  Not less. </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: David Post -- Georgetown Law Ctr. - Washington <BR>Date: Tue Jun 11
10:34:02 1996 <BR>Subject: But . . .  </P>

<P>While I don't disagree with some of what Mr. Boggs says in the above, there are
a couple of nagging problems here.  First, while it is certainly true that one
man's "lobbying" is another's constitutionally-protected "petitioning the
government for redress," the fact is that the profusion of lobbying activity has
led to a perception of the government as, in effect, selling law to the highest
bidder.  I think I'd take issue with the statement that "the answer is more
people fighting for more special interests."  Madison warned us a long time ago
about the danger of "faction" in a democratic society -- the sum of "special
interests" does not equal the "public interest" (which is, supposedly, the
constituency that lawmakers are charged with serving).  There's also a question
about the role of lawyers in all of this.  The perception of lawyers as "hired
guns," prepared to make *any* arguments for which clients will pay them, is
widespread.  Now, in the context of many kinds of representation, lawyers can
legitimately say that they really *must* do that -- for example in the context
of defending an accused criminal, where (a) society has determined that someone
needs to hold the prosecutor's feet to the fire and force the government to
prove its case, and (b) we believe that the "truth" will only come out in the
context of an adversarial process where each side makes the best arguments it
can.  But in the public policy/lobbying context, it doesn't seem that either of
these rationales apply. To many observers, this looks like a misuse of lawyerly
skills, using the ability to persuade that is so useful and important in the
adversarial context, for very different purposes.  Your thoughts? David Post  </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: T.R. Goldman -- Legal Times - Washington <BR>Date: Tue Jun 11 12:07:40
1996 <BR>Subject: postscript to mr. post </P>


<P>Although you are closely associated with the trial lawyers, a longtime products
liability lobbyist once told me that you would have been just as happy to
represent the other side of the issue -- it was all a matter of who hired you
first. Obviously, a good lawyer/lobbyist can argue any side of any issue. But 1.
are you a more effective lobbyist if you personally believe in the side you are
arguing? and  2. are there any clients -- barring those that are banned because
of conflicts -- that you would or have refused in the past? </P>

<P>thanks. </P>





<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: Tom Boggs -- Patton Boggs Blow - Washington <BR>Date: Tue Jun 11
21:01:01 1996 <BR>Subject: But . . . </P>

<P>I'll respond to Ted's question first, because David's question requires
additional thought.  Have we ever turned down a potential client?  Yes.  Some
examples.  When the government of South Africa attempted to hire Patton Boggs
during apartheid, we said no.  When a young associate (now partner) was asked to
represent the "adult entertainment" industry before Congress, we decided to take
a pass.  There are other examples, but I think you get the point. </P>

<P>Am I more effective when I believe in the client's cause?  Of course.  But if
you view legislative representation in the same manner as advocacy before a
court of law, then each client is entitled to a vigorous advocate.  Luckily, I
seldom find myself in the position of representing clients whose causes I find
distasteful. </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: Tom Boggs -- Patton Boggs Blow - Washington <BR>Date: Tue Jun 11
21:57:04 1996 <BR>Subject: But . . . </P>

<P>Wow.  I admire the alliteration in your "profusion of perceptions",  but I have
to take issue with the accuracy of some of them. </P>

<P>The perception that legislative advocacy amounts to a mere "selling of the law"
is a common stereotype which suggests that Members of Congress, democratically
elected, can be bought and sold.  In my experience, nothing could be further
from the truth.  Although the modern media has tended to reduce politics to a
collection of sound bites, the vast majority of our elected officials are
honest, hard-working, public servants who suffer as we lobbyists do from this
kind of cynical assessment.   </P>

<P>As for your observation that the sum of "special interests" do not make up the
"public interest," I can only respond, "What other index of the public's
interest does one have than the petitions of organized groups of motivated and
interested citizens placed before democratically-elected officials?"  Should we
attempt to govern by social science survey?  I doubt Madison would approve of
that, either.  I do know that he approved of representative government and the
system of checks and balances that protects those who are least able to
represent themselves from the tyranny of any majority.  The right of petition,
like the existence of a free press, is part of the design of that system. </P>

<P>As for your indictment of lawyers as "hired guns" who commonly make "any
argument" with impunity, it is another bit of cynicism to which I cannot
subscribe.  As a lobbyist, if I make "any" argument to Congresswoman X, no
matter what the consequences to her in terms of public reaction, I certainly
will never be invited back into her office when the fact becomes known.  Common
sense and professional survival therefore dictate that I tell her the truth,
plain and simple.  Moreover, skilled professional advocacy has as rightful a
place in legislative practice as it does in any legal arena.  And Constitutional
rights and other legal privileges are just as subject to challenge in Congress
as in a court of law, if not more so.  It is not a misuse of lawyers' skills to
use them on Capitol Hill. </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: Tom Boggs -- Patton Boggs Blow - Washington <BR>Date: Tue Jun 11
21:59:24 1996 <BR>Subject: But . . . </P>

<P>Oh.  I forgot to mention one thing Dave ---- lighten up. </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: David Post -- Georgetown Law Ctr. - Washington <BR>Date: Wed Jun 12
11:16:20 1996 <BR>Subject: Lightening up </P>

<P>OK, OK -- thanks for your reply to my [overbearing? overheated?] posting -- and
I certainly don't want to appear to be berating you on any of this.  But this is
-- as you certainly know and appreciate -- important stuff, important both for
the profession and for how our society works.  So -- taking your thoughtful
reply to indicate that you don't mind (or even enjoy?) engaging in these
questions, let me push -- lightly, I promise -- a little further. </P>


<P>I do not disagree with your characterization of Members of Congress as generally
honest and hard-working.  But that does not mean they are not bought and sold --
not through illegal means (e.g., bribery) but legal means (campaign
contributions and the "access" that money can, in fact, buy).   Now, you write
that "Moreover, skilled professional advocacy has as rightful a place in
legislative practice as it does in any legal arena."  Precisely where we
disagree.  If Members were, in fact, acting like "judges" -- listening to all
arguments on various sides of public policy issues and then trying to find the
one that best serves the public interest -- advocacy of this kind might be a
good thing.  But that is not, in my experience, what they do.  I've had exposure
to this recently in regard to efforts to modify the Copyright Act.  There's
enormous lobbying activity by many of the discrete interests affected by the
bill -- publishers, the copyright collectives (ASCAP, etc.), the Hollywood
community, etc.  But there is a broad public interest that is really not
considered -- because most people have only the tiniest stake in what happens to
the copyright act, there's no mechanism for their voice to be heard as part of
this debate.  Now, sometimes there's a "special interest" that may be broadly
enough constituted that it stands in for the public -- in the copyright case,
the librarians often function this way.  But often that's not the case.  If the
legislative process is about advocacy for specific interests, there are
structural reasons for thinking that one of the "parties" doesn't have
representation.  Isn't that something people should be concerned about? David   </P>



<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: David R. Johnson -- Counsel Connect - Washington <BR>Date: Wed Jun 12
12:03:58 1996 <BR>Subject: public interest </P>

<P>In your response to David Post, you ask: "What other index of the public's
interest does one have than the petitions of organized groups of motivated and
interested citizens placed before democratically-elected officials?"  </P>

<P>How about the general public interest in a decision making process that brings
all points to bear on public policy debates. Surely, as an advocate for a
particular cause, you would be happy if your position prevailed with minimal
debate or with the members' having limited awareness of opposing arguments. Yet,
from the perspective of the community as a whole, that process -- and it's
substantive outcomes would not be best. </P>

<P>Have you seen Sandel's piece in the Atlantic a month or so ago about the need to
rediscover a sense of "civic" virtue (along the lines of perceiving a public
interest in debating issues from a point of view that values civility and shared
search for truth)? Any reactions to it? </P>

<P>More generally, if you were to adopt (hypothetically, only, perhaps) this
"public interest" point of view, how would you change our current process to
assure, structurally, more systematic canvassing of the views of dispersed
interests? </P>




<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: J B Harris -- Atty - J.B. Harris - Miami <BR>Date: Wed Jun 12 15:42:36
1996 <BR>Subject: The heart of it </P>

<P>This is a terrific dialogue and one that points up the fundamental tension
between democracy and distrust.  The real issue is how do we, as a democratic
society, preserve democracracy that's awash in a sea of undemocratic
institutions and forces.  The institutions that Mr. Boggs and others represent
are by their nature undemocratic.  Firms, corporations and many foreign states
are hierarchical, despotic and exist not to preserve democratic values, but to
subvert them to their own ends, i.e. making money. This means trying to
circumvent environmental, tax, trade and safety and health laws that put a drag
on profits.  While folks certainly benefit from profitability, at what cost to
democracy, at what cost to society?  Perhaps these questions should be
emblazoned on the doorways to the House and Senate, just in case lobbyist and
others forget what's really important.  </P>

<P>JB</P>




<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: Tom Boggs -- Patton Boggs Blow - Washington <BR>Date: Wed Jun 12
15:41:22 1996 <BR>Subject: Anyone can get representation </P>

<P>In David Post's response, he suggests that professional advocacy does not have a
rightful place in the legislative arena because some interests have no voice in
the process.  I disagree.   You think some interests have no voice.  I think
they simply lack substantial interest in the particular issue at stake. </P>

<P>You selected the example of the copyright bill.  Take the ASCAP/BMI issue to
which you refer.  (For those readers who are -- probably thankfully -- unaware
of the issue, the ASCAP issue is a fight over licensing fees between the music
copyright licensing associations and businesses which play copyrighted music as
background noise.)   Is there really a big public interest in that issue which
lacks representation? </P>

<P>The music licensing associations believe that they should be able to charge
restaurants, bowling alleys and movie theatres licensing fees for background
music even if that music is broadcast over a radio station which has already
paid once for the right to use the copyrighted music.  The current law supports
them.  The business establishments argue that music is not their business --
hamburgers, bowling and movies are their business.  They would like to see the
law changed. </P>

<P>In this scenario I presume that the unrepresented "public interest" would be the
consumers who frequent these establishments.  But would bowlers really care if
they knew that they pay, indirectly, a couple pennies a year to have background
music while they bowl?  It just isn't a big enough issue to get worked up about.</P>


<P>But those same bowlers might be represented on other issues more important to
them.  Perhaps they care deeply about their religious beliefs.  Chances are,
their church or synagogue is part of a religious denomination with very
sophisticated representation in Washington.  Those bowlers are consumers, and
may have joined an organization like the Consumer Federation of America, or
supported through subscriptions a group like Consumers Union.  Those two
organizations have some of the most talented lobbyists in Washington.  Those
bowlers may have a little money in a retirement account.  That account is
probably invested in mutual funds.  The funds are made up of corporations, among
others.  Both the mutual funds and the corporations probably have Washington
lobbyists fighting hard to improve their bottom line, so that the fund can
perform better, and our bowlers pensions can grow!  Maybe the bowlers are
retirees who belong to the AARP or the National Alliance for Senior Citizens,
two more groups with suburb organizational skills here in Washington.  I think
you get the point.  Our bowlers have a lot of influence. </P>

<P>My response to David Johnson's comment is similar.  What is the "public
interest" on any given issue?    I would be much more worried with a system
where policy makers would try to divine in a vacuum what the "civic virtue"
should be.  We have a representative democracy so that people, with interests,
can tell their elected representives what they want them to do.  Don't trust
your government.  Trust the people. </P>

<P>I also disagree that a "more systematic canvassing of views" would make for
better policy making.  Should we legislate by opinion survey?  If individuals
REALLY care about a particular issue, they will join together with like minded
individuals and petition their government.  Why should elected officials believe
that their constituents really care about an issue just because some couch
potatoes answered the phone one night and responded to an opinion survey? </P>









<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: David R. Johnson -- Counsel Connect - Washington <BR>Date: Wed Jun 12
21:18:58 1996 <BR>Subject: follow up </P>

<P>I agree with you that surveys are inferior to informed and interested dialogue.
(that's not what I meant by systematic canvassing, but the inadequate expression
was my own.) </P>

<P>And there may or may not be a discernible public interest "on any given issue". </P>

<P>But you didn't fully engage my question, which was: does the public's interest
in having policy questions decided optimally, from the perspective of the group
as a whole, suggest any changes in our current system. </P>

<P>I understand that you argue that representation of those who care deeply enough
to form a group to hire a lobbyist is a good proxy for the intensity of their
concerns. But doesn't that systematically disserve the real but not critical
interests that people have in things that don't affect them so centrally that
they can or will mobilize. Doesn't your position mean anyone can get away with
stealing a few cents (or a few utils) from everyone, because the transaction and
information costs of mobilizing in opposition are just too high to allow any
counterattack? </P>

<P>You are persuasive on the need to make a contrary case by showing a practical
alternative that doesn't simply empower those who purport to speak for some
ephemeral "public interest" to impose their own will. But there may be such an
alternative: a representative, deliberative body access to which is not
preferentially given to those willing to spend (or raise as a group and spend)
substantial sums of money. </P>

<P>I sense your response to this will be that such a body cannot exist -- because
factions will raise and spend money on those issues that are important enough to
them, no matter what structural reforms we might make. So we might as well relax
and enjoy it. But Federalist No. 10 suggests the contrary -- that structural
changes could limit the impact of factions by making it harder for those who
share specific interest to find each other, by making it harder for them to
reach the representatives, etc. </P>

<P>As a thought experiment, let's suppose that we walled off each Congress from
contact with the outside world after it convenes and until it adjourns. Should
make it harder to spend money to influence the debate. Doesn't, to be sure,
prevent lots of other forms of influence. But is it a good idea, or bad? And
why? </P>




<P><hr></P>

<P>Appended by: David Post -- Georgetown Law Ctr. - Washington <BR>Date: Thu Jun 13
12:04:37 1996 <BR>Subject: Bowling </P>

<P>Not to beat a dead horse, but -- my point is precisely the one you make, that
the bowlers don't care as much about this issue as do either the ASCAPs of the
world or the bowling industry.  That's why we have mohair subsidies -- because
mohair growers (do you 'grow' mohair??) care *a lot* and consumers don't care
very much about the penny or two additional they pay.  So Members of Congress
see this as a debate between ASCAP and the Bowling Alley Association of America,
or between the domestic mohair producers and the mohair importers.  Congress in
theory is supposed to choose those policies that maximize the general welfare --
but they see themselves as only choosing between those groups that have a
pre-eminent economic stake, without really considering the small individual
stakes -- those individuall pennies that you and I pay -- that may add up to a
BIG number. David </P>
</blockquote>
