<PRE>
</PRE>


Editor's Note:  The following is a transcript of a speech given by
Senator Bob Dole in front of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors.


<H3 align=center>SENATOR BOB DOLE REMARKS PREPARED FOR DELIVERY 
<BR><BR>
AMERICAN SOCIETY OF NEWSPAPER EDITORS
<BR><BR>
WASHINGTON, DC<BR>
APRIL 19, 1996</H3>

<P>Thank you, Edward Seaton for that introduction and thank you all for
the opportunity to be here today. </P>

<P>I know that most speakers who address this audience start with a
discussion of freedom of the press and the vital role of the Fourth
Estate in defending this most precious of constitutional guarantees. 
But as important as the press's constitutional contribution is, there
is much more to your place in our economy and society, much that
makes this industry a good snapshot of what my campaign for President
this year will be all about. </P>

<P>In the coming months, I will be talking about entrepreneurship,
economic growth, and the opportunities that the new global economy
will open to all of us -- if the right policies come from Washington.</P>


<P>I will also be talking about reaffirming America's core values --
respect for the rule of law, reverence for our faiths, devotion to
integrity and reason in our national discourse, dedication to family,
optimism about the future, belief in hard work, personal
responsibility, and honesty in our dealings. </P>

<P>And when we talk about reaffirming the values of our national life,
newspapers are among the prime transmitters of our values -- in the
character of reporting, in the open forums for serious debate that so
many editorial pages have become, in a medium driven by respect for
ideas and national discourse. </P>

<P>I believe this campaign takes place at a defining moment in our
national history.  And the choice the American people will make this
November could not be more profound. </P>

<P>Will we have, as our founders intended, a government controlled by
the people, or a people increasingly controlled by an ever larger,
more arrogant, and more intrusive government? </P>

<P>The President says "the era of big government is over," but two years
ago he hit American families with the largest tax increase in
history, and , as a result, our economy limps along at sub-standard
growth rates -- barely half the average rate of the 1980's. </P>

<P>A growing national debt eats away at our future, and our children's
future, yet that same President chose to veto the first balanced
budget in a generation, offering a fantasy budget in its place that
won't make real cuts until the next century. </P>

<P>A liberal education establishment leaves 25 percent of our high
school seniors functionally illiterate, and a seemingly perpetual
welfare bureaucracy assaults the values of self-reliance and breaks
families apart by driving fathers away. </P>

<P>Yet the President opposes serious attempts to reform education and
vetoed a welfare bill that would have truly ended the scourge of
"welfare as we know it." </P>

<P>But of all the values and issues that we will be debating in this
campaign, perhaps none is more important than the one we used to take
for granted -- Americans' confidence in their courts and trust in the
rule of law. </P>

<P>We hear a great deal about the sense of uncertainty that so many
Americans feel.  And, as we know, corporate layoffs are among the
sources of this anxiety -- together with the sliding of after-tax
incomes, which have begun declining again after their steady rise in
the 1980's. </P>

<P>But, I believe there is a reason beyond economics for the concern so
many of us feel -- and that's the lowering of what the editors of the
Wall Street Journal called sometime ago our social "guard rails," the
standards that guide day-to-day behavior, that make for a sense of
civility and fairness and right and wrong in our daily lives. </P>

<P>Our courts and our legal system were intended to be the most secure
of those guard rails.  They are supposed to set predictable standards
of what is fair and unfair, of what is right and wrong, of what the
law says and what it doesn't say. </P>

<P>They should be the glue that holds our society together, that helps
to guarantee all Americans a right as precious as any other -- the
right to live and raise our families in peaceful, law-abiding
communities, to send our children to school without fear of violence
and drugs, to feel safe in our homes and on our streets. </P>

<P>That is how it should be.  But American today is a society in which
law-abiding citizens feel increasingly at risk.  You know the
figures.  Each and every year, some 43 million Americans are victims
of crime.  Some 11 million are victims of violent crime. </P>

<P>Most Americans surely share the concern of FBI Director Louis Freeh,
who said that crime remains at "intolerable levels" and warned of the
disturbing skyrocketing of violent crimes by juveniles.  No society
that considers itself civilized can accept an annual death toll of
almost 24,000 murders, no matter how bad the previous year's carnage.</P>


<P>There are many reasons for the crime explosion:  the proliferation of
drugs; the almost total obliteration of the family in the welfare
culture of the inner city where as many as 80 percent of all children
are born out of wedlock, and too many into a life of neglect; and
maybe -- I certainly believe it to be the case -- a popular culture
that in movies and television glorifies violence, casual sex, and
anti-social behavior.  I have spoken on these issues -- and I will
continue to throughout this campaign. </P>

<P>Today, however, I want to address another issue, one that is also
devastating.  If we are looking for the "root causes" of the crime
explosion, this is clearly one of them. </P>

<P>I am speaking of the crisis in our courts.  The crisis in our legal
system.  And the crisis of confidence this is causing in America. </P>

<P>The legal guard rails that protected our society -- that ensured a
certain fundamental level of security and safety for America's
families -- those guard rails have in many places been knocked down,
even dismantled, often by the very judges and jurists who have been
entrusted with the sacred duty of upholding the rule of law. </P>

<P>Now, of course I'm aware that whenever one focuses the spotlight of
criticism on the actions of some of our judges, a hue and cry is
raised about the "independence of the judiciary."  Judicial
independence is a basic, vital constitutional principle, one that
every elected official is sworn to uphold, as we are sworn to uphold
the Constitution.  It is a principle that I take very seriously as a
Senator. </P>

<P>But there is nothing in the Constitution that says judges should be
above criticism, that they can not or should not be held up to
scrutiny for their actions -- actions that often have a huge and
immediate impact on American life, actions that help shape the
character of our nation. </P>

<P>Our founders intended our judges to be independent, not untouchable. 
All of us in public life are subject to criticism.  It's possible
that even I might come in for a little criticism between now and
November.  It's all part of the vigorous debate of ideas and policies
that makes democracy work. </P>

<P>And I believe that the kind of judges we appoint -- and the basic
philosophies they hold -- should be an important issue in this
campaign for the Presidency of the United States.  Because in the
long run, the federal judges a President chooses may be his most
profound legacy.  Legislation comes and goes.  A bad bill this year
can be voted down next year.  Bud judges remain. Long after the
President leaves office, they will still be on the bench -- the
rulings they make stretching out over a lifetime, affecting the lives
not just of one generation, but their children too. </P>

<P>Let me say that not all Republican-appointed judges are perfect and
not all Democrat-appointed judges are bad. Most judges are fine
public servants and out of deference to a President's constitutional
prerogative I have not opposed most of President Clinton's judicial
nominees. But the fact is, when it comes to what kind of judges we
want to appoint to the federal bench, President Clinton and I
fundamentally differ. </P>

<P>It's no secret where I stand. I've said it before. I will say it to
you now. </P>

<P>I will appoint justices to the Supreme Court who know how to read and
respect the clear language of the Constitution as it is written and
don't search to find rationalizations for their liberal agenda in
so-called "emanations" and "penumbras" never intended or imagined by
founders. </P>

<P>I will appoint judges who respect the rule of law, who understand
that society is not to blame for crime, criminals are; judges who
protect the rights of crime victims, not invent ever newer and more
expansive "rights" for criminal defendants. </P>

<P>And Dole judges will hand down strict sentences to criminals in order
to protect law-abiding citizens from further violence and harm. </P>

<P>I find it shameful that law-abiding Americans are often locked behind
bars -- the security bars on the windows of their homes -- while
criminals are left free to roam the streets. </P>

<P>President Clinton may talk the same language as I do on many of these
issues. I know he does. But as, I'm sorry to say, with so many
things, his actions profoundly depart from the meaning of his words. </P>

<P>Many of the judges Mr. Clinton has appointed to the federal bench are
precisely the ones who are dismantling those guard rails that protect
society from the predatory, the violent, the anti-social elements in
our midst. </P>

<P>His appointees to the Supreme court have been among the most willing
to use technicalities to overturn death sentences for brutal
murderers. They frequently vote to grant last minute stays of
execution, even when the death row inmate's claims are plainly
frivolous. </P>

<P>And a startling number of Mr. Clinton's lower court judges have
demonstrated an outright hostility to law enforcement. </P>

<P>You've all heard, many of you have probably written about, the
infamous decision of Judge Harold Baer in New York, who found that it
was perfectly reasonable for men to run from the police, because --
he said -- residents in the area regard law enforcement as "corrupt."
He added that he would have been suspicious, quote, "had the men not
run when the cops began to stare at them." Based on this "reasoning"
-- I put the word in quotation marks -- Judge Baer suppressed the
physical evidence the police found: 75 pounds of cocaine and 4 pounds
of heroin -- $4 million worth of poisonous drugs. He even suppressed
the defendant's voluntary confession. </P>

<P>As I say, Judge Baer's decision received some notoriety, and he even
reversed his decision when the criticism mounted -- finally coming
from an embarrassed White House itself. But the appalling fact is,
Judge Baer is hardly an exception among Clinton judicial appointees. </P>

<P>Let me give you a few more examples from Bill Clinton's judicial
"Hall of Shame." </P>

<P>Take the case of Clinton-appointee Judge Leonie Brinkema of Virginia,
who disregarded U.S. sentencing guidelines to go easy on a man who
was convicted of three counts of murder for hire, saying the
defendant was "naive" and "unrealistic," undeserving of the
punishment required by law. </P>

<P>Or Judge Rosemary Barkett, who previously served on the Florida
Supreme Court. While on this court, she joined a dissenting opinion
that exemplifies the liberal view of the criminal as victim of
society. This is how Judge Barkett described a brutal,
racially-motivated killing, quote, "This case is not simply a
homicide case, it is also a social awareness case." The murderer, the
judges declared, was motivated by the "pervasive illness of racial
discrimination" and the victim was, in the murderer's eyes, only "a
symbolic representative of the class causing the perceived
injustices." </P>

<P>When judges make decisions like this, they don't so much wield a
gavel as wield a sledgehammer against the delicate structure of the
rule of law. Bill Clinton rewarded this judge with a seat on the
Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals where she continues to press her
liberal agenda. </P>

<P>For this decision, Judge Barkett wins a leading role in Bill
Clinton's judicial Hall of Shame, but in many ways she is outdone by
another Clinton appointee, Judge H. Lee Sarokin. Judge Sarokin first
attained national fame as a federal district court judge, ruling in
favor of a homeless man who had been evicted from a public library in
New Jersey because he harassed library personnel, talked loudly to
himself, and emitted a body odor sufficiently overpowering to drive
away patrons and staff. Judge Sarokin, in a decision of
quintessential liberal self-rightousness, lectured, quote, "[if] we
wish to shield our eyes and ears from the homeless, we should revoke
their condition, not their library cards." </P>

<P>Judge Sarokin attained additional fame when the Third Circuit Court
of Appeals took the extraordinary step of removing him from a tobacco
case for blatant bias. Even the New York Times applauded the removal,
stating that Judge Sarokin had "flunked an important test of
credibility." </P>

<P>Even more startling, in an article published in the West Virginia Law
Review, Judge Sarokin suggests that pre-trial and pre-conviction
detention of violent criminals is somehow unconstitutional. If this
radical position were to prevail, vicious criminals would be free to
roam the streets before their convictions -- or flee until they get
caught again . . . if they are caught again. </P>

<P>This judge, who twists the Constitution to impose his liberal views
of social policy, whose bias in the courtroom is so blatant that he
had to be removed from a case -- this judge was hand-picked by
President Clinton to sit on the Third Circuit Court of Appeals, the
second highest court in the land -- and the very court that had
removed him for bias earlier. </P>

<P>I voted against confirming Judge Sarokin. I have profound questions
whether such a man should be sitting on the federal bench, let alone
one of the highest courts in the land. And I think it is a profoundly
important question that the American people will have to ask this
November -- if our society can afford to keep in office a President
who consistently appoints such liberal judges to the federal bench. </P>

<P>As it stands right now, Mr. Clinton has appointed nearly 25 percent
of all the sitting judges. In another four years, he might easily be
able to bring that number to more than 50 percent. </P>

<P>Do we really want the majority of judges on the federal bench to
think like Judges Barkett, Baer, Brinkema, and Sarokin -- an all-star
team of liberal leniency -- judges who seem intent on dismantling the
rule of law from the bench? </P>

<P>Then there's the Supreme Court. Since Bill Clinton took office, some
of the High Court's most important rulings -- on issues ranging from
affirmative action to private property rights to religious expression
in public schools -- were decided by just one vote. If we give Bill
Clinton the opportunity to make just one more appointment to the
Supreme Court, we could have the most liberal court since the Warren
Court of the 1960s. </P>

<P>We could lock in liberal judicial activism for the next generation,
and the social landscape could dramatically change. More federal
intrusion in the lives of average Americans. More centralized power
in Washington. Less freedom of religious expression. More rights for
criminals -- and more arrogant disregard of the rights of law-abiding
citizens. </P>

<P>Now I want to be clear. Federal judges do have a duty to protect the
rights of the accused to a fair trial. Judges should have the power
to strike down laws that are contrary to the Constitution. </P>

<P>But the power of the courts to override the sovereign will of the
people comes with a heavy responsibility, and must be used with the
utmost restraint -- without that restraint, judicial review becomes
nothing less than judicial tyranny. </P>

<P>I believe that it is vital to America that in the coming months of
this campaign President Clinton and I debate in a forthright and
candid manner our two very different visions of the federal
judiciary.  He has a clear record -- let him explain to the American
people the principles that guided his appointments of Judges Barkett,
Baer, Brinkema, and Sarokin -- and so many others like them. </P>

<P>And I will forthrightly and candidly lay down my principles because I
think the American people have a right to know. </P>

<P>For me, as I have said, foremost among those principles is respect
for the clear and evident meaning of the Constitution, which includes
the much neglected and abused 10th Amendment. </P>

<P>Dole judges will know the 10th Amendment by heart.  It reads; "The
powers not delegated to the United States by the Constitution, nor
prohibited by it to the States, are reserved to the States
respectively, or to the people." The federal power grab will end in
the Dole Administration. </P>

<P>Dole judges will also share the American people's -- and the
Constitution's -- vision of a color blind society free of
discrimination.  We are a nation built on the principle of individual
rights and responsibilities, and laws that divide our citizens by
race or group strike at the heart of what America is all about. 
After thirty years of liberal experimentation, America knows that
state-mandated discrimination caused only bitterness and division,
and undermines the foundation of fairness on which any society must
be built. </P>

<P>Americans deserve fairness, not favoritism. </P>

<P>I've always been a big believer in public discourse. The more the
American people know about what government officials -- including
federal judges -- are doing in their name, the stronger our democracy
will be.  As President, I will respect the public's right to know by
requiring my Attorney General to publish an annual report collecting
and summarizing the decisions of our federal judges in the area of
criminal law.  Thanks to the members of the Fourth Estate, we learned
of Judge Baer -- but how many similar decisions go unreported,
unknown to the public at large? </P>

<P>I also intend to stop the harassment of our legal system by convicted
criminals, who last year filed more than 65,000 civil lawsuits
against the government in federal court, most of them entirely
frivolous.  The cost to the taxpayer was about $81 million.  Over the
same time, the Justice Department initiated only about 45,000
prosecutions.  In other words, convicted criminals outscored our
Justice Department by 20,000 lawsuits.  I introduced a bill to shut
down this waste of taxpayers' money.  President Clinton vetoed it. 
As President, I will make sure that it passes. </P>

<P>Finally, it is time to remove the American Bar Association from its
role in reviewing potential judicial appointees.  Originally founded
to ensure "competence and integrity" in the bar, the ABA has become
nothing more than another blatantly partisan liberal advocacy group. </P>

<P>In my hands, I have the ABA's 1995 lobbying disclosure form, which
lists the ABA's position on many of the issues that have come before
Congress.  Here are some of the highlights: </P>

<P>Mandatory minimum sentences for dealers who sell drugs to children. 
The ABA is opposed. </P>

<P> A constitutional amendment to protect the flag. 
The ABA is opposed. </P>

<P> The Religious Equality Amendment allowing 
voluntary school prayer.  The ABA is opposed. </P>

<P>Meaningful habeas corpus reform.  Real product liability reform. 
Prison litigation reform.  Opposed, opposed, opposed. </P>

<P>The ABA even opposes closing legal loopholes that would make it
easier to convict vicious sex offenders. With that kind of record of
liberal political activism, why do we allow the American Bar
Association to judge our judges? </P>

<P>In a Dole Administration, the American Bar Association will no longer
have a retainer at the White House and the trial lawyers will not be
calling the shots.  in place of the narrowly partisan and
ideologically liberal ABA, I will create a non-partisan Judicial
Integrity Panel, consisting of police, prosecutors, crime victims,
legal scholars, and representatives of other legal and professional
organizations.  As President, I will look to this panel -- not the
ABA -- to advise me who is, and who isn't, qualified to sit on the
federal bench. </P>

<P>America has a choice this November.  Will we continue down the path
his Administration has set us on -- of liberal experimentation in our
courts -- or will we regain the common sense and common wisdom
contained in the very clearly written prose of our Constitution? </P>

<P>Will we restore confidence in the rule of law?  Will we restore the
American people's trust in the fairness of our legal system?  Will
the law once again become an expression of our deepest values as a
nation?  Will it support the "guard rails" of individual
responsibility, of a civil society that is itself truly civil? </P>

<P>I am determined to make the rule of law the rule in America once
again.  I am determined to do all that is in the President's power to
re-establish the integrity of our courts and restore safety,
fairness, and civility to our land. </P>

<P>To establish justice and ensure domestic tranquility are two of the
primary objectives of our Constitution.  And they will be my sacred
objectives as President. </P>

<P>Thank you and God bless America.</P>


<H2>FACT SHEET</H2>

<P>Bob Dole believes that the kind of judges we appoint -- and the basic
philosophies they hold -- should be an important issue in this
campaign.  Indeed, in the long run, the federal judges a President
chooses may be his most profound and lasting legacy. </P>

<P>As it now stands, President Clinton has appointed nearly 25% of all
federal judges and if reelected this number would probably exceed
50%.  The American people must ask themselves whether they can afford
to reelect a president who will continue to appoint liberal judges
who too often seem intent on dismantling the rule of law from the
bench. </P>

<P>As President, Bob Dole will attack this crisis at its core and
appoint judges who protect the rights of crime victims, not invent
newer and more expansive "rights" for criminal defendants.  He will
appoint judges who respect the rule of law, who understand that
society is not to blame for crime, criminals are. </P>

<P>Here are just several examples of President Clinton's judicial "Hall
of Shame": </P><UL>

<P><LI> District Judge Harold Baer of New York suppressed as evidence
almost 80 pounds of drugs and the voluntary confession of the
defendant because he believed that the police did not have cause to
search a car after they witnessed four men place large duffel bags in
the car and then run when they spotted the police.  Judge Baer's
"reasoning" was that in this particular neighborhood, residents must
regard the police as "corrupt" and therefore it would have been
suspicious "had the men not run when the cops began to stare at
them."  Judge Baer reversed his ill-reasoned opinion after much
public scrutiny.  <I>U.S. v. Bayless</I>, 913 F. Supp. 232 (S.D.N.Y. 1996). </P>

<P><LI>  Judge Rosemary Barkett of the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals, while
serving on the Florida Supreme Court, joined a dissenting opinion
that described a brutal, racially-motivated killing as "a social
awareness case." Judge Barkett insisted that the killer had "socially
redeeming values," even though he stabbed his victim repeatedly, shot
him twice, and laughed at the victim while he pled for his life. 
<I>Dougan v. State of Florida</I>, 515 So.2d 1 (Fla. 1992). </P>

<P><LI> District Judge Leonie Brinkema of Virginia disregarded U.S.
Sentencing Guidelines and reduced the sentence of a man convicted of
three counts of murder for hire in part because she felt the
defendant was "naive" and "unrealistic."  <I>U.S. v. Morin</I>
(unpublished). </P>

<P><LI> District Judge Raymond Jackson of Virginia dismissed all federal
charges against a youth because he thought there was no substantial
federal interest in prosecuting a juvenile for armed robbery.  <I>U.S.
v. Male Juvenile</I>, 844 F. Supp. 280 (E.D. Va. 1994). </P>

<P><LI>  Judge M. Blane Michael of the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals who
joined a dissent with Carter appointees arguing that a not
fully-operative letter bomb sent to a U.S. Attorney was not a
"dangerous weapon."  <I>U.S. v. Harnrick</I>, 43 F.3d 877 (4th Cir. 1995)
(en banc). </P>

<P>Not only are the lower courts at risk, but our nation's highest Court
is as well.  Many of the Supreme Court's most important rulings since
Bill Clinton took office -- on issues ranging from affirmative action
(<I>Adarand v. Pena</I>, 115 S. Ct. 2097 (1995)) to private property rights
(<I>Dolan v. City of Tigard</I>, 114 S. Ct. 2309 (1994)) to religious
expression in public schools (<I>Rosenberger v. University of Virginia</I>,
115 S.Ct. 2510 (1995)) -- were decided by just one vote.  If Bill
Clinton is given the opportunity to make just one more appointment to
the Supreme Court, the result could be the most liberal court since
the Warren Court of the 1960s. </P>
</UL>

<I>See <a href=http://www.dole96.com>Dole's homepage</a> and the <a href=http://www.abanet.org/>American Bar Association's homepage</a></I> <I> for more information.</I><BR>

