<H2><a href=vol5.htm><B>VOLUME V</B></a></H2>


<H3>FDA LACKS
AUTHORITY TO REGULATE<BR>
CIGARETTES AS MEDICAL DEVICES</H3>

A.
INTRODUCTION................V-1<P>
B. CIGARETTES ARE NOT MEDICAL "DEVICES"<BR>
 WITHIN
THE MEANING OF THE FDCA............V-6<P>
 1. A Product Must Be Intended<BR>
 for
Medical Use To Be a<BR>
 Medical "Device"..............V-7<P>
 2. Cigarettes Are Not
Medical "Devices"<BR>
 Because FDA Has Expressly<BR>
 Found That They Achieve<BR>
 Their
Primary Intended Purposes<BR>
 Through Chemical Means............V-16<P>
 a. FDA Has
Found That Cigarettes<BR>
 Affect a Structure or Function<BR>
 of the Body Only Through
the<BR>
 Supposed Pharmacological<BR>
 Effect of Nicotine...........V-16<P>
 b. A Drug
Delivery System<BR>
 Containing a Drug Is a<BR>
 "Drug," Not a
"Device"...........V-19<P>
c. Cigarettes Are Not<BR>
"Combination
Products"............. V-29<P>
 3.  The Combination Product Provisions<BR>
of Section
503(g) of the FDCA Do Not<BR>
Make Cigarettes "Devices," and<BR>
Heckler v. Chaney Does
Not Give<BR>
FDA Discretion To Do So..............     V-35<P>
a. FDA Does Not Have
the<BR>
Unfettered Discretion It<BR>
Asserts To Choose or Ignore<BR>
Regulatory
Requirements..........     V-36<P>
b. Section 503(g) of the FDCA<BR>
Does Not Give FDA
Such<BR>
Discretion............     V-41<P>
 (i) The Text of Section
503(g)........V-41<P>
 (ii) The Legislative History<BR>
 of Section
503(g)............V-43<P>
 c. FDA's Regulation Implementing<BR>
 Section 503(g) Does
Not Give<BR>
 the Agency Discretion To Choose<BR>
Which FDCA Requirements Apply<BR>
 to
Cigarettes.............. V-50<P>
 d. Heckler v. Chaney Does Not Give<BR>
 FDA
Discretion To Ignore Mandatory<BR>
 Statutory Provisions...........  V-53<P>
C.
CIGARETTES MAY NOT BE REGULATED AS<BR>
 "RESTRICTED DEVICES" AS PROPOSED BY FDA....... 
V-56<P>
 1. Section 520(e) Only Permits FDA To<BR>
 Restrict Medical Devices To Use
by<BR>
 or Under the Supervision of Qualified<BR>
 Health Professionals............ 
V-57<P>
 a. Statute and Legislative History.........  V-57<P>
 b. Administrative
Precedents........ V-62<P>
 2. FDA's Proposal Does Not Satisfy<BR>
 Section 520(e)'s
Threshold Requirement<BR>
 That Restrictions Must Make a Device<BR>
 Safe for Its Intended
Users........  V-64<P>
 3. Section 520(e) Does Not Authorize<BR>
 Restrictions on
Advertising or Promotion....  V-67<P>
 4.  Section 520(e) Restrictions May
Not<BR>
Extend to Matters Ancillary to Sale,<BR>
Distribution, or Use of the
Physical<BR>
Device Itself................   V-73<P>
 5.  FDA's Decision To Regulate
Cigarettes<BR>
as Medical "Devices" Produces<BR>
Untenable Conflicts with
Other<BR>
Statutory Provisions............... V-76<P>
<P>
-- ii
--<P>

a. Conflicts with Other Statutes...........     V-77<P>
(i)
Conflict with FCLAA Provision<BR>
Relating to Cigarette Labels.......     V-77<P>
(ii)
Conflict with FCLAA Provision<BR>
for Confidentiality of
Cigarette<BR>
Ingredients............     V-82<P>
b. Disregard of Mandatory
Provisions<BR>
of the FDCA................     V-83<P>
(i) Device
Classification...........     V-83<P>
(ii) Premarket Review............    
V-88<P>
 (iii) Adequate Warnings for<BR>
Protection of Users and<BR>
Adequate
Directions for Use........     V-92<P>
(iv) Reports by Manufacturers........    
V-92<P>
(v) Postmarket Surveillance.........     V-93<P>
(vi) Device User Facility
Reports........     V-94<P>
 (vii) "Dangerous" Devices Are<BR>
Misbranded.............    
V-95<P>
(viii) Mandatory Recall............     V-97<P>
c. FDA Has Created a
Regulatory<BR>
Scheme Never Authorized by<BR>
Congress...............    
V-97<P>
