<H3>COMMENTS ON FDA's PROPOSED REGULATIONS<BR>
PART 897<BR>
SUBPART D -- LABELING
AND ADVERTISING</H3>


PART 897<P>
Subpart D--Labeling
and Advertising........VII-1<P>
A.  Proposed Subpart D Exceeds FDA's<BR>
Authority
Under the FDCA.............VII-2<P>
1.  FDCA Sections 520(e) and 502 Do<BR>
Not
Authorize FDA's Proposed<BR>
Advertising Regulations...........VII-2<P>
2.  FDA Has
Expanded the Scope of "Labeling"<BR>
Beyond Statutory Limits..........VII-6<P>
B. 
Proposed Subpart D Is Contrary to<BR>
Law and Violates the First
Amendment........VII-10<P>
1.  Subpart D Is Precluded by the ADAMHA<BR>
Reorganization
Act of 1992 and the<BR>
Federal Cigarette Labeling and<BR>
Advertising
Act............VII-10<P>
2.  Under the First Amendment, the<BR>
Government May Not
Restrict Speech<BR>
To Alter Social Attitudes or To Mute<BR>
Messages Deemed To Be
Inconsistent<BR>
with Government Policy..........VII-10<P>
3.  The Proposed
Regulations Do Not Pass<BR>
Muster Under the First Amendment<BR>
Because FDA Cannot
Demonstrate That<BR>
the Regulations "Will In Fact"<BR>
Directly and Materially Advance
the<BR>
Agency's Stated Goals and Are<BR>
"Sufficiently Tailored" to Those
Goals......VII-11<P>
a.  The Supreme Court's Test for Restrictions<BR>
on Commercial
Speech Place a Heavy Burden<BR>
of Justification on FDA........VII-11<P>
<P>
b. 
The Supreme Court Has Rejected<BR>
FDA's "Greater-Includes-the-Lesser"<BR>
Rationale for
Subpart D's<BR>
Restrictions on Commercial Speech......VII-16<P>
4.  FDA Has Not
Demonstrated That Its<BR>
Proposed Rules "Will In Fact" Reduce<BR>
Underage
Smoking..............VII-19<P>
a.  Young People Begin To Smoke<BR>
Primarily Because
of the Influence<BR>
of Family and Friends, and Not<BR>
Because of
Advertising.........VII-19<P>
