<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of June 17:</B></TT></font> </P>





<P><B><a href="/spotlight/cda/">Seminar- <I>Decent Exposure:  CDA Ruling</I></a></B><ul>

Calling the Internet "a never-ending world-wide conversation" which "deserves

the highest protection 

 from governmental intrusion," a federal three-judge panel ruled that the

Communications Decency Act

 is unconstitutional and granted the ACLU's motion for a preliminary injunction.

 To contact 

 legal experts for comment, see <a href="/counselquote/">Counsel Quote</a>.  

</ul>

</P><P>



<a href="/spotlight/boggs.html"><B>Virtual Power Lunch: Thomas Hale Boggs Jr.</B></a></font><ul>

Thomas Hale Boggs Jr. is one of the most prominent lobbyists in

the country. No stranger to the halls of power, he is the son of two members of

Congress. Boggs is online on Counsel 

Connect discussing the role he's played as lobbyist in Washington, D.C., during

the last 30 years. Here he is discussing the usefulness of lobbying. <P>

</ul>



<P><b><a href="http://www.wolfenet.com/~dhillis/opinion2.htm"><i>Considerations When Placing

  Court Opinions on the Internet</i></a></b><ul>

Court opinions are making themselves at home on the Web. Opinions of the U.S.

Supreme Court, all federal circuit courts, and more and more state courts appear

in cyberland.  As courts post opinions online, judicial webmasters grapple with

vexing issues. Hypertext or text files? How to ensure accuracy?  How long to

post?  What about footnotes?  Read legal analyst Bradley J. Hillis' ambitious

commentary for e-court lovers.

</ul>



</P>



