<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of June 3:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.sec.gov/edgarhp.htm">EDGAR Database</a></b>

<ul>

Want to inspect Microsoft's 1995 annual report?  How about Exxon's latest 10Q

filing?  Step over to the Securities and Exchange Commission's home page and plug

into EDGAR, that famous, humongous, searchable database of recent corporate

securities filings.  According to the SEC, as of May, 1996 all public domestic

companies are required to file via EDGAR.

</ul>





</P><P> 





<P><b><a href="http://www.usis.usemb.se/human/index.htm ">Human Rights Practices, 1995</a></b><ul>

In 1995, from Angola to Rwanda, in "many countries around the world widespread

abuses of human rights continued unabated."  Here's the report submitted to

Congress by the Department of State on the status of internationally recognized

human rights. The U.S. will use these unsettling findings to set policy, engage

in diplomacy and offer assistance globally. 

</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a



href="http://enso.unl.edu:80/ndmc">National Drought Mitigation Center</a></B>

<ul>

Never mind twisters, Hollywood's disaster darling of the summer of '96.  The

real threat being battled across the southwest, in Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, and

other states, is one of the worst droughts on record.  For maps, links and

information on droughts, rainfall, climate, water resources, and research

projects in the U.S. and around the world, visit this site from the University

of Nebraska-Lincoln.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a 

href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/Publications/html/Publications-plain.html">White House

