<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of May 27:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.atlanet.org">Association of Trial Lawyers of America</a></b><ul>

Calling itself "the world's largest trial bar," with 60,000 members and offline

headquarters in Washington, DC, ATLA hosts an exclusive service for Association

insiders. ATLA's webclub features recent federal and state opinions, info on upcoming

events and ATLA educational programs, ATLA publications, its amicus curiae briefs,

links, and a "Web Tour for Trial Lawyers."

</ul>





</P><P> 





<P><b><a href="http://theway.com/teahan/dt2.html">Death and Taxes</a></b><ul>

Quick--what are the two things no one can avoid? You know the answer.  And now, from

the New York firm of Teahan & Constantino, here's an electronic newsletter devoted

to developments in estate planning and tax law, making everyone's least favorite

subjects, well, less painful to face. Death and Taxes analyzes the law and offers

tips for planners. Don't miss the new New York Official Probate Petition.

</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a



href="http://www2.cob.ohio-state.edu/~richards/banking.htm">Electronic Banking Resource

Center</a></B>

<ul>

What are the differences between Secure Electronic Payment Protocol (SEPP) and Micro

Payment Transfer Protocol (MPTP)? What is Money Magic?  Clickshare?  NetPay?  Thanks

to an enterprising MBA student at Ohio State University, e-customers can cash in on

the latest info on e-banking and virtual money payment standards.  With a collection

of links to cyberbanks and other e-commerce entities.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a 

href="http://www.osha.gov">Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA)</a></B> 

<ul>



One hundred million American working folks and their six and a half million employers

are covered by the Occupational Health and safety Act of 1970.   The Act and much

more come alive on OSHA's weboffice.  Read OSHA regs, compliance assistance info,

articles and fact sheets on OSHA policy, procedures and programs, workplace safety,

employer guidelines and lots more.  Be careful out there.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a href="http://www.house.gov/white/internet_caucus/netcauc.html">Congressional Internet

Caucus</a></B><ul>



Some call them the government's wired evangelists. A bipartisan group of savvy

cyberfaring congresspersons have joined together to spread the Net word and get other

members of Congress online.  Formed by Republican Rick White, from Microsoft's home

state, the Internet Caucus posts on its home page a cyberpledge, statement of

principles, open letter to the Net community, and a roster of members.</ul>

</P>







<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of May 20:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.ustr.gov/reports/tpa/1996/contents.html">1996 Trade Policy Agenda and 1995

Annual Report</a></b><ul>

Last year, total U.S. trade increased 16.1 percent, hitting a record $2.2 trillion. 

Travel out to this new trading post and invest time in reviewing President Clinton's

recently released agenda for implementation of trade agreements such as NAFTA, along

with highlights of bilateral and regional agreements, and the annual report on the

Trade Agreements Program.

</ul>





</P><P> 





<P><b><a href="http://www.faa.gov">Federal Aviation Administration</a></b><ul>





As investigations continue into the deadly crash of a Valujet DC-9 in the Florida

Everglades this month, visit the FAA's webport to find out about the federal

government's role in aviation safety and regulation.  The FAA posts info about its

activities and offices, news releases, fact sheets, Air Traffic Services (ATS)

materials, and a "Hot Topics" section.  Fly through links to other aviation sites.

</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a



href="http://www.findlaw.com/search/lawcrawler.html">LawCrawler</a></B>

<ul>

Another slick new search engines hits webtown as FindLaw rolls out LawCrawler, a tool

for searching legal sites across the Net.  Using LawCrawler, lawyers and other

law-seeking cybercitizens may limit research to particular legal sites in, for

example, selected countries or regions, U.S. states, or U.S. government branches or

agencies.  Try it.

</ul>







</p><P>



<B> <a 

href="http://www.duke.edu/%7Eptavern/Pete.meta-index.html">Meta-Index of Non-Profit

Organizations</a></B> 

<ul>From Charity Village to Nonprofit Prophets, here's a comprehensive warehouse of hot

links to non-profit resources across the datasphere.  Commendable categories include

human rights, health, civil liberties, politics, environmental issues and animal

rights. A thousand points of cyberlight.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a href="http://www.uscourts.gov/ttb/index.html">The Third Branch</a></B><ul>

What's going on behind the scenes of the federal judiciary?  Find out the latest on

electronic filing, judicial appointments, where the Judicial Committee spends its

budget and other issues the courts grapples with when they're not, well, holding

court.  This monthly newsletter comes from the Administrative Office of the U.S.

Courts.  With archived issues since February, 1995.</ul>

</P><BR>





<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of May 13:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.epa.gov/iaq">EPA's Indoor Air Home Page</a></b><ul>



Here's a breath of fresh air for environmental lawyers  and others. The EPA has put

together a roomfull of  publications, facts and info on radon, second-hand  smoke, lead,

organic gasses, carbon monoxide, pesticides, asbestos, formaldehyde, and other nasty

stuff.  With links  to EPA's main pages, and the Office of Air & Radiation. 

</ul>





</P><P> 





<P><b><a href="http://www.texlaw.com">TexLaw</a></b>

<ul>



The law of the Lone Star state rides onto the Web  in style with the launch of the website

from American  Lawyer Media's <I> Texas Lawyer</I>.  TexLaw features  top legal news, a

daily opinion bulletin covering all  Texas appellate courts, classifieds, links to state

resources, CLE calendar, and more.  Yippee! 



</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a



href="http://www.lochnet.com/client/smart/intranet.htm">The Complete Intranet Resource</a></B>

<ul>

What are Intranets?  Intranets are the corporate  world's answer to public websites. 

These sites are  firewalled, private, members only net clubs, and more  and more companies

are rolling them out for employees,  clients, and insiders.  Will Intranets overtake Internet 

sites as the primary use of Web servers? To open the  doors of the Intranet, visit this

page for articles, links, software FAQ's, discussions, case studies, Intranet events, more.

</ul>







</p><P>



<B> <a 

href="http://www.un.org/News/dh/latest.htm">UN Daily Highlights</a></B> 

<ul>

What happened at a recent African Conference on Consumer Protection?  What's the latest

spin from Mohammad Bualley,  chair of the Arab group?  From the Central News Section  of

the Department of Public Information, tune in to highlights of UN activity and

international public  affairs.  Updated every weekday.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a href="http://vmag.law.vill.edu:8080">Virtual Magistrate</a></B><ul>

Got a gripe in cyberville?  Harmed by wrongful e-posts? Take your complaint to the Virtual

Magistrate, an online forum for digital dispute resolution.  Brought to the Web by the

Cyberlaw Space Institute, the American Arbitration Association, the Villanova Center for

Information Law and Policy, and the National Center for Automated Information Research.



</ul>



</P><BR>





<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of May 6:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.tiac.net/users/agin/blawfind.html">The

Bankruptcy Lawfinder</a></b><ul>



From bankruptcy lawyer Warren Agin  &#45; of Boston's Barron & Stadfeld,

here is a compilation of pointers to bankruptcy sources and sites. 

Selections include bankruptcy legislation and rules, government

offices, and recent U.S. Supreme Court bankruptcy cases. Also, follow

the

link to the excellent Bankruptcy Creditors' Service Internet

Bankruptcy Library. Go belly-up on the Web.

</ul>





</P><P> 





<P><b><a href="http://stats.bls.gov/blshome.html">Bureau of Labor

Statistics</a></b><ul>



What are the latest figures on American

average hourly earnings?  How about

unemployment projections?  What does the "Economy at a Glance"

reveal? BLS is the number-crunching arm of the Department of Labor. 

Visit its site for labor economics stats, reports on productivity and

technology, regional news, publications and research projects.



</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a



href="http://www.intercall.com/~hamilton/psmlpn.html">Post-Soviet

Media Law & Policy Newsletter</a></B>

<ul>



Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law presents an archive of its

newsletter tracking media law and policy developments in the former

Soviet Union and East and Central Europe.  The latest issue includes

articles on Russian broadcasting, Hungarian media law, and the first

nationwide private T.V. channel in Central Europe.

</ul>







</p><P>



<B> <a 

href="http://www.moneypages.com/syndicate/index.html">The

Syndicate</a></B> 

<ul>

Finance buffs listen up.  Here's a goldmine of resources devoted to

everything in finance, featuring a meta-index of more than 1000

well-organized links to accountants and mortgages, banks, bonds,

brokers, investments, insurance, stocks, mutual funds, forecasts and

more.  With monthly featured articles.  Surf long and prosper.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a href="http://www.courttv.com/deleted/1638.html"><I>The New

Abortion Front</I></a></B><ul>

<I>Texas Lawyer </I> examines the latest tactic of the

anti-abortion group

 Life Dynamics, Inc. -- increasing the number of abortion-related

medical malpractice suits. 

 "Abortion malpractice is poised to become the most prolific

litigation 

  opportunity of a decade!" promises lawyer recruitment literature. On the

Court TV Law Center.



</ul>



</P>





<P><FONT SIZE="+2" color="000000"><LI><TT><B>Week of April 29:</B></TT></font> </P>



<P><b><a href="http://www.doe.gov">Department of

Energy</a></b><ul>



What's hot at energy?  Now that the Federal Energy Regulatory

Commission (FERC) has broken the monopoly held by utilities over 

distribution of wholesale power, zoom over to the Department of 

Energy's outpost to catch the DOE in action. Read fact sheets, news 

reports, speeches, testimony, and follow links to other Energy sites,

including FERC.

</ul>





</P><P> 





<b>Sexual Harassment and Mitsubishi</I></b><ul>

Gears are grinding at Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturing as the automaker

grapples with a sexual harassment lawsuit brought by the Equal Employment Opportunity

Commission - <B><a href="/spotlight/mitsu.html"><I>E.E.O.C. v.

Mitsubishi</I></a></B>, and a related class action - <B><a 

href="/spotlight/mitsu2.html"><I>Evans  v. Mitsubishi</I></a></B>.



</ul>



</P><P> 



<B><a href="http://www.unicef.org/sowc96/"><I>State of the World's

Children 1996</I></a></B>

<ul>



As the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) marks its 50th year,

its 16th annual report on the world's children appears on the Web for

the first time.   Children globally remain victimized by war, famine,

disease.  UNICEF highlights facts and stats, and spotlights children

in regions from Sub-Sahara Africa to the industrialized countries.

With a forward by UNICEF executive director Carol Bellamy.

</ul>







</p><P>



<B> <a



href="http://www.droit.umontreal.ca/Droit/CSC/SCC.html">Supreme Court

of Canada</a></B> 

<ul>

A cooperative project by the Supreme Court of Canada and the Centre 

de Recherche en Droit Public at the University of Montreal brings to 

the Web recent Canadian Supreme Court rulings (1993 to present).  

Search for opinions in French and English. Catch up on issues of 

Supreme Court Bulletins. And check out a brief history of the Court 

and short bios of the nine justices.

</ul>



</p><P>



<B> <a href="http://www.courttv.com/teens/">Teen Court TV</a></B><ul>

Is it cooler than Court TV?  You decide.  As Court TV launches its  specialized souped-up

programming block for kids, the Court TV Law  Center rolls out the Teen Court TV homepage. 

Featuring Talk Back! discussion groups, quizzes, survey, interviews, "You Be the  Judge" contests

and lots of hot legal information.  This may even be cooler than Court TV. For kids and lawyers who

have them.

</ul>



</P>





</P>      

</UL>  

