<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>

Counsel Quote's Hot Topics</TITLE>



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  LINK="#000080"  VLINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="paper.gif">



<IMG SRC="/counselquote/hotdocsheader.gif" ALIGN=TOP>



<HR>



<center>

<A HREF="/images/cquotenavbar.map">

<IMG BORDER=0

SRC="/counselquote/cquotenavbar.gif" ISMAP>

</A>

</center>



<HR>

<blockquote>

<H2>

<font color=ff0000>

Aloha to Gay Marriage?</font>

</H2>





<P>

<FONT SIZE="+2">

F</Font>

ollowing a Hawaii trial judge's decision allowing same-sex marriages in Baehr v. Miike, Counsel Connect held an instant seminar to discuss the decision's implications. In the following discussion, panelists discuss the possibility of amending the Constitution to define marriage as a union between one man and one woman. This conversation is reprinted with the respondents' permission.</P>



<P>

<HR>

<P>

Originally posted by: Rick Duncan -- U. of Nebraska Law School - Hickman, NE 402-472-6044

<BR><A href=mailto:rdunca01@counsel.com>rdunca01@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Mon Dec 9 16:17:07 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>A number of people have begun to float an idea that may take hold -- the idea is an amendment to the U.S. Constitution to define marriage as a relationship between one man and one woman. I haven't seen any draft yet, but it might go something like this:</P>



<P>"Marriage is a relationship between one man and one woman. Neither the United States government nor any state or local government shall recognize any other relationship as a marriage or as equivalent to marriage."</P>



<P>In light of the national consensus in support of conventional marriage, this is exactly one of those rare cases in which a constitutional amendment is justified. An activist court in one small state is threatening to throw a monkey wrench into our collective understanding of marriage. A constitutional amendment would trump the Hawaii courts and also instruct the U.S. Supreme Court that the will of the people about the meaning of marriage should prevail. Any thoughts? </P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Cary Cheifetz -- Skoloff & Wolfe, PC - Livingston, NJ 201-992-0900

<BR><A href=mailto:ccheifet@counsel.com>ccheifet@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Mon Dec 9 17:26:36 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>Haven't we learned from the failure of Prohibition that the Constitution should not be used as a document to legislate social behavior? I cannot fathom that the federal government's interest in marriage is so strong that it arises to the level of the need for a constitutional amendment and I would fear the consequences of what other social issues might find their way into the Constitution. Abortion? Divorce? Child birth limits on the poor?</P>



<P>Each unpopular cause is fair game.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Michael Masinter -- Nova University - Miami, FL 954-452-6151

<BR><A href=mailto:masinter@counsel.com>masinter@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Mon Dec 9 17:44:08 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>I think a constitutional amendment, though clearly the constitutionally proper response to Hawaii's choice to be different, is wrong. I attach no significance to how Hawaii reached its decision; if its people think their court has misconstrued their constitution, their remedy is to amend their constitution. But I see no reason why the rest of us should amend ours. The future of the republic does not turn on whether Hawaii extends legal recognition to same-sex marriages. I would leave it to the good people of Hawaii to govern themselves.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Arthur S Leonard -- New York Law School - New York, NY

<BR><A href=mailto:aleonard@counsel.com>aleonard@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Mon Dec 9 18:22:36 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>A constitutional amendment defining marriage may not be necessary. Federal statutes supersede state constitutions under the Supremacy Clause. Presumably a federal statute defining marriage would override any decision in Hawaii, unless it were successfully argued that Congress does not have authority to legislate on the subject. (And, if Congress lacks authority to legislate on the subject, then the Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) may well be unconstitutional on that ground -- at least the part of DOMA which purports to relieve the federal government from recognizing lawfully contracted same-sex marriages.)</P>



<P>The thing that's interesting about a constitutional amendment, as proposed by Prof. Duncan, is that this is a process that is much easier to stop than legislation. An amendment requires super-majorities from both houses of Congress, followed by ratification in 3/4 of the states. As the battles played out in state legislatures over the past year have indicated, this is not necessarily an issue where ratification would sweep through the states. And since this is a time-consuming process, it is possible that with same-sex marriage becoming a reality in Hawaii, people will notice that the sky is not falling in and that, in fact, the number of same-sex couples who marry in Hawaii will not be extraordinary. (Look at the experience with domestic partnership registration -- even in places where the registration carries substantial benefits, the number registering is actually rather small compared to the eligible population.) So, it is possible that a constitutional amendment, even if it gets the required super-majorities in Congress, could well stall in the states, as the Equal Rights Amendment stalled back in the 1970s.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Thomas E. Baker -- Texas Tech Law - Lubbock, TX 806-742-3793

<BR><A href=mailto:tbaker02@counsel.com>tbaker02@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 09:26:20 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>I think we are stuck with federalism. This from an 18th-century mind like mine. If one state wants to go its way as a "laboratory" then it should. But of course, the state legislature and the people of Hawaii can trump the state Supreme Court.</P>



<P>Maybe the problem is having a written constitution with judicial review. While I would not lightly give up the U.S. Constitution, I would be willing to completely rewrite my own state constitution -- Texas has a doozy. If the new federalism plays out like Justice Brennan hoped, with fifty state Warren courts, maybe some laboratory will pull the plug on the experiment and take steps to downsize state court judicial review of the state constitution. . . . </P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Bruce McAllister -- Steel Hector - Miami, FL 305-577-7075

<BR><A href=mailto:bmcallis@counsel.com>bmcallis@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 11:00:15 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>Domestic Partner Registration, with which I am not familiar, may be the answer to the following:</P>



<P>1. If a legislature (federal or state) will not conduct an inquiry into how best to recognize (among other measures, give legal protection to) gay relationships, perhaps the courts must;</P>



<P>2. Why aren't we looking for a "third way" to provide gay persons with what they need and are entitled to by way of legal recognition? I don't care who is deemed to have the burden of proof on this issue -- that is, is according gay couples the full panoply of traditional marital rights and responsibilities the only way to accord them equal treatment? -- but some institution should initiate the inquiry.</P>



<P>I feel intuitively that recognizing gay marriages will, in the end, prove to be the right thing to do, but we are dealing here not only with perhaps the most powerful and numinous forces in the history of mankind, but also with an incredibly complicated network of legal, social and religious relationships which no one, to my knowledge, has thought through in light of Hawaii's initiative. To respond to this issue with a locked-in, either/or response seems to me to be very superficial.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Michael Masinter -- Nova University - Miami, FL 954-452-6151

<BR><A href=mailto:masinter@counsel.com>masinter@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 11:24:23 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>I want to reply to Prof. Leonard's suggestion that Congress has legislative power here. How could Congress constitutionally forbid a state from establishing same-sex marriages? What is the source of its power to legislate? Surely not the Commerce Clause. And whatever the narrow grant of authority in the Full Faith and Credit Clause (FFCC) means, it cannot mean that Congress has the power to intrude into Hawaii's decision to allow same-sex marriages. I do not even think the FFCC gives Congress the power to relieve other states from whatever the FFCC obligates them to do, though I am far from sure that the FFCC requires interstate recognition. But setting aside full faith and credit issues, how could Congress possibly have the legislative power to forbid Hawaii from providing for same-sex marriages?</P>



<P>That said, why must Congress defer to Hawaii in establishing what constitutes a marriage for purposes of federal benefit programs? Here congressional spending power would seem plenary, limited only by guarantees of individual rights. It seems plausible to me that Congress is powerless to interfere with Hawaii's expected decision to allow same-sex marriages, but that Congress is not obligated to recognize same-sex marriages in providing benefits under, say, the Social Security Act unless the denial of benefits can be shown to be a denial of equal protection.</P>



<P>Am I missing something?</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Rick Duncan -- U. of Nebraska Law School - Hickman, NE 402-472-6044

<BR><A href=mailto:rdunca01@counsel.com>rdunca01@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 13:26:36 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending Constitution</P>



<P>Cary Cheifetz argues that the federal government's interest in marriage is not sufficiently strong to justify a constitutional amendment to define marriage as a relationship between one man and one woman. Similarly, Prof. Masinter argues that:</P>



<P>"The future of the republic does not turn on whether Hawaii extends legal recognition to same-sex marriages. I would leave it to the good people of Hawaii to govern themselves."</P>



<P>It warms my heart to hear so much concern for state's rights and federalism expressed in a public forum. I, too, am a strong supporter of the right of the people in the several states to decide most issues. And indeed, the people of Hawaii have clearly expressed their will that marriage be defined as a relationship between one man and one woman. But the will of the people has been overridden by an activist court, and because our society is mobile, that court's decision threatens to affect not just the good people of Hawaii but also the good people of Massachusetts, Nebraska, Utah, New York and the rest of the country.</P>



<P>We have a very broad national consensus on the meaning of marriage, the most basic unit in society. This is exactly the situation that justifies an amendment to the U.S. Constitution, an amendment designed to preserve a national consensus on an issue of fundamental importance. This is not a case of the national government depriving the people the right to make their own laws. It is, instead, an act of the People reasserting their right to rule.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Arthur S Leonard -- New York Law School - New York, NY

<BR><A href=mailto:aleonard@counsel.com>aleonard@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 14:46:42 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>I'm curious about the source of authority for the statement that there is a consensus against same-sex marriage in society. Although no public opinion poll has yet shown a majority of the general population supporting the idea of same-sex marriage, the numbers have been shifting over the past few years as the debate has proceeded. A substantial minority, perhaps more than a third of the general population of the country, is now receptive to the idea of same-sex marriage. When one breaks down these polls by age groups, it turns out that young adults support same-sex marriage by a fair margin, the middle aged are skeptical, and the older part of the population is opposed.</P>



<P>It is also worth noting that the population was overwhelming opposed to interracial marriage at the time the Supreme Court struck down the Virginia miscegenation law in the 1960s.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Rick Eichor -- Attorney General's Office - Honolulu, HI 808-586-1180

<BR><A href=mailto:reichorn@counsel.com>reichorn@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 15:06:49 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the U.S. Constitution</P>



<P>In reply to Prof. Leonard's question about the source of numbers on opposition to same-sex marriage, the Hawaii polls taken in March of 1996 and repeated in July or August of 1996 were consistent in showing about 70 percent opposed to it, also national polls in <I>Time</I> (or <I>Newsweek</I>) showed similar results. These polls have not varied in any statistically significant manner for several years. As for the public opinion polls at the time of <I>Loving</I>, the U.S. Supreme Court was quick to point out that only sixteen (as I recall) states had laws on interracial marriage, it was legal and practiced in the vast majority of the states. Thus, the public policy followed by the legislatures in the majority of the states could be considered at least tacitly, if not expressly, to approve of interracial marriages. That is not the case with same-sex marriage. If this were left to the policy making legislative branches, I suspect the debate would be much different.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: James Trowbridge -- Quinnipiac College - Hamden, CT 203-287-3233

<BR><A href=mailto:jtrowb00@counsel.com>jtrowb00@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 19:25:38 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending the US Constitution</P>



<P>Why not deal with the constitutions and "activist" supreme courts of "small states" by providing that small states may not provide state residents with rights not protected by the U.S. Constitution? This will protect the republic from the crazy notions that regularly come out of Maine, Vermont, Delaware, New Mexico, and Hawaii. Somewhere along the line, some persons who support traditional values have rejected the historic rights of the peoples of the states to form their own constitutions.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: David Butler -- Alpert & Raice - West Orange, NJ 201-325-1188

<BR><A href=mailto:dbutler0@counsel.com>dbutler0@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Tue Dec 10 19:51:06 1996

<BR>Subject: Let's not prostitute</P>



<P>Let's not prostitute the Constitution to salve the psyches of the homophobic. While I am troubled with the idea of affording homosexual marriages the same legal status as heterosexual marriages (What's the social benefit? What's the harm in not doing it? Gays can still have marriage ceremonies, and make vows of commitment, even without the king's blessing, and can also engage in estate planning to protect their mates), I don't think the federal government has any reason to get involved in such a "family" issue. In fact, I think this issue has even less to do with the federal government than does the "anti-flag burner" amendment which was promoted a few years back -- at least that had to do with a symbol of the federal government. I'm also trying to understand how I, a New Jersey resident, have been adversely affected by the Hawaii Court's decision -- even though I disagree with it, I'm content to let the Hawaii court decide the issue as it sees fit.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: James M Beck -- Pepper, Hamilton - Philadelphia, PA 215-981-4000

<BR><A href=mailto:jbeck000@counsel.com>jbeck000@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Wed Dec 11 08:04:33 1996

<BR>Subject: A Modest Proposal</P>



<P>Who needs a constitutional amendment? Let's simply recognize as true what the religious opponents of same-sex marriage strenuously argue -- that marriage is a religious institution from top to bottom and it is incompatible with sexual practices and preferences that many of the faithful regard as an abomination. What then?</P>



<P>Under the establishment clause, no governmental benefit or penalty may be conferred as a result of marriage or the lack thereof. No pensions, no property rights, no divorce laws, no nuthin'. We then go to a civil system similar to what is used in Europe where anyone, gay, straight or in-between, can sign a contract to live with one another for life and assume all of the legal obligations and benefits that are now associated with marriage.</P>



<P>The various religions are able to keep and defend the spiritual aspects of the institution of marriage and cannot have their religious values transgressed by the government, be it courts or legislatures, and on the other hand everyone stands equal before the law.</P>



<P>

<HR noshade>

</P>



<P>Appended by: Arthur S Leonard -- New York Law School - New York, NY

<BR><A href=mailto:aleonard@counsel.com>aleonard@counsel.com</a>

<BR>Date: Thu Dec 12 11:04:37 1996

<BR>Subject: Amending Constitution</P>



<P>Another thread has begun to develop the significance of government involvement in defining marriage. To summarize very concisely, a careful study of the U.S. Code and the legal codes of states and cities would show hundreds upon hundreds of provisions in which marital status or relationships are relevant to determining legal status, entitlement for benefits, legal obligations, etc. Many of them might only apply to a small portion of the population at any particular time, but taken all together, they create a pervasive significant for governmental recognition of relationships that make this about much more than estate planning or taxes. Try telling the small but significant number of international couples that the federal definition of marriage for immigration and citizenship purposes is not important (and this is not one that private parties can contract around). Try telling the dependent survivor in a long-term, same-sex relationship akin to marriage that the definition of marriage for purposes of Social Security survivor benefits is not significant. (On the purely mundane, everyday level, try telling the couple who are denied access to "married-student housing" at a university because the state doesn't license same-sex marriages that this is not significant. I'm aware of a situation brewing here in New York City at a major medical school where the denial of access to married-student housing for same-sex couples is becoming a major issue -- especially because of the extraordinary housing costs in the NYC metropolitan area.) There are significant equity issues involved almost everywhere you look.</P>



</DOC>
