<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Counsel Quote -  Story Ideas</TITLE>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="paper.gif">
<p align=center><img src="/counselquote/storyheader.gif" width=600 height=100 alt="COUNSEL CANVAS">
<HR>
<center><A HREF="/images/cquotenavbar.map"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/counselquote/cquotenavbar.gif" ISMAP></A></center>
<HR><BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Most of the Counsel Quote Web site is devoted to helping journalists
contact lawyers for expert information about legal issues. But why not have
the inquiries flow both ways?</P>

<P>Counsel Connect members occasionally raise issues they think deserve more
media attention, and this section is designed to help these members
interact with the media in ways that challenge reporters to cover the
justice system and the profession in new way.</P></B>



<H2><font color=ff0000>1. Judicial Administration</font></H2>

<P>From: Martin L. Haines<BR>
Judge, Retired<BR>
Moorestown, New Jersey<BR>
E-Mail: <a href="mailto:mhainesn@counsel.com">mhainesn@counsel.com</a><BR>
Phone: 1-609-235-3813</P>

<P>I have an interest in judicial administration - in how the courts operate
internally.  One major problem: Getting the press interested in the
subject. The reason for non-interest: It is very difficult for the press to
get inside information. Much is secret and court managers are not
communicative for many reasons.</P>

<P>   This would start as a reversal of your present approach, which requires
the press to initiate inquiries. It would require some initial challenges
to the press, ones that, hopefully, would attract inquiries, after which
exchanges would take place.</P>

<P>It is my view that the administrative side of the courts -- much ignored --
is arguably more important than the judicial side, if you set aside the
societal effect of judicial decisions. After all, judges, acting
judicially, only hear and decide, while court managers (which include
judges acting as managers) invent the rules (including ones that discipline
lawyers and judges), raise the monies with which to run the courts, assign
judges, assign cases and decide when and where they will be heard, hire and
fire and assign personnel, etc., etc., etc.</P>
<P><I>More ideas coming soon!</I></P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
